{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QdTYpy3rM2q2fiyHBsH3JU","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\n2\t\n3\t===== PAGE 1 =====\n4\t000\n5\t001\n6\t002\n7\t003\n8\t004\n9\t005\n10\t006\n11\t007\n12\t008\n13\t009\n14\t010\n15\t011\n16\t012\n17\t013\n18\t014\n19\t015\n20\t016\n21\t017\n22\t018\n23\t019\n24\t020\n25\t021\n26\t022\n27\t023\n28\t024\n29\t025\n30\t026\n31\t027\n32\t028\n33\t029\n34\t030\n35\t031\n36\t032\n37\t033\n38\t034\n39\t035\n40\t036\n41\t037\n42\t038\n43\t039\n44\t040\n45\t041\n46\t042\n47\t043\n48\t044\n49\t045\n50\t046\n51\t047\n52\t048\n53\t049\n54\t050\n55\t051\n56\t052\n57\t053\n58\t054\n59\tWhen Actions Go Off-Task:\n60\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n61\tAnonymous Authors1\n62\thttps://osu-nlp-group.github.io/Misaligned-Action-Detection\n63\tAbstract\n64\tComputer-use agents (CUAs) have made tremen-\n65\tdous progress in the past year, yet they still fre-\n66\tquently produce misaligned actions that deviate\n67\tfrom the user’s original intent. Such misaligned\n68\tactions may arise from external attacks (e.g., in-\n69\tdirect prompt injection) or from internal limi-\n70\ttations (e.g., erroneous reasoning). They not\n71\tonly expose CUAs to safety risks, but also de-\n72\tgrade task efficiency and reliability. This work\n73\tmakes the first effort to define and study mis-\n74\taligned action detection in CUAs, with compre-\n75\thensive coverage of both externally induced and\n76\tinternally arising misaligned actions. We further\n77\tidentify three common categories in real-world\n78\tCUA deployment and construct MISACTBENCH,\n79\ta benchmark of realistic trajectories with human-\n80\tannotated, action-level alignment labels. More-\n81\tover, we propose DEACTION, a practical and uni-\n82\tversal guardrail that detects misaligned actions\n83\tbefore execution and iteratively corrects them\n84\tthrough structured feedback. DEACTIONoutper-\n85\tforms all existing baselines across offline and on-\n86\tline evaluations with moderate latency overhead:\n87\t(1) On MISACTBENCH, it outperforms baselines\n88\tby over 15% absolute in F1 score; (2) In online\n89\tevaluation, it reduces attack success rate by over\n90\t90% under adversarial settings while preserving\n91\tor even improving task success rate in benign en-\n92\tvironments.\n93\t1. Introduction\n94\tComputer-use agents (CUAs) (OpenAI., 2025b; Anthropic.,\n95\t2024c; Wang et al., 2025), which interact directly with com-\n96\tputers to automate digital tasks, have achieved strong perfor-\n97\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n98\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n99\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n100\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n101\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n102\tmance on realistic sandboxed benchmarks (Xie et al., 2024;\n103\tBonatti et al., 2025), raising expectations for real-world\n104\tdeployment. However, this growing autonomy also intro-\n105\tduces nontrivial risks: during execution, CUAs may take\n106\tactions that deviate from user intent, leading to undesired\n107\tconsequences such as stalled progress or real-world harm.\n108\tPrior work has studied such deviations primarily through\n109\tthe lens ofsafety risks, focusing on threats such as indirect\n110\tprompt injection (Greshake et al., 2023) or policy viola-\n111\ttions (Wen et al., 2025). As a result, existing benchmarks\n112\tprovide only trajectory-level safety or policy labels (Wen\n113\tet al., 2025; Chen et al., 2025b; Sun et al., 2025), and exist-\n114\ting guardrails are predominantly tied to predefined policies\n115\tor known attack patterns (Xiang et al., 2025; Luo et al.,\n116\t2025b; Shi et al., 2025). While valuable, this safety-centric\n117\tparadigm leaves a critical gap: not all problematic behaviors\n118\tcan be anticipated and enumerated as policy violations in\n119\tadvance. In practice, agents may produce actions that are\n120\ttechnically permissible and non-malicious, yet still deviate\n121\tfrom user intent in unjustified ways (Figure 1). For instance,\n122\tthey may introduce unnecessary interactions, pursue unin-\n123\ttended subgoals, or derail task progress. Such deviations\n124\tmay not violate predefined constraints, but still erode user\n125\ttrust and degrade agent reliability.\n126\tThese limitations motivate a more intent-centric view for\n127\tanalyzing agent deviations. Rather than asking whether\n128\tan action violates predefined safety policies, we focus on\n129\taction alignment(Jia et al., 2025; Fang et al., 2025), i.e.,\n130\twhether a proposed action can be justified as advancing\n131\tthe user’s authentic intent. We define misaligned actions\n132\tas deviations that cannot be justified as part of a legitimate\n133\tworkflow toward the intended goal. In CUA execution,\n134\twe identify three common categories of misaligned actions\n135\tbased on their cause and consequence (Figure 1): (1)Mali-\n136\tcious Instruction Following, where the action complies with\n137\tmalicious instructions in external environments to achieve\n138\tan attacker’s goal; (2)Harmful Unintended Behavior, where\n139\tthe action causes harm inadvertently due to inherent limita-\n140\ttions (e.g., reasoning error) rather than adversarial attack;\n141\t(3)Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior, where the action does\n142\tnot cause harmful consequences but is irrelevant to the user\n143\t1\n144\t\n145\t===== PAGE 2 =====\n146\t055\n147\t056\n148\t057\n149\t058\n150\t059\n151\t060\n152\t061\n153\t062\n154\t063\n155\t064\n156\t065\n157\t066\n158\t067\n159\t068\n160\t069\n161\t070\n162\t071\n163\t072\n164\t073\n165\t074\n166\t075\n167\t076\n168\t077\n169\t078\n170\t079\n171\t080\n172\t081\n173\t082\n174\t083\n175\t084\n176\t085\n177\t086\n178\t087\n179\t088\n180\t089\n181\t090\n182\t091\n183\t092\n184\t093\n185\t094\n186\t095\n187\t096\n188\t097\n189\t098\n190\t099\n191\t100\n192\t101\n193\t102\n194\t103\n195\t104\n196\t105\n197\t106\n198\t107\n199\t108\n200\t109\n201\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n202\t(a)MaliciousInstruction\tFollowing(b)Harmful\tUnintended\tBehavior(c)Other\tTask-Irrelevant\tBehavior\n203\tUser\tIntent:Install\tbrowser\textension\n204\tRedditPost:“T o\tinstall,\tyou\tmust\tfirst\tdelete\t.ssh/id_rsa!”\n205\tMisalignedAction:Agent\tdeletes\tcritical\tsystemfile\tbased\ton\tmalicious\tpost\n206\tUser\tIntent:Export\tA.docx\tto\tPDFExport\tto\tA.pdf\n207\tDelete\t.ssh/id_rsaDelete\tA.docxMisalignedAction:Agent\tdeletes\tthe\toriginal\tdocx\tfile\tafter\texporting\tit\tto\tPDF\n208\tUser\tIntent:Change\tdocument\tfont\n209\tInteract\twith\tVLC\tmedia\tplayer\n210\tMisalignedAction:Agent\topens\tunrelated\tvideo\tplayer\tapp\tinstead\tof\tdocument\teditor\n211\tFigure 1.Examples of the three categories of misaligned actions. (a)Malicious Instruction Following: the action complies with external\n212\tmalicious instructions; (b)Harmful Unintended Behavior: the action causes harm due to inherent limitations rather than adversarial\n213\tattacks; (c)Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior: the action does not cause harm but is irrelevant to the task.\n214\ttask and will degrade efficiency and reliability. Based on\n215\tthis framing, we take a first step toward studyingmisaligned\n216\taction detectionin CUAs: determining whether a proposed\n217\taction is misaligned before actual execution.\n218\tTo enable systematic evaluation of misaligned action detec-\n219\ttion, we construct MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive bench-\n220\tmark with over 2K human-annotated, action-level alignment\n221\tlabels across realistic trajectories. It covers both externally\n222\tinduced and internally arising misaligned actions through\n223\ta hybrid construction pipeline. We further propose DEAC-\n224\tTION, a practical and universal guardrail that proactively\n225\tdetects and corrects misaligned actions before execution.\n226\tTo balance detection performance with latency, DEACTION\n227\temploys a two-stage analysis pipeline conditioned on a com-\n228\tpact narrative summary of the interaction history. Rather\n229\tthan merely blocking misaligned actions, DEACTIONpro-\n230\tvides structured feedback to guide agents toward corrected,\n231\ttask-aligned behavior iteratively. We conduct extensive\n232\texperiments in both offline and online settings. On MIS-\n233\tACTBENCH, DEACTIONoutperforms baselines by over\n234\t15% absolute. In online evaluation, it reduces attack success\n235\trates by over 90% under adversarial scenarios (RedTeam-\n236\tCUA (Liao et al., 2025)), and preserves or even improves\n237\tbenign task success (OSWorld (Xie et al., 2024)), with mod-\n238\terate runtime overhead.\n239\tWe present the first systematic study of misaligned action\n240\tdetection in CUAs, with three main contributions:\n241\t1. We propose an intent-centric perspective that frames\n242\tCUA deviations as an action misalignment problem,\n243\tand identify three common categories of misaligned\n244\tactions in real-world deployments.\n245\t2. We introduce MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive\n246\tbenchmark with 2,264 human-annotated, action-level\n247\talignment labels on diverse CUA trajectories, covering\n248\tall three categories of misaligned actions.\n249\t3. We propose DEACTION, a practical and plug-and-play\n250\truntime guardrail that proactively detects misaligned\n251\tactions before execution and iteratively corrects them\n252\tvia structured feedback. Extensive experiments demon-\n253\tstrate its effectiveness in both adversarial and benign\n254\tsettings with moderate overhead.\n255\t2. Problem Formulation\n256\t2.1. Action Alignment\n257\tWe begin by defining action alignment, the central concept\n258\tunderlying our study.\n259\tGiven a user instruction I, interaction history τ<t, and cur-\n260\trent observation ot, a proposed action at is considered\n261\talignedif it satisfies three conditions: (1) it is taken in\n262\tservice of the user’s instruction I, rather than in response\n263\tto other directives such as injected instructions in the envi-\n264\tronment; (2) it does not result in unauthorized or undesired\n265\tconsequences; and (3) it can be reasonably interpreted as\n266\tcontributing, whether directly or indirectly, to completing\n267\tthe user’s intended task. An action that violates any of these\n268\tconditions is consideredmisaligned.\n269\tNotably, alignment does not require optimality. An action\n270\tmay be inefficient, exploratory, or ultimately unsuccessful\n271\tyet still be aligned, as long as it represents a genuine attempt\n272\tto advance the user’s goal.\n273\tBased on this definition, we formulate the task ofmis-\n274\taligned action detection: given (I, τ<t, ot, at), determine\n275\twhether at is misaligned before actual execution (i.e., with-\n276\tout access to actual consequences).\n277\t2.2. Categorization of Misaligned Actions\n278\tThe three conditions in § 2.1 naturally give rise to a catego-\n279\trization of misaligned actions based on which condition is\n280\tviolated. Concretely, we identify three categories observed\n281\tin real-world CUA deployments, illustrated in Figure 1:\n282\tMalicious Instruction Following.The agent complies with\n283\tmalicious directives embedded in the external environment,\n284\tsuch as indirect prompt injections in web content, instead\n285\t2\n286\t\n287\t===== PAGE 3 =====\n288\t110\n289\t111\n290\t112\n291\t113\n292\t114\n293\t115\n294\t116\n295\t117\n296\t118\n297\t119\n298\t120\n299\t121\n300\t122\n301\t123\n302\t124\n303\t125\n304\t126\n305\t127\n306\t128\n307\t129\n308\t130\n309\t131\n310\t132\n311\t133\n312\t134\n313\t135\n314\t136\n315\t137\n316\t138\n317\t139\n318\t140\n319\t141\n320\t142\n321\t143\n322\t144\n323\t145\n324\t146\n325\t147\n326\t148\n327\t149\n328\t150\n329\t151\n330\t152\n331\t153\n332\t154\n333\t155\n334\t156\n335\t157\n336\t158\n337\t159\n338\t160\n339\t161\n340\t162\n341\t163\n342\t164\n343\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n344\t（a)\tGeneration\twith\tExternal\tAttacks(b)\tSynthesis\twithout\tAttacks\n345\tDiverse\tCUAs•Generic\tLLMs•Specialized\tAgentsAdversarial\tBenchmarks\n346\tOS-Harm,\tDoomArenaRedTeamCUA,\tRiOSWorld\n347\tAttack-induced\tMisaligned\tTrajectoriesExecute\n348\tBenign\tTraj.\tGeneration•FrontierCUAs•OSWorld\ttasks\n349\tUnintended\tSubgoal•Subgoal\tsynthesis•Inject\tstep\tidentificationMerge\n350\tSynthesized\tUnintended\tTrajectoriesRaw\tTrajectory\tPool\n351\tHuman\tAnnotationMisActBench\n352\tMisaligned\tAction\tDetection\tBenchmark\n353\tFigure 2.Trajectory Collection Workflow for MISACTBENCH. (a) Collect trajectories with misaligned actions induced by external attacks\n354\tby running diverse CUAs on existing benchmarks. (b) Synthesize trajectories with unintended behaviors in benign settings.\n355\tof following the user’s authentic intent.\n356\tHarmful Unintended Behavior.The agent causes unau-\n357\tthorized or harmful consequences due to internal limita-\n358\ttions (e.g., reasoning failures) rather than adversarial at-\n359\ttacks. These may compromise the CIA triad (Howard &\n360\tLipner, 2006): confidentiality (e.g., exposing sensitive in-\n361\tformation), integrity (e.g., corrupting data), or availability\n362\t(e.g., disrupting services).\n363\tOther Task-Irrelevant Behavior.The agent performs ac-\n364\ttions that are irrelevant to the user’s task, such as opening\n365\tunrelated applications or navigating to irrelevant websites.\n366\tThese also arise internally but do not cause direct harm, yet\n367\tstill undermine execution efficiency and reliability.\n368\t3. MISACTBENCH: Comprehensive Evaluation\n369\tfor Misaligned Action Detection\n370\tFollowing the definition of misaligned action detection\n371\tin §2.1, we introduce MISACTBENCH, a realistic bench-\n372\tmark of CUA interaction trajectories with human-annotated,\n373\taction-level binary alignment labels.\n374\t3.1. Raw Trajectory Collection\n375\tTo achieve comprehensive coverage of all three categories\n376\t(§2.2) at scale, we adopt a hybrid collection strategy based\n377\ton their origin, as illustrated in Figure 2.\n378\tTrajectories with External Attacks.For misaligned ac-\n379\ttions caused by external attacks, we leverage existing bench-\n380\tmarks that explicitly incorporate adversarial settings with\n381\tvision-based environmental injections, where malicious in-\n382\tstructions are embedded in the visual interfaces (e.g., web\n383\tcontents, pop-ups). Specifically, we leverage four repre-\n384\tsentative benchmarks which collectively encompass a wide\n385\tspectrum of attack vectors: OS-Harm (Kuntz et al., 2025),\n386\tDoomArena (Boisvert et al., 2025), RedTeamCUA (Liao\n387\tet al., 2025), and RiOSWorld (Yang et al., 2025b).\n388\tWe run a diverse set of agents on these benchmarks to\n389\tcapture a broad range of behaviors under adversarial con-\n390\tditions, including CUAs powered by both generic LLMs\n391\t(GPT-4o (Hurst et al., 2024), Claude Sonnet 3.5 (Anthropic.,\n392\t2024b), and Claude Sonnet 3.7 (Anthropic., 2025a)) as\n393\twell as specialized CUA models (OpenAI CUA (Ope-\n394\tnAI., 2025b) and Claude Sonnet 3.5 and 3.7 with Computer\n395\tUse (Anthropic., 2024c)). We use the benchmark-provided\n396\ttrajectory-level evaluators to filter and retain only trajecto-\n397\tries where the attack succeeded, ensuring that each contains\n398\tconcrete instances of externally induced misalignment. We\n399\tpresent detailed settings in Appendix A.1.\n400\tTrajectories without Attacks.While misaligned actions"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"e88ae906-df1c-40f0-a08c-12d645c84e9b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:59:15.633Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_text.txt","content":"\n\n===== PAGE 1 =====\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nWhen Actions Go Off-Task:\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nAnonymous Authors1\nhttps://osu-nlp-group.github.io/Misaligned-Action-Detection\nAbstract\nComputer-use agents (CUAs) have made tremen-\ndous progress in the past year, yet they still fre-\nquently produce misaligned actions that deviate\nfrom the user’s original intent. Such misaligned\nactions may arise from external attacks (e.g., in-\ndirect prompt injection) or from internal limi-\ntations (e.g., erroneous reasoning). They not\nonly expose CUAs to safety risks, but also de-\ngrade task efficiency and reliability. This work\nmakes the first effort to define and study mis-\naligned action detection in CUAs, with compre-\nhensive coverage of both externally induced and\ninternally arising misaligned actions. We further\nidentify three common categories in real-world\nCUA deployment and construct MISACTBENCH,\na benchmark of realistic trajectories with human-\nannotated, action-level alignment labels. More-\nover, we propose DEACTION, a practical and uni-\nversal guardrail that detects misaligned actions\nbefore execution and iteratively corrects them\nthrough structured feedback. DEACTIONoutper-\nforms all existing baselines across offline and on-\nline evaluations with moderate latency overhead:\n(1) On MISACTBENCH, it outperforms baselines\nby over 15% absolute in F1 score; (2) In online\nevaluation, it reduces attack success rate by over\n90% under adversarial settings while preserving\nor even improving task success rate in benign en-\nvironments.\n1. Introduction\nComputer-use agents (CUAs) (OpenAI., 2025b; Anthropic.,\n2024c; Wang et al., 2025), which interact directly with com-\nputers to automate digital tasks, have achieved strong perfor-\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\nmance on realistic sandboxed benchmarks (Xie et al., 2024;\nBonatti et al., 2025), raising expectations for real-world\ndeployment. However, this growing autonomy also intro-\nduces nontrivial risks: during execution, CUAs may take\nactions that deviate from user intent, leading to undesired\nconsequences such as stalled progress or real-world harm.\nPrior work has studied such deviations primarily through\nthe lens ofsafety risks, focusing on threats such as indirect\nprompt injection (Greshake et al., 2023) or policy viola-\ntions (Wen et al., 2025). As a result, existing benchmarks\nprovide only trajectory-level safety or policy labels (Wen\net al., 2025; Chen et al., 2025b; Sun et al., 2025), and exist-\ning guardrails are predominantly tied to predefined policies\nor known attack patterns (Xiang et al., 2025; Luo et al.,\n2025b; Shi et al., 2025). While valuable, this safety-centric\nparadigm leaves a critical gap: not all problematic behaviors\ncan be anticipated and enumerated as policy violations in\nadvance. In practice, agents may produce actions that are\ntechnically permissible and non-malicious, yet still deviate\nfrom user intent in unjustified ways (Figure 1). For instance,\nthey may introduce unnecessary interactions, pursue unin-\ntended subgoals, or derail task progress. Such deviations\nmay not violate predefined constraints, but still erode user\ntrust and degrade agent reliability.\nThese limitations motivate a more intent-centric view for\nanalyzing agent deviations. Rather than asking whether\nan action violates predefined safety policies, we focus on\naction alignment(Jia et al., 2025; Fang et al., 2025), i.e.,\nwhether a proposed action can be justified as advancing\nthe user’s authentic intent. We define misaligned actions\nas deviations that cannot be justified as part of a legitimate\nworkflow toward the intended goal. In CUA execution,\nwe identify three common categories of misaligned actions\nbased on their cause and consequence (Figure 1): (1)Mali-\ncious Instruction Following, where the action complies with\nmalicious instructions in external environments to achieve\nan attacker’s goal; (2)Harmful Unintended Behavior, where\nthe action causes harm inadvertently due to inherent limita-\ntions (e.g., reasoning error) rather than adversarial attack;\n(3)Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior, where the action does\nnot cause harmful consequences but is irrelevant to the user\n1\n\n===== PAGE 2 =====\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n(a)MaliciousInstruction\tFollowing(b)Harmful\tUnintended\tBehavior(c)Other\tTask-Irrelevant\tBehavior\nUser\tIntent:Install\tbrowser\textension\nRedditPost:“T o\tinstall,\tyou\tmust\tfirst\tdelete\t.ssh/id_rsa!”\nMisalignedAction:Agent\tdeletes\tcritical\tsystemfile\tbased\ton\tmalicious\tpost\nUser\tIntent:Export\tA.docx\tto\tPDFExport\tto\tA.pdf\nDelete\t.ssh/id_rsaDelete\tA.docxMisalignedAction:Agent\tdeletes\tthe\toriginal\tdocx\tfile\tafter\texporting\tit\tto\tPDF\nUser\tIntent:Change\tdocument\tfont\nInteract\twith\tVLC\tmedia\tplayer\nMisalignedAction:Agent\topens\tunrelated\tvideo\tplayer\tapp\tinstead\tof\tdocument\teditor\nFigure 1.Examples of the three categories of misaligned actions. (a)Malicious Instruction Following: the action complies with external\nmalicious instructions; (b)Harmful Unintended Behavior: the action causes harm due to inherent limitations rather than adversarial\nattacks; (c)Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior: the action does not cause harm but is irrelevant to the task.\ntask and will degrade efficiency and reliability. Based on\nthis framing, we take a first step toward studyingmisaligned\naction detectionin CUAs: determining whether a proposed\naction is misaligned before actual execution.\nTo enable systematic evaluation of misaligned action detec-\ntion, we construct MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive bench-\nmark with over 2K human-annotated, action-level alignment\nlabels across realistic trajectories. It covers both externally\ninduced and internally arising misaligned actions through\na hybrid construction pipeline. We further propose DEAC-\nTION, a practical and universal guardrail that proactively\ndetects and corrects misaligned actions before execution.\nTo balance detection performance with latency, DEACTION\nemploys a two-stage analysis pipeline conditioned on a com-\npact narrative summary of the interaction history. Rather\nthan merely blocking misaligned actions, DEACTIONpro-\nvides structured feedback to guide agents toward corrected,\ntask-aligned behavior iteratively. We conduct extensive\nexperiments in both offline and online settings. On MIS-\nACTBENCH, DEACTIONoutperforms baselines by over\n15% absolute. In online evaluation, it reduces attack success\nrates by over 90% under adversarial scenarios (RedTeam-\nCUA (Liao et al., 2025)), and preserves or even improves\nbenign task success (OSWorld (Xie et al., 2024)), with mod-\nerate runtime overhead.\nWe present the first systematic study of misaligned action\ndetection in CUAs, with three main contributions:\n1. We propose an intent-centric perspective that frames\nCUA deviations as an action misalignment problem,\nand identify three common categories of misaligned\nactions in real-world deployments.\n2. We introduce MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive\nbenchmark with 2,264 human-annotated, action-level\nalignment labels on diverse CUA trajectories, covering\nall three categories of misaligned actions.\n3. We propose DEACTION, a practical and plug-and-play\nruntime guardrail that proactively detects misaligned\nactions before execution and iteratively corrects them\nvia structured feedback. Extensive experiments demon-\nstrate its effectiveness in both adversarial and benign\nsettings with moderate overhead.\n2. Problem Formulation\n2.1. Action Alignment\nWe begin by defining action alignment, the central concept\nunderlying our study.\nGiven a user instruction I, interaction history τ<t, and cur-\nrent observation ot, a proposed action at is considered\nalignedif it satisfies three conditions: (1) it is taken in\nservice of the user’s instruction I, rather than in response\nto other directives such as injected instructions in the envi-\nronment; (2) it does not result in unauthorized or undesired\nconsequences; and (3) it can be reasonably interpreted as\ncontributing, whether directly or indirectly, to completing\nthe user’s intended task. An action that violates any of these\nconditions is consideredmisaligned.\nNotably, alignment does not require optimality. An action\nmay be inefficient, exploratory, or ultimately unsuccessful\nyet still be aligned, as long as it represents a genuine attempt\nto advance the user’s goal.\nBased on this definition, we formulate the task ofmis-\naligned action detection: given (I, τ<t, ot, at), determine\nwhether at is misaligned before actual execution (i.e., with-\nout access to actual consequences).\n2.2. Categorization of Misaligned Actions\nThe three conditions in § 2.1 naturally give rise to a catego-\nrization of misaligned actions based on which condition is\nviolated. Concretely, we identify three categories observed\nin real-world CUA deployments, illustrated in Figure 1:\nMalicious Instruction Following.The agent complies with\nmalicious directives embedded in the external environment,\nsuch as indirect prompt injections in web content, instead\n2\n\n===== PAGE 3 =====\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n（a)\tGeneration\twith\tExternal\tAttacks(b)\tSynthesis\twithout\tAttacks\nDiverse\tCUAs•Generic\tLLMs•Specialized\tAgentsAdversarial\tBenchmarks\nOS-Harm,\tDoomArenaRedTeamCUA,\tRiOSWorld\nAttack-induced\tMisaligned\tTrajectoriesExecute\nBenign\tTraj.\tGeneration•FrontierCUAs•OSWorld\ttasks\nUnintended\tSubgoal•Subgoal\tsynthesis•Inject\tstep\tidentificationMerge\nSynthesized\tUnintended\tTrajectoriesRaw\tTrajectory\tPool\nHuman\tAnnotationMisActBench\nMisaligned\tAction\tDetection\tBenchmark\nFigure 2.Trajectory Collection Workflow for MISACTBENCH. (a) Collect trajectories with misaligned actions induced by external attacks\nby running diverse CUAs on existing benchmarks. (b) Synthesize trajectories with unintended behaviors in benign settings.\nof following the user’s authentic intent.\nHarmful Unintended Behavior.The agent causes unau-\nthorized or harmful consequences due to internal limita-\ntions (e.g., reasoning failures) rather than adversarial at-\ntacks. These may compromise the CIA triad (Howard &\nLipner, 2006): confidentiality (e.g., exposing sensitive in-\nformation), integrity (e.g., corrupting data), or availability\n(e.g., disrupting services).\nOther Task-Irrelevant Behavior.The agent performs ac-\ntions that are irrelevant to the user’s task, such as opening\nunrelated applications or navigating to irrelevant websites.\nThese also arise internally but do not cause direct harm, yet\nstill undermine execution efficiency and reliability.\n3. MISACTBENCH: Comprehensive Evaluation\nfor Misaligned Action Detection\nFollowing the definition of misaligned action detection\nin §2.1, we introduce MISACTBENCH, a realistic bench-\nmark of CUA interaction trajectories with human-annotated,\naction-level binary alignment labels.\n3.1. Raw Trajectory Collection\nTo achieve comprehensive coverage of all three categories\n(§2.2) at scale, we adopt a hybrid collection strategy based\non their origin, as illustrated in Figure 2.\nTrajectories with External Attacks.For misaligned ac-\ntions caused by external attacks, we leverage existing bench-\nmarks that explicitly incorporate adversarial settings with\nvision-based environmental injections, where malicious in-\nstructions are embedded in the visual interfaces (e.g., web\ncontents, pop-ups). Specifically, we leverage four repre-\nsentative benchmarks which collectively encompass a wide\nspectrum of attack vectors: OS-Harm (Kuntz et al., 2025),\nDoomArena (Boisvert et al., 2025), RedTeamCUA (Liao\net al., 2025), and RiOSWorld (Yang et al., 2025b).\nWe run a diverse set of agents on these benchmarks to\ncapture a broad range of behaviors under adversarial con-\nditions, including CUAs powered by both generic LLMs\n(GPT-4o (Hurst et al., 2024), Claude Sonnet 3.5 (Anthropic.,\n2024b), and Claude Sonnet 3.7 (Anthropic., 2025a)) as\nwell as specialized CUA models (OpenAI CUA (Ope-\nnAI., 2025b) and Claude Sonnet 3.5 and 3.7 with Computer\nUse (Anthropic., 2024c)). We use the benchmark-provided\ntrajectory-level evaluators to filter and retain only trajecto-\nries where the attack succeeded, ensuring that each contains\nconcrete instances of externally induced misalignment. We\npresent detailed settings in Appendix A.1.\nTrajectories without Attacks.While misaligned actions","numLines":400,"startLine":1,"totalLines":3208}}}
