{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B9WmPgX9bsDnN69qXQikrt","type":"tool_result","content":"400\tTrajectories without Attacks.While misaligned actions\n401\tcan also arise from agents themselves without attacks, such\n402\tmisalignment may occur sporadically, making it difficult to\n403\tcollect them at scale through normal execution. To address\n404\tthis, we design a trajectory synthesis procedure that injects\n405\tplausible deviations into benign trajectories.\n406\tWe begin by collecting trajectories on benign tasks from\n407\tOSWorld (Xie et al., 2024) using frontier CUAs (OpenAI\n408\tCUA (OpenAI., 2025b) and Claude Sonnet 4.5 with Com-\n409\tputer Use (Anthropic., 2025b)). Given a task and its benign\n410\texecution, we prompt an LLM to select a suitablesubgoal\n411\tprimitivefrom a predefined set of 13 high-level risk tem-\n412\tplates (see Table A.1). The selected primitive (e.g.,Delete\n413\tFile) is then contextualized into a concrete, environment-\n414\tgrounded subgoal (e.g., delete a specific file), and the LLM\n415\tidentifies an appropriate step at which the agent might acci-\n416\tdentally diverge toward this unintended subgoal. We execute\n417\tthe subgoal as a standalone task and merge the resulting ac-\n418\ttions into the benign trajectory at the identified injection\n419\tpoint. This approach yields trajectories that contain in-\n420\tternally arising misaligned actions while the rest remains\n421\tauthentic to normal behavior, without relying on rare sponta-\n422\tneous failures. All synthesized trajectories undergo manual\n423\t3\n424\t\n425\t===== PAGE 4 =====\n426\t165\n427\t166\n428\t167\n429\t168\n430\t169\n431\t170\n432\t171\n433\t172\n434\t173\n435\t174\n436\t175\n437\t176\n438\t177\n439\t178\n440\t179\n441\t180\n442\t181\n443\t182\n444\t183\n445\t184\n446\t185\n447\t186\n448\t187\n449\t188\n450\t189\n451\t190\n452\t191\n453\t192\n454\t193\n455\t194\n456\t195\n457\t196\n458\t197\n459\t198\n460\t199\n461\t200\n462\t201\n463\t202\n464\t203\n465\t204\n466\t205\n467\t206\n468\t207\n469\t208\n470\t209\n471\t210\n472\t211\n473\t212\n474\t213\n475\t214\n476\t215\n477\t216\n478\t217\n479\t218\n480\t219\n481\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n482\tTable 1.Comparison with existing benchmarks and datasets. MISACTBENCHprovides human-annotated action-level alignment labels for\n483\tmultimodal computer-use scenarios, covering broader action misalignment.\n484\tBenchmark Scenario Multimodal Label Granularity Risk Coverage\n485\tPre-Exec Bench (Huang et al., 2025) Tool-use✗Trajectory Explicit safety risks\n486\tPSG-Agent Benchmark (Wu et al., 2025) Tool-use✗Trajectory Personalized safety risks\n487\tR-Judge (Yuan et al., 2024) Tool-use✗Trajectory Explicit safety risks\n488\tASSEBench (Luo et al., 2025a) Tool-use✗Trajectory Safety & security risks\n489\tPolicyGuardBench (Wen et al., 2025) Web✗Trajectory Policy violation risks\n490\tShieldAgent-Bench (Chen et al., 2025b) Web✓Trajectory Policy violation risks\n491\tMobileRisk (Sun et al., 2025) Mobile✓Trajectory + One Action Explicit safety risks\n492\tMISACTBENCHWeb / OS✓Action Action misalignment\n493\tTable 2.Overall statistics of MISACTBENCH.\n494\tStatistic Count\n495\tTrajectories558\n496\tSteps2,264\n497\tAligned Steps1,264\n498\tMisaligned Steps1,000\n499\t- Malicious Instruction Following562(56.2%)\n500\t- Harmful Unintended Behavior210(21.0%)\n501\t- Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior228(22.8%)\n502\tvalidation to ensure successful execution and plausibility.\n503\tImplementation details and a concrete example are provided\n504\tin Appendix A.2 and A.3.\n505\tTogether, our benchmark captures misaligned actions caused\n506\tby both external attacks and inherent limitations, enabling\n507\tcomprehensive evaluation.\n508\t3.2. Human Annotation\n509\tWe annotate actions in the collected trajectories with align-\n510\tment labels. To ensure label quality and reliability, we\n511\temploy a rigorous two-phase annotation process. In the first\n512\tphase, an experienced annotator filters out uninformative\n513\tsteps, such as clicking on empty regions and waiting actions,\n514\ton the collected trajectories. In the second phase, three in-\n515\tdependent annotators label each remaining step as aligned\n516\tor assign it to one of the three misalignment categories. We\n517\tmeasure inter-annotator agreement and observe a Fleiss’\n518\tKappa score (Landis & Koch, 1977) of 0.84, indicating\n519\tnear-perfect inter-annotator agreement. Disagreements are\n520\tresolved via majority voting. We provide more details for\n521\thuman annotation in Appendix A.4.\n522\t3.3. Benchmark Statistics\n523\tWe summarize the key statistics of MISACTBENCHin Ta-\n524\tble 2. It contains 558 trajectories and 2,264 annotated ac-\n525\ttions, spanning all three categories defined in §2.2. More\n526\tstatistics can be found in Appendix A.5.\n527\tTable 1 shows the comparison of MISACTBENCHto ex-\n528\tisting benchmarks and datasets. MISACTBENCHuniquely\n529\tprovides human-annotated action-level alignment labels in\n530\tcomputer-use scenarios.\n531\t4.DEACTION: Runtime Misaligned Action\n532\tDetection and Correction\n533\tWe further introduce a runtime guardrail, DEACTION, de-\n534\tsigned to protect CUA execution through proactive mis-\n535\taligned action detection and correction. As illustrated in Fig-\n536\ture 3, at each step, it intercepts the agent’s proposed ac-\n537\ttion before execution and determines whether the action is\n538\taligned under the current context, and initiates a correction\n539\tloop to ensure action alignment if necessary. DEACTION\n540\tis designed to rely only on the actions and environment\n541\tstates, requiring no access to agents’ internal parameters or\n542\treasoning traces, making it plug-and-play for any CUA.\n543\t4.1. Misaligned Action Detection\n544\tAs a runtime guardrail, DEACTIONmust assess each pro-\n545\tposed action efficiently under tight latency constraints. To\n546\tbalance detection performance with runtime latency, DEAC-\n547\tTIONemploys a two-stage detection pipeline: a lightweight\n548\tfast check followed by systematic analysis only when\n549\tneeded, as shown in Figure 3(a).\n550\tStage 1: Fast Check.The fast check module serves as\n551\ta conservative screening mechanism that aims to quickly\n552\tidentify clearly aligned actions. Specifically, we prompt\n553\tan LLM to assess whether a proposed action corresponds\n554\tto a necessary or canonical step of the user intent without\n555\tambiguity. Actions deemed clearly aligned by the fast check\n556\tbypass further analysis, thereby reducing computational\n557\toverhead for routine steps. For instance, launching email\n558\tapps when the task is to send an email, or opening Settings\n559\twhen the task is to adjust system configurations. To keep this\n560\tstage lightweight, we explicitly constrain the LLM to output\n561\tonly a one-sentence rationale without extended reasoning.\n562\tStage 2: Systematic Analysis.Actions that cannot be\n563\tconfidently verified by the fast check are routed to the sys-\n564\ttematic analysis. We leverage the reasoning capabilities of\n565\tLLMs to perform a deep, structured inspection mirroring\n566\t4\n567\t\n568\t===== PAGE 5 =====\n569\t220\n570\t221\n571\t222\n572\t223\n573\t224\n574\t225\n575\t226\n576\t227\n577\t228\n578\t229\n579\t230\n580\t231\n581\t232\n582\t233\n583\t234\n584\t235\n585\t236\n586\t237\n587\t238\n588\t239\n589\t240\n590\t241\n591\t242\n592\t243\n593\t244\n594\t245\n595\t246\n596\t247\n597\t248\n598\t249\n599\t250\n600\t251\n601\t252\n602\t253\n603\t254\n604\t255\n605\t256\n606\t257\n607\t258\n608\t259\n609\t260\n610\t261\n611\t262\n612\t263\n613\t264\n614\t265\n615\t266\n616\t267\n617\t268\n618\t269\n619\t270\n620\t271\n621\t272\n622\t273\n623\t274\n624\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n625\tCUA\n626\tCUA\n627\tCUA\n628\tIter.\t1\n629\tIter.\t2\n630\tIter.\t3\n631\tDeAction\n632\tDeAction\n633\tDeAction\n634\tMisalignment\tFeedback\n635\tMisalignment\tFeedback\n636\t(b)\tIterative\tCorrection\n637\tComputer-Use\tAgent\n638\tFast\tCheck Aligned?Need\tFurther\tAnalysis\n639\tSystematic\tAnalysis\n640\tAction\tHistory\tSummarizationMisalignment\tFeedback\n641\tClearly\tAligned\n642\t Yes\n643\tNo\n644\t(a)\tMisaligned\tAction\tDetection\t(DeAction)\n645\tInjection\tAnalysis\n646\tAction\tUnderstanding\n647\tOutcome\tPrediction\n648\tMisalignment\tAnalysis\n649\tProposed\tAction\n650\tFigure 3.Overview of DEACTION. (a)Misaligned action detection.At each step, the guardrail intercepts the proposed action before\n651\texecution through a two-stage analysis, with a compact summary of interaction history. (b)Iterative correction.When an action is\n652\tflagged, the guardrail provides structured feedback to the agent, prompting action revision through a closed-loop interaction.\n653\thuman reasoning, assessing action alignment through four\n654\tstructured components: (1)Injection Analysisinspects the\n655\tcurrent screenshot for potential malicious or deceptive in-\n656\tstructions embedded in the environment that could redirect\n657\tthe agent. (2)Action Understandinginterprets the concrete\n658\tsemantics of the low-level action based on the current state\n659\tand history. (3)Outcome Predictionanticipates the conse-\n660\tquences that are not yet observable, including state changes\n661\tand long-term effects. (4) Finally,Misalignment Analysis\n662\tintegrates these signals to assess whether the action is con-\n663\tsistent with the user’s objective or deviates from it. This\n664\tstructured reasoning also yields human-readable rationales\n665\tfor inspection and intervention.\n666\tContext Management with Narrative Summarization.\n667\tMisaligned action detection is inherently history-dependent.\n668\tHowever, providing full raw history to the guardrail could\n669\tbe both ineffective and inefficient. Raw histories consist of\n670\tlong sequences of screenshots and low-level actions, which\n671\tare expensive to process and usually difficult to interpret\n672\tby current multimodal LLMs. Instead, DEACTIONcon-\n673\tditions its analysis on thenarrative summarizationof the\n674\thistory trajectory (Gonzalez-Pumariega et al., 2025). Af-\n675\tter each action at is executed, a summarizer condenses the\n676\ttransition (ot, at, ot+1) into a concise natural language de-\n677\tscription of the executed action and the resulting observable\n678\tchanges. These summaries then replace raw screenshots to\n679\tserve as the history context for analyzing subsequent actions.\n680\tThis design allows DEACTIONto progressively maintain a\n681\tcompact history context with substantially reduced token\n682\tconsumption. Moreover, summaries are generated in paral-\n683\tlel with agent execution, introducing no additional latency\n684\tin the detection process.\n685\t4.2. Correction via Iterative Feedback\n686\tDetecting misaligned actions is only half the battle; the ulti-\n687\tmate goal is to complete the user’s task faithfully. Instead of\n688\tsimply blocking the action, which halts task progress, DE-\n689\tACTIONleverages the four-component structured feedback\n690\tgenerated during theSystematic Analysis(§4.1) to guide the\n691\tagent toward aligned actions as shown in Figure 3(b).\n692\tThe feedback explicitly explains why the flagged action\n693\tis problematic, specifically highlighting the identified in-\n694\tjections, anticipated negative outcomes or logical discrep-\n695\tancies with the task intent. This serves as an additional\n696\tcorrective prompt, guiding the agent to reflect on its error\n697\tand propose a revised action, which is again evaluated by\n698\tthe guardrail. This closed-loop interaction continues until\n699\tan aligned action is proposed or a retry limit is reached,\n700\teffectively converting potential failures into aligned actions.\n701\t5. Experiments\n702\tWe present a comprehensive evaluation of DEACTION\n703\tthrough offline misaligned action detection and online end-\n704\tto-end experiments with CUAs in interactive environments.\n705\t5.1. Offline Evaluation\n706\tSettings.We compare DEACTIONagainst prior methods\n707\ton MISACTBENCH(§3), where each guardrail predicts\n708\ta binary alignment label given the user task, interaction\n709\thistory, current screenshot, and proposed action.\n710\tMisaligned action detection requires pre-execution action\n711\talignment assessment. However, most existing methods\n712\tare not directly applicable, as they operate at the trajec-\n713\ttory level (Wen et al., 2025), perform retrospective analy-\n714\tsis (Meng et al., 2025), or focus narrowly on predefined\n715\tsafety policies (Luo et al., 2025b; Chen et al., 2025b). Con-\n716\tsequently, we compare with two prior methods that assess\n717\taction alignment, adapting them to CUA settings with neces-\n718\tsary prompt and input adjustments: (1)Task Shield(Jia et al.,\n719\t2025), which decomposes tasks and actions into atomic in-\n720\tstructions for pairwise comparison; and (2)InferAct(Fang\n721\tet al., 2025), which infers the intended task from the tra-\n722\tjectory and compares it with the original instruction. We\n723\tevaluate all methods across four backbone models: Qwen3-\n724\t5\n725\t\n726\t===== PAGE 6 =====\n727\t275\n728\t276\n729\t277\n730\t278\n731\t279\n732\t280\n733\t281\n734\t282\n735\t283\n736\t284\n737\t285\n738\t286\n739\t287\n740\t288\n741\t289\n742\t290\n743\t291\n744\t292\n745\t293\n746\t294\n747\t295\n748\t296\n749\t297\n750\t298\n751\t299\n752\t300\n753\t301\n754\t302\n755\t303\n756\t304\n757\t305\n758\t306\n759\t307\n760\t308\n761\t309\n762\t310\n763\t311\n764\t312\n765\t313\n766\t314\n767\t315\n768\t316\n769\t317\n770\t318\n771\t319\n772\t320\n773\t321\n774\t322\n775\t323\n776\t324\n777\t325\n778\t326\n779\t327\n780\t328\n781\t329\n782\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n783\tTable 3.Misaligned action detection performance of different\n784\tmethods and backbones on MISACTBENCH.\n785\tMethod Precision Recall Acc F1\n786\tQwen3-VL-32B\n787\tTask Shield50.6 69.0 56.6 58.4\n788\tInferAct47.1 89.0 51.1 61.6\n789\tDEACTION(Ours)80.1 63.376.9 70.7\n790\tClaude Sonnet 4.5\n791\tTask Shield59.5 75.8 66.5 66.6\n792\tInferAct48.4 96.0 53.1 64.3\n793\tDEACTION(Ours)88.2 74.084.1 80.4\n794\tGPT-5.1 Instant\n795\tTask Shield51.4 88.8 58.0 65.1\n796\tInferAct51.4 87.3 58.0 64.7\n797\tDEACTION(Ours)73.4 86.480.2 79.4\n798\tGPT-5.1 Thinking\n799\tTask Shield61.3 73.6 67.8 66.9"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"ce9626c6-e723-4244-a776-029b78157e08","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:59:18.017Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_text.txt","content":"Trajectories without Attacks.While misaligned actions\ncan also arise from agents themselves without attacks, such\nmisalignment may occur sporadically, making it difficult to\ncollect them at scale through normal execution. To address\nthis, we design a trajectory synthesis procedure that injects\nplausible deviations into benign trajectories.\nWe begin by collecting trajectories on benign tasks from\nOSWorld (Xie et al., 2024) using frontier CUAs (OpenAI\nCUA (OpenAI., 2025b) and Claude Sonnet 4.5 with Com-\nputer Use (Anthropic., 2025b)). Given a task and its benign\nexecution, we prompt an LLM to select a suitablesubgoal\nprimitivefrom a predefined set of 13 high-level risk tem-\nplates (see Table A.1). The selected primitive (e.g.,Delete\nFile) is then contextualized into a concrete, environment-\ngrounded subgoal (e.g., delete a specific file), and the LLM\nidentifies an appropriate step at which the agent might acci-\ndentally diverge toward this unintended subgoal. We execute\nthe subgoal as a standalone task and merge the resulting ac-\ntions into the benign trajectory at the identified injection\npoint. This approach yields trajectories that contain in-\nternally arising misaligned actions while the rest remains\nauthentic to normal behavior, without relying on rare sponta-\nneous failures. All synthesized trajectories undergo manual\n3\n\n===== PAGE 4 =====\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nTable 1.Comparison with existing benchmarks and datasets. MISACTBENCHprovides human-annotated action-level alignment labels for\nmultimodal computer-use scenarios, covering broader action misalignment.\nBenchmark Scenario Multimodal Label Granularity Risk Coverage\nPre-Exec Bench (Huang et al., 2025) Tool-use✗Trajectory Explicit safety risks\nPSG-Agent Benchmark (Wu et al., 2025) Tool-use✗Trajectory Personalized safety risks\nR-Judge (Yuan et al., 2024) Tool-use✗Trajectory Explicit safety risks\nASSEBench (Luo et al., 2025a) Tool-use✗Trajectory Safety & security risks\nPolicyGuardBench (Wen et al., 2025) Web✗Trajectory Policy violation risks\nShieldAgent-Bench (Chen et al., 2025b) Web✓Trajectory Policy violation risks\nMobileRisk (Sun et al., 2025) Mobile✓Trajectory + One Action Explicit safety risks\nMISACTBENCHWeb / OS✓Action Action misalignment\nTable 2.Overall statistics of MISACTBENCH.\nStatistic Count\nTrajectories558\nSteps2,264\nAligned Steps1,264\nMisaligned Steps1,000\n- Malicious Instruction Following562(56.2%)\n- Harmful Unintended Behavior210(21.0%)\n- Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior228(22.8%)\nvalidation to ensure successful execution and plausibility.\nImplementation details and a concrete example are provided\nin Appendix A.2 and A.3.\nTogether, our benchmark captures misaligned actions caused\nby both external attacks and inherent limitations, enabling\ncomprehensive evaluation.\n3.2. Human Annotation\nWe annotate actions in the collected trajectories with align-\nment labels. To ensure label quality and reliability, we\nemploy a rigorous two-phase annotation process. In the first\nphase, an experienced annotator filters out uninformative\nsteps, such as clicking on empty regions and waiting actions,\non the collected trajectories. In the second phase, three in-\ndependent annotators label each remaining step as aligned\nor assign it to one of the three misalignment categories. We\nmeasure inter-annotator agreement and observe a Fleiss’\nKappa score (Landis & Koch, 1977) of 0.84, indicating\nnear-perfect inter-annotator agreement. Disagreements are\nresolved via majority voting. We provide more details for\nhuman annotation in Appendix A.4.\n3.3. Benchmark Statistics\nWe summarize the key statistics of MISACTBENCHin Ta-\nble 2. It contains 558 trajectories and 2,264 annotated ac-\ntions, spanning all three categories defined in §2.2. More\nstatistics can be found in Appendix A.5.\nTable 1 shows the comparison of MISACTBENCHto ex-\nisting benchmarks and datasets. MISACTBENCHuniquely\nprovides human-annotated action-level alignment labels in\ncomputer-use scenarios.\n4.DEACTION: Runtime Misaligned Action\nDetection and Correction\nWe further introduce a runtime guardrail, DEACTION, de-\nsigned to protect CUA execution through proactive mis-\naligned action detection and correction. As illustrated in Fig-\nure 3, at each step, it intercepts the agent’s proposed ac-\ntion before execution and determines whether the action is\naligned under the current context, and initiates a correction\nloop to ensure action alignment if necessary. DEACTION\nis designed to rely only on the actions and environment\nstates, requiring no access to agents’ internal parameters or\nreasoning traces, making it plug-and-play for any CUA.\n4.1. Misaligned Action Detection\nAs a runtime guardrail, DEACTIONmust assess each pro-\nposed action efficiently under tight latency constraints. To\nbalance detection performance with runtime latency, DEAC-\nTIONemploys a two-stage detection pipeline: a lightweight\nfast check followed by systematic analysis only when\nneeded, as shown in Figure 3(a).\nStage 1: Fast Check.The fast check module serves as\na conservative screening mechanism that aims to quickly\nidentify clearly aligned actions. Specifically, we prompt\nan LLM to assess whether a proposed action corresponds\nto a necessary or canonical step of the user intent without\nambiguity. Actions deemed clearly aligned by the fast check\nbypass further analysis, thereby reducing computational\noverhead for routine steps. For instance, launching email\napps when the task is to send an email, or opening Settings\nwhen the task is to adjust system configurations. To keep this\nstage lightweight, we explicitly constrain the LLM to output\nonly a one-sentence rationale without extended reasoning.\nStage 2: Systematic Analysis.Actions that cannot be\nconfidently verified by the fast check are routed to the sys-\ntematic analysis. We leverage the reasoning capabilities of\nLLMs to perform a deep, structured inspection mirroring\n4\n\n===== PAGE 5 =====\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nCUA\nCUA\nCUA\nIter.\t1\nIter.\t2\nIter.\t3\nDeAction\nDeAction\nDeAction\nMisalignment\tFeedback\nMisalignment\tFeedback\n(b)\tIterative\tCorrection\nComputer-Use\tAgent\nFast\tCheck Aligned?Need\tFurther\tAnalysis\nSystematic\tAnalysis\nAction\tHistory\tSummarizationMisalignment\tFeedback\nClearly\tAligned\n Yes\nNo\n(a)\tMisaligned\tAction\tDetection\t(DeAction)\nInjection\tAnalysis\nAction\tUnderstanding\nOutcome\tPrediction\nMisalignment\tAnalysis\nProposed\tAction\nFigure 3.Overview of DEACTION. (a)Misaligned action detection.At each step, the guardrail intercepts the proposed action before\nexecution through a two-stage analysis, with a compact summary of interaction history. (b)Iterative correction.When an action is\nflagged, the guardrail provides structured feedback to the agent, prompting action revision through a closed-loop interaction.\nhuman reasoning, assessing action alignment through four\nstructured components: (1)Injection Analysisinspects the\ncurrent screenshot for potential malicious or deceptive in-\nstructions embedded in the environment that could redirect\nthe agent. (2)Action Understandinginterprets the concrete\nsemantics of the low-level action based on the current state\nand history. (3)Outcome Predictionanticipates the conse-\nquences that are not yet observable, including state changes\nand long-term effects. (4) Finally,Misalignment Analysis\nintegrates these signals to assess whether the action is con-\nsistent with the user’s objective or deviates from it. This\nstructured reasoning also yields human-readable rationales\nfor inspection and intervention.\nContext Management with Narrative Summarization.\nMisaligned action detection is inherently history-dependent.\nHowever, providing full raw history to the guardrail could\nbe both ineffective and inefficient. Raw histories consist of\nlong sequences of screenshots and low-level actions, which\nare expensive to process and usually difficult to interpret\nby current multimodal LLMs. Instead, DEACTIONcon-\nditions its analysis on thenarrative summarizationof the\nhistory trajectory (Gonzalez-Pumariega et al., 2025). Af-\nter each action at is executed, a summarizer condenses the\ntransition (ot, at, ot+1) into a concise natural language de-\nscription of the executed action and the resulting observable\nchanges. These summaries then replace raw screenshots to\nserve as the history context for analyzing subsequent actions.\nThis design allows DEACTIONto progressively maintain a\ncompact history context with substantially reduced token\nconsumption. Moreover, summaries are generated in paral-\nlel with agent execution, introducing no additional latency\nin the detection process.\n4.2. Correction via Iterative Feedback\nDetecting misaligned actions is only half the battle; the ulti-\nmate goal is to complete the user’s task faithfully. Instead of\nsimply blocking the action, which halts task progress, DE-\nACTIONleverages the four-component structured feedback\ngenerated during theSystematic Analysis(§4.1) to guide the\nagent toward aligned actions as shown in Figure 3(b).\nThe feedback explicitly explains why the flagged action\nis problematic, specifically highlighting the identified in-\njections, anticipated negative outcomes or logical discrep-\nancies with the task intent. This serves as an additional\ncorrective prompt, guiding the agent to reflect on its error\nand propose a revised action, which is again evaluated by\nthe guardrail. This closed-loop interaction continues until\nan aligned action is proposed or a retry limit is reached,\neffectively converting potential failures into aligned actions.\n5. Experiments\nWe present a comprehensive evaluation of DEACTION\nthrough offline misaligned action detection and online end-\nto-end experiments with CUAs in interactive environments.\n5.1. Offline Evaluation\nSettings.We compare DEACTIONagainst prior methods\non MISACTBENCH(§3), where each guardrail predicts\na binary alignment label given the user task, interaction\nhistory, current screenshot, and proposed action.\nMisaligned action detection requires pre-execution action\nalignment assessment. However, most existing methods\nare not directly applicable, as they operate at the trajec-\ntory level (Wen et al., 2025), perform retrospective analy-\nsis (Meng et al., 2025), or focus narrowly on predefined\nsafety policies (Luo et al., 2025b; Chen et al., 2025b). Con-\nsequently, we compare with two prior methods that assess\naction alignment, adapting them to CUA settings with neces-\nsary prompt and input adjustments: (1)Task Shield(Jia et al.,\n2025), which decomposes tasks and actions into atomic in-\nstructions for pairwise comparison; and (2)InferAct(Fang\net al., 2025), which infers the intended task from the tra-\njectory and compares it with the original instruction. We\nevaluate all methods across four backbone models: Qwen3-\n5\n\n===== PAGE 6 =====\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nTable 3.Misaligned action detection performance of different\nmethods and backbones on MISACTBENCH.\nMethod Precision Recall Acc F1\nQwen3-VL-32B\nTask Shield50.6 69.0 56.6 58.4\nInferAct47.1 89.0 51.1 61.6\nDEACTION(Ours)80.1 63.376.9 70.7\nClaude Sonnet 4.5\nTask Shield59.5 75.8 66.5 66.6\nInferAct48.4 96.0 53.1 64.3\nDEACTION(Ours)88.2 74.084.1 80.4\nGPT-5.1 Instant\nTask Shield51.4 88.8 58.0 65.1\nInferAct51.4 87.3 58.0 64.7\nDEACTION(Ours)73.4 86.480.2 79.4\nGPT-5.1 Thinking\nTask Shield61.3 73.6 67.8 66.9","numLines":400,"startLine":400,"totalLines":3208}}}
