{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WZQoiEEWfbkKEu4PNsBJ7k","type":"tool_result","content":"800\tInferAct56.0 70.1 62.5 62.3\n801\tDEACTION(Ours)89.9 76.885.9 82.8\n802\tVL-32B (Yang et al., 2025a), Claude Sonnet 4.5 (Anthropic.,\n803\t2025b), GPT-5.1 Instant, and GPT-5.1 Thinking (OpenAI.,\n804\t2025a). We treat misaligned actions as the positive class\n805\tand report Precision, Recall, Accuracy, and F1. More exper-\n806\timental details are in Appendix C.1.\n807\tResults.As shown in Table 3, our method consistently out-\n808\tperforms prior approaches on MISACTBENCH, achieving\n809\tsubstantially higher accuracy and F1 across different back-\n810\tbones. While Task Shield and InferAct sometimes achieve\n811\thigh recall, their precision often hovers around50%, indicat-\n812\ting they tend to over-flag actions as misaligned and roughly\n813\thalf of their flagged actions are false positives. Such behav-\n814\tior limits practical utility, as frequent false alarms disrupt\n815\tnormal task execution. In contrast, DEACTIONmaintains\n816\tstrong recall while significantly improving precision, reach-\n817\ting up to 89.9%, resulting in more reliable detection with\n818\tthe highest F1 scores (∼80%).\n819\tAdditionally, we analyze the detection performance of DE-\n820\tACTIONacross three misalignment categories and evaluate\n821\twhether it can classify flagged actions in Appendix E.1. Re-\n822\tsults show that malicious instruction following is easiest to\n823\tidentify due to explicit cues, while the two internally arising\n824\tcategories remain challenging to both detect and classify.\n825\tEffect of History Representation.Action alignment is\n826\tinherently context-dependent, so we study how different\n827\thistory representations affect detection performance on\n828\ta randomly sampled subset of MISACTBENCH(see Ap-\n829\tpendix C.2 for details). We use GPT-5.1 Thinking (the best\n830\tsetting in Table 3) throughout ablation studies. We compare\n831\tthree settings: (1)Actions Only; (2)Actions + Observations,\n832\twhich additionally includes screenshots; and (3)Actions +\n833\tNarrative Summary(our default), which additionally com-\n834\tpresses each step into a concise natural language description.\n835\t65\n836\t70\n837\t75\n838\t80Recall (%)\n839\t65\n840\t70\n841\t75\n842\t80F1 (%)\n843\tActions Only Actions + Obs. Actions + Narrative Summary\n844\tFigure 4.Performance under different history representations.\n845\tAs shown in Figure 4, narrative summary achieves the best\n846\tperformance. Using actions alone performs the worst, con-\n847\tfirming that observations provide important context for as-\n848\tsessing subsequent actions. While incorporating screenshots\n849\t(i.e.,+Obs) improves the detection performance, it is still\n850\tless effective than narrative summaries and introduces sub-\n851\tstantially higher latency ( 18s vs. 11s per step) as well as\n852\tmuch higher token consumption (over 1K tokens per screen-\n853\tshot vs. 41 tokens per summary). These results validate\n854\tnarrative summaries as a practical history representation: it\n855\tretains sufficient long-horizon context for alignment assess-\n856\tment, while avoiding latency introduced by raw screenshots.\n857\tLatency–Performance Tradeoff.We examine how the two-\n858\tstage design balances detection performance and latency\n859\ton the same subset (Appendix C.2). We evaluate three\n860\tconfigurations: (1)Fast Check Only, which relies solely on\n861\tthe fast check; (2)Systematic Analysis Only, which applies\n862\tsystematic analysis to every action; and (3)Fast Check +\n863\tSystematic, the default two-stage setting.\n864\tTable 4 shows that the two-stage design achieves a favorable\n865\tbalance between detection performance and latency. Com-\n866\tpared to systematic analysis alone, the two-stage approach\n867\treduces latency while achieving the same performance, as it\n868\tbypasses heavy reasoning for clearly aligned actions. Note\n869\tthatthis latency reduction could be more pronounced in\n870\treal-world deployment: The balanced label distribution of\n871\tMISACTBENCHcauses most of the actions to be routed to\n872\tsystematic analysis, whereas real-world executions with pre-\n873\tdominantly aligned actions would see higher bypass rates.\n874\tConversely, relying solely on the fast check yields the low-\n875\test latency but suffers from substantially degraded precision\n876\t(70.6%), indicating that lightweight screening alone tends to\n877\tover-flag actions. These results confirm that the fast check\n878\tis most effective as a conservative filter for clearly aligned\n879\tactions, reserving systematic analysis for ambiguous cases.\n880\tError Analysis.We inspect representative failure cases of\n881\tDEACTION. First, well-disguised malicious instructions\n882\tcan deceive the fast check and injection analysis, leading to\n883\tmissed misaligned actions. Second, errors may stem from in-\n884\tsufficient grounding capabilities of LLMs when interpreting\n885\tcoordinate-based actions or predicting their outcomes. In ad-\n886\t6\n887\t\n888\t===== PAGE 7 =====\n889\t330\n890\t331\n891\t332\n892\t333\n893\t334\n894\t335\n895\t336\n896\t337\n897\t338\n898\t339\n899\t340\n900\t341\n901\t342\n902\t343\n903\t344\n904\t345\n905\t346\n906\t347\n907\t348\n908\t349\n909\t350\n910\t351\n911\t352\n912\t353\n913\t354\n914\t355\n915\t356\n916\t357\n917\t358\n918\t359\n919\t360\n920\t361\n921\t362\n922\t363\n923\t364\n924\t365\n925\t366\n926\t367\n927\t368\n928\t369\n929\t370\n930\t371\n931\t372\n932\t373\n933\t374\n934\t375\n935\t376\n936\t377\n937\t378\n938\t379\n939\t380\n940\t381\n941\t382\n942\t383\n943\t384\n944\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n945\tTable 4.Latency–performance trade-off of detection configurations. The two-stage design balances detection performance and efficiency.\n946\tPrecision Recall Acc F1 Latency (s)\n947\tFast Check Only70.6 86.7 79.7 77.8 4.2\n948\tSystematic Analysis Only85.8 75.1 84.6 80.1 13.1\n949\tFast Check + Systematic85.4 75.1 84.5 79.9 11.3\n950\tdition, even when all preceding analyses function correctly,\n951\tthe guardrail may still produce erroneous judgments due\n952\tto flawed intent-level reasoning, such as an overly narrow\n953\tnotion of task relevance. Detailed examples are provided\n954\tin Appendix E.4. Despite the strong overall performance\n955\tof DEACTION, these failure modes highlight promising\n956\tdirections for future work, such as more robust injection\n957\tdetection, fine-grained action understanding, and accurate\n958\tintent-level reasoning.\n959\t5.2. Online Evaluation\n960\tWhile offline evaluation measures detection accuracy on\n961\tpre-collected trajectories, it creates a gap with real-world\n962\tdeployment by missing the full workflow, particularly the\n963\titerative correction loop. We therefore evaluate DEACTION\n964\tend-to-end in realistic interactive environments to assess its\n965\timpact on CUA adversarial robustness, task performance,\n966\tand runtime latency.\n967\tSettings.We conduct experiments under two settings:\n968\t(1)Adversarial, using high-risk tasks from RedTeam-\n969\tCUA (Liao et al., 2025) featuring indirect prompt injections;\n970\tand (2)Benign, using standard tasks from OSWorld (Xie\n971\tet al., 2024). We experiment with three representative CUAs,\n972\tcovering both closed-source and open-source agents from\n973\tdifferent developers: computer use version of Claude Sonnet\n974\t4.5 (Anthropic., 2025b), OpenAI CUA (OpenAI., 2025b),\n975\tand OpenCUA-72B (Wang et al., 2025). We report At-\n976\ttack Success Rate (ASR) and Utility under Attack (UA) for\n977\tRedTeamCUA, and task Success Rate (SR) for OSWorld.\n978\tWe compare against four representative baselines covering\n979\tdiverse defense paradigms: (1)Defensive System Prompt\n980\t(DSP)(Liao et al., 2025), which augments the agent’s\n981\tsystem prompt with warnings about potential injections;\n982\t(2)PromptArmor(Shi et al., 2025), an input guardrail\n983\tthat identifies injected instructions and alerts accordingly;\n984\t(3)Output guardrails:Task Shield(Jia et al., 2025) and\n985\t(4)InferAct(Fang et al., 2025), which were introduced in\n986\t§C.1. For DEACTIONand all output guardrails, we set the\n987\tmaximum correction iterations to 3. Due to the high cost of\n988\tonline evaluation, we only compare with other defenses on\n989\tthe open-source agent, i.e., OpenCUA-72B. For all methods,\n990\twe use GPT-5.1 Instant as the backbone, which achieves the\n991\tbest cost-performance balance in offline experiments. More\n992\tdetails are in Appendix D.\n993\tResults.As shown in Table 5, on RedTeamCUA, DEAC-\n994\t0.0 2.5 5.0 7.5 10.0 12.5 15.0 17.5\n995\tPer-step Guardrail Latency (s)\n996\t0\n997\t5\n998\t10\n999\t15\n1000\t20\n1001\t25\n1002\t30\n1003\t35Attack Success Rate (%)\n1004\tNo Defense\n1005\tDSP\n1006\tPromptArmor\n1007\tT ask Shield InferAct\n1008\tOurs\n1009\tNo Defense\n1010\tDSP\n1011\tPromptArmor\n1012\tT ask Shield\n1013\tInferAct\n1014\tOurs\n1015\tFigure 5.Comparison of attack success rate (ASR) versus per-step\n1016\tguardrail latency on RedTeamCUA. DEACTIONis Pareto-optimal,\n1017\tachieving the lowest ASR while incurring moderate latency.\n1018\tTIONreduces ASR by over 90% across all CUAs while im-\n1019\tproving task success rate under attack (UA), demonstrating\n1020\tits effectiveness against adversarial attacks and in correct-\n1021\ting misaligned actions. Importantly, this protection comes\n1022\twithout sacrificing utility in benign environments: SR on\n1023\tOSWorld remains comparable or sometimes improved with\n1024\tDEACTION, indicating it does not over-constrain normal\n1025\tbehavior. This is essential for real-world, universally ap-\n1026\tplicable guardrails across environments with or without\n1027\tadversarial attacks.\n1028\tDEACTIONoutperforms baselines in both effectiveness and\n1029\tefficiency: As shown in Figure 5, DEACTIONachieves the\n1030\tlowest ASR with moderate latency. DSP and PromptArmor\n1031\tprovide limited ASR reduction and can degrade benign per-\n1032\tformance. Other output guardrails (InferAct and The Task\n1033\tShield) achieve lower ASR than DSP and PromptArmor\n1034\tbut incur substantially higher latency and hinder normal\n1035\ttask execution, due to their tendency to over-flag actions,\n1036\ttriggering excessive iterative correction.\n1037\tRuntime Analysis.We analyze the runtime behavior of\n1038\tDEACTIONin online experiments, with statistics averaged\n1039\tacross two settings and all CUAs. Detailed breakdowns\n1040\tare included in Appendix E.2. (1)Latency:With DEAC-\n1041\tTIONenabled, online execution incurs manageable over-\n1042\thead: guardrail reasoning accounts for 25% of per-step\n1043\texecution time ( 7.2s out of 28.1s on average). (2)Two-\n1044\tstage Routing:The two-stage design substantially reduces\n1045\tunnecessary computation. 45% of actions are approved\n1046\tdirectly by the fast check with an average latency of only\n1047\t3.2s, while the remaining actions are routed to systematic\n1048\tanalysis. This indicates that a large fraction of routine or\n1049\tclearly aligned actions bypass deep reasoning, allowing the\n1050\tguardrail to concentrate computational resources on ambigu-\n1051\t7\n1052\t\n1053\t===== PAGE 8 =====\n1054\t385\n1055\t386\n1056\t387\n1057\t388\n1058\t389\n1059\t390\n1060\t391\n1061\t392\n1062\t393\n1063\t394\n1064\t395\n1065\t396\n1066\t397\n1067\t398\n1068\t399\n1069\t400\n1070\t401\n1071\t402\n1072\t403\n1073\t404\n1074\t405\n1075\t406\n1076\t407\n1077\t408\n1078\t409\n1079\t410\n1080\t411\n1081\t412\n1082\t413\n1083\t414\n1084\t415\n1085\t416\n1086\t417\n1087\t418\n1088\t419\n1089\t420\n1090\t421\n1091\t422\n1092\t423\n1093\t424\n1094\t425\n1095\t426\n1096\t427\n1097\t428\n1098\t429\n1099\t430\n1100\t431\n1101\t432\n1102\t433\n1103\t434\n1104\t435\n1105\t436\n1106\t437\n1107\t438\n1108\t439\n1109\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n1110\tTable 5.Online evaluation results. We report Attack Success Rate (ASR) and Utility under Attack (UA) on RedTeamCUA, Success Rate\n1111\t(SR) on OSWorld. DEACTIONconsistently reduces ASR across different CUAs while maintaining benign utility and reasonable latency.\n1112\tAgent Defense Adversarial (RedTeamCUA) Benign (OSWorld)\n1113\tASR (%)↓UA (%)↑SR (%)↑\n1114\tClaude Sonnet 4.5 No Defense60.0 44.042.9\n1115\tDEACTION6.0 76.040.7\n1116\tOpenAI CUA No Defense42.0 82.0 26.0\n1117\tDEACTION4.0 84.0 30.7\n1118\tOpenCUA-72B\n1119\tNo Defense32.0 48.0 39.0\n1120\tDSP24.0 52.0 38.3\n1121\tPromptArmor26.0 44.0 35.2\n1122\tTask Shield22.0 58.0 36.6\n1123\tInferAct22.070.036.5\n1124\tDEACTION2.060.039.6\n1125\tous or higher-risk steps. (3)Guardrail Intervention:When\n1126\tDEACTIONflags an action as misaligned (16% of steps),\n1127\t78% are ultimately corrected to aligned behavior through\n1128\titerative feedback, with 62% corrected in a single revision.\n1129\tThis demonstrates that DEACTIONactively recovers aligned\n1130\texecution rather than merely blocking progress.\n1131\tMore Cost-Efficient Deployment.While all prior exper-\n1132\timents use the same LLM backbone for all components\n1133\tin DEACTION, its modular design allows adopting differ-\n1134\tent LLMs for different components. Empirically, we ob-\n1135\tserve that replacing the fast check and narrative summarizer\n1136\twith lighter models (e.g., GPT-5 mini) reduces cost by 65%\n1137\twhile preserving comparable detection performance. In\n1138\tcontrast, the systematic analysis benefits substantially from\n1139\tstronger reasoning, and downgrading it leads to notable per-\n1140\tformance degradation. Online evaluation confirms that this\n1141\tcost-efficient configuration achieves similar effectiveness.\n1142\tDetails are in Appendix E.3.\n1143\t6. Related Work\n1144\tComputer-Use Agents.Computer-use agents (CUAs) auto-\n1145\tmate complex digital workflows by interacting with graph-\n1146\tical user interfaces (GUIs), translating high-level user in-\n1147\tstructions into low-level keyboard and mouse actions (Ope-\n1148\tnAI., 2025b; Anthropic., 2024c; Wang et al., 2025; Zheng\n1149\tet al., 2024). Existing CUAs fall into two categories:LLM-\n1150\tadapted CUAsrepurpose general-purpose large language\n1151\tmodels (LLMs) with agentic scaffolding, leveraging their\n1152\tstrong reasoning and visual capabilities (Xie et al., 2024).\n1153\tIn contrast,specialized CUAs, such as OpenAI CUA (Ope-\n1154\tnAI., 2025b) and Claude Computer Use (Anthropic., 2024c),\n1155\tare explicitly designed for GUI interaction and incorporate\n1156\ttailored perception (Anthropic., 2024a; Qin et al., 2025;\n1157\tCheng et al., 2024; Gou et al., 2025), reasoning (OpenAI.,\n1158\t2025b; Wang et al., 2025), and computer-use tools (An-\n1159\tthropic., 2024c). While these agents have demonstrated\n1160\timpressive performance on realistic benchmarks (Xie et al.,\n1161\t2024; Bonatti et al., 2025; Koh et al., 2024; Xue et al., 2025;\n1162\tRawles et al., 2024), their real-world deployment introduces\n1163\tchallenges. Unlike sandbox environments, real-world exe-\n1164\tcution requires strict alignment with user intent over long\n1165\thorizons, where even minor deviations can lead to undesired\n1166\tside effects or safety risks.\n1167\tMisaligned Actions in Agent Execution.Despite rapid\n1168\tprogress, prior work has repeatedly observed that CUAs\n1169\tmay produce actions deviating from the user’s original in-\n1170\ttent (Srikumar et al., 2025; Jones et al., 2025). Such mis-\n1171\taligned actions arise from multiple sources (Chen et al.,\n1172\t2025a). A major class isenvironment-induced misalign-\n1173\tment, most notably indirect prompt injections, where agents\n1174\tfollow malicious content in web pages, documents or UI ele-\n1175\tments (Jones et al., 2025; Yang et al., 2025b; Boisvert et al.,\n1176\t2025; Kuntz et al., 2025; Evtimov et al., 2025). Agents may\n1177\talso exhibitinternally arising misalignment, performing\n1178\tactions that cause unintended harm or side effects due to\n1179\tmisinterpreted task boundaries or erroneous reasoning (Ope-\n1180\tnAI., 2025b; Lynch et al., 2025; Greenblatt et al., 2024;\n1181\tKuntz et al., 2025; Naik et al., 2025). In addition, some\n1182\tmisaligned actions are non-malicious yet task-irrelevant,\n1183\tsuch as engaging in unjustified interactions with unrelated\n1184\tapplications. Such misaligned actions are difficult to cap-\n1185\tture with safety-centric guardrails (Xiang et al., 2025; Hu\n1186\tet al., 2025; Luo et al., 2025b; Zheng et al., 2025). While\n1187\tprior studies provide retrospective analysis of misaligned\n1188\tbehaviors (Fronsdal et al., 2025; Meng et al., 2025), prac-\n1189\ttical runtime guardrails that can detect a broad range of\n1190\tmisaligned actions in CUA deployment remain lacking.\n1191\t7. Conclusion\n1192\tIn this work, we make the first effort to define and study\n1193\tmisaligned action detection in CUAs, a practical yet under-\n1194\texplored problem for reliable CUA deployment. We identify\n1195\t8\n1196\t\n1197\t===== PAGE 9 =====\n1198\t440\n1199\t441\n1200\t442\n1201\t443\n1202\t444\n1203\t445\n1204\t446\n1205\t447\n1206\t448\n1207\t449\n1208\t450\n1209\t451\n1210\t452\n1211\t453\n1212\t454\n1213\t455\n1214\t456\n1215\t457\n1216\t458\n1217\t459\n1218\t460\n1219\t461\n1220\t462\n1221\t463\n1222\t464\n1223\t465\n1224\t466\n1225\t467\n1226\t468\n1227\t469\n1228\t470\n1229\t471\n1230\t472\n1231\t473\n1232\t474\n1233\t475\n1234\t476\n1235\t477\n1236\t478\n1237\t479\n1238\t480\n1239\t481\n1240\t482\n1241\t483\n1242\t484\n1243\t485\n1244\t486\n1245\t487\n1246\t488\n1247\t489\n1248\t490\n1249\t491\n1250\t492\n1251\t493\n1252\t494\n1253\tDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n1254\tthree categories of misaligned actions in CUAs and intro-\n1255\tduce MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive benchmark with\n1256\thuman-annotated action-level labels. We also propose DE-\n1257\tACTION, a practical and universal guardrail that proactively\n1258\tdetects misaligned actions before execution and corrects\n1259\tthem through iterative feedback. Experiments demonstrate\n1260\tthat DEACTIONimproves misaligned action detection, re-\n1261\tduces attack success rate under adversarial settings, and\n1262\tpreserves task success rate in benign environments, con-\n1263\tfirming its practicality as a plug-and-play protection for\n1264\treal-world CUA deployment.\n1265\tImpact Statement\n1266\tThis paper studies misaligned action detection in computer-\n1267\tuse agents and proposes a runtime guardrail to improve\n1268\taction alignment during agent execution. The primary goal\n1269\tof this work is to enhance the reliability and robustness of\n1270\tcomputer-use agents operating in open-ended, real-world\n1271\tcomputer environments.\n1272\tBy detecting and correcting misaligned actions before exe-\n1273\tcution, this work aims to reduce safety risks, unnecessary\n1274\tside effects, and execution-time failures that may arise when\n1275\tagents interact with complex user interfaces. As such, the\n1276\tproposed benchmark and guardrail have the potential to\n1277\tsupport safer and more reliable deployment of computer-\n1278\tuse agents in practical applications. Overall, we believe\n1279\tthis work contributes positively to the development of more\n1280\ttrustworthy and controllable machine learning systems.\n1281\tReferences\n1282\tAnthropic. Developing a computer use model.,\n1283\t2024a. URL https://www.anthropic.com/\n1284\tnews/developing-computer-use.\n1285\tAnthropic. Introducing computer use, a new\n1286\tclaude 3.5 sonnet, and claude 3.5 haiku, 2024b.\n1287\tURL https://www.anthropic.com/news/\n1288\t3-5-models-and-computer-use.\n1289\tAnthropic. Claude computer use (beta), 2024c. URL\n1290\thttps://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/\n1291\tagents-and-tools/computer-use.\n1292\tAnthropic. Claude 3.7 sonnet system card,\n1293\t2025a. URL https://assets.anthropic.\n1294\tcom/m/785e231869ea8b3b/original/\n1295\tclaude-3-7-sonnet-system-card.pdf.\n1296\tAnthropic. Introducing claude sonnet 4.5., 2025b.\n1297\tURL https://www.anthropic.com/news/\n1298\tclaude-sonnet-4-5.\n1299\tBoisvert, L., Bansal, M., Evuru, C. K. R., Huang, G., Puri,"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"608763de-1d99-4ee8-b983-abbc631ea47b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:59:20.532Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_text.txt","content":"InferAct56.0 70.1 62.5 62.3\nDEACTION(Ours)89.9 76.885.9 82.8\nVL-32B (Yang et al., 2025a), Claude Sonnet 4.5 (Anthropic.,\n2025b), GPT-5.1 Instant, and GPT-5.1 Thinking (OpenAI.,\n2025a). We treat misaligned actions as the positive class\nand report Precision, Recall, Accuracy, and F1. More exper-\nimental details are in Appendix C.1.\nResults.As shown in Table 3, our method consistently out-\nperforms prior approaches on MISACTBENCH, achieving\nsubstantially higher accuracy and F1 across different back-\nbones. While Task Shield and InferAct sometimes achieve\nhigh recall, their precision often hovers around50%, indicat-\ning they tend to over-flag actions as misaligned and roughly\nhalf of their flagged actions are false positives. Such behav-\nior limits practical utility, as frequent false alarms disrupt\nnormal task execution. In contrast, DEACTIONmaintains\nstrong recall while significantly improving precision, reach-\ning up to 89.9%, resulting in more reliable detection with\nthe highest F1 scores (∼80%).\nAdditionally, we analyze the detection performance of DE-\nACTIONacross three misalignment categories and evaluate\nwhether it can classify flagged actions in Appendix E.1. Re-\nsults show that malicious instruction following is easiest to\nidentify due to explicit cues, while the two internally arising\ncategories remain challenging to both detect and classify.\nEffect of History Representation.Action alignment is\ninherently context-dependent, so we study how different\nhistory representations affect detection performance on\na randomly sampled subset of MISACTBENCH(see Ap-\npendix C.2 for details). We use GPT-5.1 Thinking (the best\nsetting in Table 3) throughout ablation studies. We compare\nthree settings: (1)Actions Only; (2)Actions + Observations,\nwhich additionally includes screenshots; and (3)Actions +\nNarrative Summary(our default), which additionally com-\npresses each step into a concise natural language description.\n65\n70\n75\n80Recall (%)\n65\n70\n75\n80F1 (%)\nActions Only Actions + Obs. Actions + Narrative Summary\nFigure 4.Performance under different history representations.\nAs shown in Figure 4, narrative summary achieves the best\nperformance. Using actions alone performs the worst, con-\nfirming that observations provide important context for as-\nsessing subsequent actions. While incorporating screenshots\n(i.e.,+Obs) improves the detection performance, it is still\nless effective than narrative summaries and introduces sub-\nstantially higher latency ( 18s vs. 11s per step) as well as\nmuch higher token consumption (over 1K tokens per screen-\nshot vs. 41 tokens per summary). These results validate\nnarrative summaries as a practical history representation: it\nretains sufficient long-horizon context for alignment assess-\nment, while avoiding latency introduced by raw screenshots.\nLatency–Performance Tradeoff.We examine how the two-\nstage design balances detection performance and latency\non the same subset (Appendix C.2). We evaluate three\nconfigurations: (1)Fast Check Only, which relies solely on\nthe fast check; (2)Systematic Analysis Only, which applies\nsystematic analysis to every action; and (3)Fast Check +\nSystematic, the default two-stage setting.\nTable 4 shows that the two-stage design achieves a favorable\nbalance between detection performance and latency. Com-\npared to systematic analysis alone, the two-stage approach\nreduces latency while achieving the same performance, as it\nbypasses heavy reasoning for clearly aligned actions. Note\nthatthis latency reduction could be more pronounced in\nreal-world deployment: The balanced label distribution of\nMISACTBENCHcauses most of the actions to be routed to\nsystematic analysis, whereas real-world executions with pre-\ndominantly aligned actions would see higher bypass rates.\nConversely, relying solely on the fast check yields the low-\nest latency but suffers from substantially degraded precision\n(70.6%), indicating that lightweight screening alone tends to\nover-flag actions. These results confirm that the fast check\nis most effective as a conservative filter for clearly aligned\nactions, reserving systematic analysis for ambiguous cases.\nError Analysis.We inspect representative failure cases of\nDEACTION. First, well-disguised malicious instructions\ncan deceive the fast check and injection analysis, leading to\nmissed misaligned actions. Second, errors may stem from in-\nsufficient grounding capabilities of LLMs when interpreting\ncoordinate-based actions or predicting their outcomes. In ad-\n6\n\n===== PAGE 7 =====\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371\n372\n373\n374\n375\n376\n377\n378\n379\n380\n381\n382\n383\n384\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nTable 4.Latency–performance trade-off of detection configurations. The two-stage design balances detection performance and efficiency.\nPrecision Recall Acc F1 Latency (s)\nFast Check Only70.6 86.7 79.7 77.8 4.2\nSystematic Analysis Only85.8 75.1 84.6 80.1 13.1\nFast Check + Systematic85.4 75.1 84.5 79.9 11.3\ndition, even when all preceding analyses function correctly,\nthe guardrail may still produce erroneous judgments due\nto flawed intent-level reasoning, such as an overly narrow\nnotion of task relevance. Detailed examples are provided\nin Appendix E.4. Despite the strong overall performance\nof DEACTION, these failure modes highlight promising\ndirections for future work, such as more robust injection\ndetection, fine-grained action understanding, and accurate\nintent-level reasoning.\n5.2. Online Evaluation\nWhile offline evaluation measures detection accuracy on\npre-collected trajectories, it creates a gap with real-world\ndeployment by missing the full workflow, particularly the\niterative correction loop. We therefore evaluate DEACTION\nend-to-end in realistic interactive environments to assess its\nimpact on CUA adversarial robustness, task performance,\nand runtime latency.\nSettings.We conduct experiments under two settings:\n(1)Adversarial, using high-risk tasks from RedTeam-\nCUA (Liao et al., 2025) featuring indirect prompt injections;\nand (2)Benign, using standard tasks from OSWorld (Xie\net al., 2024). We experiment with three representative CUAs,\ncovering both closed-source and open-source agents from\ndifferent developers: computer use version of Claude Sonnet\n4.5 (Anthropic., 2025b), OpenAI CUA (OpenAI., 2025b),\nand OpenCUA-72B (Wang et al., 2025). We report At-\ntack Success Rate (ASR) and Utility under Attack (UA) for\nRedTeamCUA, and task Success Rate (SR) for OSWorld.\nWe compare against four representative baselines covering\ndiverse defense paradigms: (1)Defensive System Prompt\n(DSP)(Liao et al., 2025), which augments the agent’s\nsystem prompt with warnings about potential injections;\n(2)PromptArmor(Shi et al., 2025), an input guardrail\nthat identifies injected instructions and alerts accordingly;\n(3)Output guardrails:Task Shield(Jia et al., 2025) and\n(4)InferAct(Fang et al., 2025), which were introduced in\n§C.1. For DEACTIONand all output guardrails, we set the\nmaximum correction iterations to 3. Due to the high cost of\nonline evaluation, we only compare with other defenses on\nthe open-source agent, i.e., OpenCUA-72B. For all methods,\nwe use GPT-5.1 Instant as the backbone, which achieves the\nbest cost-performance balance in offline experiments. More\ndetails are in Appendix D.\nResults.As shown in Table 5, on RedTeamCUA, DEAC-\n0.0 2.5 5.0 7.5 10.0 12.5 15.0 17.5\nPer-step Guardrail Latency (s)\n0\n5\n10\n15\n20\n25\n30\n35Attack Success Rate (%)\nNo Defense\nDSP\nPromptArmor\nT ask Shield InferAct\nOurs\nNo Defense\nDSP\nPromptArmor\nT ask Shield\nInferAct\nOurs\nFigure 5.Comparison of attack success rate (ASR) versus per-step\nguardrail latency on RedTeamCUA. DEACTIONis Pareto-optimal,\nachieving the lowest ASR while incurring moderate latency.\nTIONreduces ASR by over 90% across all CUAs while im-\nproving task success rate under attack (UA), demonstrating\nits effectiveness against adversarial attacks and in correct-\ning misaligned actions. Importantly, this protection comes\nwithout sacrificing utility in benign environments: SR on\nOSWorld remains comparable or sometimes improved with\nDEACTION, indicating it does not over-constrain normal\nbehavior. This is essential for real-world, universally ap-\nplicable guardrails across environments with or without\nadversarial attacks.\nDEACTIONoutperforms baselines in both effectiveness and\nefficiency: As shown in Figure 5, DEACTIONachieves the\nlowest ASR with moderate latency. DSP and PromptArmor\nprovide limited ASR reduction and can degrade benign per-\nformance. Other output guardrails (InferAct and The Task\nShield) achieve lower ASR than DSP and PromptArmor\nbut incur substantially higher latency and hinder normal\ntask execution, due to their tendency to over-flag actions,\ntriggering excessive iterative correction.\nRuntime Analysis.We analyze the runtime behavior of\nDEACTIONin online experiments, with statistics averaged\nacross two settings and all CUAs. Detailed breakdowns\nare included in Appendix E.2. (1)Latency:With DEAC-\nTIONenabled, online execution incurs manageable over-\nhead: guardrail reasoning accounts for 25% of per-step\nexecution time ( 7.2s out of 28.1s on average). (2)Two-\nstage Routing:The two-stage design substantially reduces\nunnecessary computation. 45% of actions are approved\ndirectly by the fast check with an average latency of only\n3.2s, while the remaining actions are routed to systematic\nanalysis. This indicates that a large fraction of routine or\nclearly aligned actions bypass deep reasoning, allowing the\nguardrail to concentrate computational resources on ambigu-\n7\n\n===== PAGE 8 =====\n385\n386\n387\n388\n389\n390\n391\n392\n393\n394\n395\n396\n397\n398\n399\n400\n401\n402\n403\n404\n405\n406\n407\n408\n409\n410\n411\n412\n413\n414\n415\n416\n417\n418\n419\n420\n421\n422\n423\n424\n425\n426\n427\n428\n429\n430\n431\n432\n433\n434\n435\n436\n437\n438\n439\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nTable 5.Online evaluation results. We report Attack Success Rate (ASR) and Utility under Attack (UA) on RedTeamCUA, Success Rate\n(SR) on OSWorld. DEACTIONconsistently reduces ASR across different CUAs while maintaining benign utility and reasonable latency.\nAgent Defense Adversarial (RedTeamCUA) Benign (OSWorld)\nASR (%)↓UA (%)↑SR (%)↑\nClaude Sonnet 4.5 No Defense60.0 44.042.9\nDEACTION6.0 76.040.7\nOpenAI CUA No Defense42.0 82.0 26.0\nDEACTION4.0 84.0 30.7\nOpenCUA-72B\nNo Defense32.0 48.0 39.0\nDSP24.0 52.0 38.3\nPromptArmor26.0 44.0 35.2\nTask Shield22.0 58.0 36.6\nInferAct22.070.036.5\nDEACTION2.060.039.6\nous or higher-risk steps. (3)Guardrail Intervention:When\nDEACTIONflags an action as misaligned (16% of steps),\n78% are ultimately corrected to aligned behavior through\niterative feedback, with 62% corrected in a single revision.\nThis demonstrates that DEACTIONactively recovers aligned\nexecution rather than merely blocking progress.\nMore Cost-Efficient Deployment.While all prior exper-\niments use the same LLM backbone for all components\nin DEACTION, its modular design allows adopting differ-\nent LLMs for different components. Empirically, we ob-\nserve that replacing the fast check and narrative summarizer\nwith lighter models (e.g., GPT-5 mini) reduces cost by 65%\nwhile preserving comparable detection performance. In\ncontrast, the systematic analysis benefits substantially from\nstronger reasoning, and downgrading it leads to notable per-\nformance degradation. Online evaluation confirms that this\ncost-efficient configuration achieves similar effectiveness.\nDetails are in Appendix E.3.\n6. Related Work\nComputer-Use Agents.Computer-use agents (CUAs) auto-\nmate complex digital workflows by interacting with graph-\nical user interfaces (GUIs), translating high-level user in-\nstructions into low-level keyboard and mouse actions (Ope-\nnAI., 2025b; Anthropic., 2024c; Wang et al., 2025; Zheng\net al., 2024). Existing CUAs fall into two categories:LLM-\nadapted CUAsrepurpose general-purpose large language\nmodels (LLMs) with agentic scaffolding, leveraging their\nstrong reasoning and visual capabilities (Xie et al., 2024).\nIn contrast,specialized CUAs, such as OpenAI CUA (Ope-\nnAI., 2025b) and Claude Computer Use (Anthropic., 2024c),\nare explicitly designed for GUI interaction and incorporate\ntailored perception (Anthropic., 2024a; Qin et al., 2025;\nCheng et al., 2024; Gou et al., 2025), reasoning (OpenAI.,\n2025b; Wang et al., 2025), and computer-use tools (An-\nthropic., 2024c). While these agents have demonstrated\nimpressive performance on realistic benchmarks (Xie et al.,\n2024; Bonatti et al., 2025; Koh et al., 2024; Xue et al., 2025;\nRawles et al., 2024), their real-world deployment introduces\nchallenges. Unlike sandbox environments, real-world exe-\ncution requires strict alignment with user intent over long\nhorizons, where even minor deviations can lead to undesired\nside effects or safety risks.\nMisaligned Actions in Agent Execution.Despite rapid\nprogress, prior work has repeatedly observed that CUAs\nmay produce actions deviating from the user’s original in-\ntent (Srikumar et al., 2025; Jones et al., 2025). Such mis-\naligned actions arise from multiple sources (Chen et al.,\n2025a). A major class isenvironment-induced misalign-\nment, most notably indirect prompt injections, where agents\nfollow malicious content in web pages, documents or UI ele-\nments (Jones et al., 2025; Yang et al., 2025b; Boisvert et al.,\n2025; Kuntz et al., 2025; Evtimov et al., 2025). Agents may\nalso exhibitinternally arising misalignment, performing\nactions that cause unintended harm or side effects due to\nmisinterpreted task boundaries or erroneous reasoning (Ope-\nnAI., 2025b; Lynch et al., 2025; Greenblatt et al., 2024;\nKuntz et al., 2025; Naik et al., 2025). In addition, some\nmisaligned actions are non-malicious yet task-irrelevant,\nsuch as engaging in unjustified interactions with unrelated\napplications. Such misaligned actions are difficult to cap-\nture with safety-centric guardrails (Xiang et al., 2025; Hu\net al., 2025; Luo et al., 2025b; Zheng et al., 2025). While\nprior studies provide retrospective analysis of misaligned\nbehaviors (Fronsdal et al., 2025; Meng et al., 2025), prac-\ntical runtime guardrails that can detect a broad range of\nmisaligned actions in CUA deployment remain lacking.\n7. Conclusion\nIn this work, we make the first effort to define and study\nmisaligned action detection in CUAs, a practical yet under-\nexplored problem for reliable CUA deployment. We identify\n8\n\n===== PAGE 9 =====\n440\n441\n442\n443\n444\n445\n446\n447\n448\n449\n450\n451\n452\n453\n454\n455\n456\n457\n458\n459\n460\n461\n462\n463\n464\n465\n466\n467\n468\n469\n470\n471\n472\n473\n474\n475\n476\n477\n478\n479\n480\n481\n482\n483\n484\n485\n486\n487\n488\n489\n490\n491\n492\n493\n494\nDetecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\nthree categories of misaligned actions in CUAs and intro-\nduce MISACTBENCH, a comprehensive benchmark with\nhuman-annotated action-level labels. We also propose DE-\nACTION, a practical and universal guardrail that proactively\ndetects misaligned actions before execution and corrects\nthem through iterative feedback. Experiments demonstrate\nthat DEACTIONimproves misaligned action detection, re-\nduces attack success rate under adversarial settings, and\npreserves task success rate in benign environments, con-\nfirming its practicality as a plug-and-play protection for\nreal-world CUA deployment.\nImpact Statement\nThis paper studies misaligned action detection in computer-\nuse agents and proposes a runtime guardrail to improve\naction alignment during agent execution. The primary goal\nof this work is to enhance the reliability and robustness of\ncomputer-use agents operating in open-ended, real-world\ncomputer environments.\nBy detecting and correcting misaligned actions before exe-\ncution, this work aims to reduce safety risks, unnecessary\nside effects, and execution-time failures that may arise when\nagents interact with complex user interfaces. As such, the\nproposed benchmark and guardrail have the potential to\nsupport safer and more reliable deployment of computer-\nuse agents in practical applications. Overall, we believe\nthis work contributes positively to the development of more\ntrustworthy and controllable machine learning systems.\nReferences\nAnthropic. Developing a computer use model.,\n2024a. URL https://www.anthropic.com/\nnews/developing-computer-use.\nAnthropic. Introducing computer use, a new\nclaude 3.5 sonnet, and claude 3.5 haiku, 2024b.\nURL https://www.anthropic.com/news/\n3-5-models-and-computer-use.\nAnthropic. Claude computer use (beta), 2024c. URL\nhttps://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/\nagents-and-tools/computer-use.\nAnthropic. Claude 3.7 sonnet system card,\n2025a. URL https://assets.anthropic.\ncom/m/785e231869ea8b3b/original/\nclaude-3-7-sonnet-system-card.pdf.\nAnthropic. Introducing claude sonnet 4.5., 2025b.\nURL https://www.anthropic.com/news/\nclaude-sonnet-4-5.\nBoisvert, L., Bansal, M., Evuru, C. K. R., Huang, G., Puri,","numLines":500,"startLine":800,"totalLines":3208}}}
