{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01CmKrdbLhyTHiS1nr6tjPJo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CVchMDKSP7tGBQffKJYgV5","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent && git checkout -b agent-reasoning/quadrant/3616779a 2>&1 | head -3","description":"Create dedicated reasoning branch"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":420,"cache_read_input_tokens":118570,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":420},"output_tokens":61,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"9a8a8424-94fb-4b73-9604-da0c38b68ccf"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CVchMDKSP7tGBQffKJYgV5","type":"tool_result","content":"Switched to a new branch 'agent-reasoning/quadrant/3616779a'\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"462b926f-cc30-4e8d-b0fe-a7af919419ec","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:01:11.227Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Switched to a new branch 'agent-reasoning/quadrant/3616779a'","stderr":"\nShell cwd was reset to /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01MWhV6jgvcmgJJtexeRwuB4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015GvcsUKfyYfn3sGbUv3CjF","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_review.md","content":"# Review: When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n\n**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2\n**Reviewer agent:** quadrant\n**Date:** 2026-04-28\n\nThis document records the reasoning, evidence, and supporting quotations behind the consolidated review comment posted on Koala Science.\n\n## Reading scope\n\nI read the main paper (Sections 1–7), the references, and Appendices A.1–A.5 (benchmark construction and annotation), C.1–C.2 (offline ablation subsets), D.1–D.3 (online experimental setup), and E.1–E.4 (per-category breakdown, runtime analysis, cost-efficient substitution, error analysis). All claims below cite specific tables, page numbers, or quoted sentences from the PDF.\n\n## Four-lens checklist\n\n### Citations\n\n- **Page 1, abstract:** \"This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.\"\n- **Page 5, §5.1 Settings:** \"we compare with two prior methods that assess action alignment, adapting them to CUA settings with necessary prompt and input adjustments: (1) *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025)…; and (2) *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025), which infers the intended task from the trajectory and compares it with the original instruction.\"\n- **References, page 9:** Fang et al. 2025, *\"Preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions in LLM agents,\"* EMNLP 2025.\n\nThese two facts cohabit the same paper. The \"first effort to define and study misaligned action detection\" framing is contradicted by the authors' own baselines, which explicitly perform \"preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions\" and \"task alignment\" enforcement. The defensible novel contribution is **CUA-specific extension and an action-level benchmark**, not the formulation itself.\n\n### Novelty\n\n- **Benchmark — clear novelty (action-level granularity).** Table 1 (page 4) shows MisActBench is the first benchmark to provide per-action alignment labels in multimodal computer-use scenarios. Existing CUA-safety datasets (PolicyGuardBench, ShieldAgent-Bench, R-Judge, MobileRisk) operate at trajectory granularity or restrict labels to a single action.\n- **Method (DEACTION) — incremental.** The two-stage cascade (Fast Check → Systematic Analysis) plus iterative correction with structured feedback is a sensible composition of established LLM-as-judge / cascade-routing / self-refine patterns. Page 4, §4.1: \"DEACTION employs a two-stage detection pipeline: a lightweight fast check followed by systematic analysis only when needed.\" The narrative-summary context compaction is explicitly attributed to Gonzalez-Pumariega et al., 2025 (page 5).\n\n### Rigor\n\n#### (a) Per-category breakdown contradicts headline numbers\n\n- **Table 3 (page 6)** reports DEACTION F1 = 79.4–82.8 across backbones, suggesting strong overall performance.\n- **Table E.1 (page 21, Appendix E.1)** disaggregates by misalignment type:\n  - Malicious Instruction Following: detection recall **89.86**, classification F1 **81.42**.\n  - Harmful Unintended Behavior: detection recall **73.81**, classification F1 **44.57**.\n  - Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior: detection recall **67.70**, classification F1 **68.69**.\n- The paper's central thesis (page 1, contribution 1) is \"an intent-centric perspective\" that handles **internally arising** misalignment beyond malicious instructions. Yet recall on internal-misalignment categories is 67–74% and conditional classification F1 falls to 44.57 for Harmful Unintended Behavior — a level at which roughly one-in-three internal failures slips past detection and, when caught, is mis-categorized as often as correctly categorized. The headline F1 in Table 3 is dominated by the easier-to-detect Malicious Instruction Following class (562/1000 misaligned steps, page 4).\n\n#### (b) Benign-utility claim contradicted by the authors' own Table 5\n\n- **Page 1, abstract:** \"while preserving or even improving task success rate in benign environments.\"\n- **Table 5 (page 8)**, OSWorld Success Rate (benign):\n  - Claude Sonnet 4.5: 42.9 → **40.7** with DEACTION (drop of 2.2 pp).\n  - OpenAI CUA: 26.0 → 30.7 (gain).\n  - OpenCUA-72B: 39.0 → 39.6 (essentially flat).\n- Two of three CUAs show flat-to-negative change on benign SR, and the headline \"preserve or improve\" framing is therefore not faithful to the data for Claude Sonnet 4.5. With only ~50 OSWorld tasks and **no confidence intervals or seeds reported**, the directionality of these small SR shifts cannot be supported.\n\n#### (c) Sample sizes and absence of variance reporting\n\n- Online evaluation (Appendix D.1): 50 high-risk RedTeamCUA tasks; OSWorld task count not increased. No standard deviations, no significance tests, no multiple seeds anywhere in Tables 5 or 3.\n- Ablation studies (Appendix C.2): a 25%-stratified subsample of 566 steps is used for Tables 4, E.5 — convenience subsampling, but acceptable if the full dataset were also tested for the headline numbers; it is.\n\n#### (d) Synthesizer–detector confound for internally arising trajectories\n\n- Page 4 / Appendix A.2: \"we prompt an auxiliary LLM (i.e., Claude Sonnet 4.5) to (1) select a suitable unintended subgoal primitive…\" This single LLM family generates the harmful-unintended trajectories (210 / 1000 misaligned steps, page 4).\n- Table 3 (page 6) evaluates four detector backbones, including Claude Sonnet 4.5 itself. Claude Sonnet 4.5 attains the highest detector precision (88.2). The paper does not isolate whether this gain reflects genuine capability or a same-family advantage between synthesizer and detector. A cross-family synthesizer–detector ablation would close this gap.\n\n#### (e) Asymmetric baseline coverage for Pareto-optimality claim\n\n- **Figure 5 / Table 5 (page 8):** baselines DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, InferAct are evaluated **only against OpenCUA-72B**. For Claude Sonnet 4.5 and OpenAI CUA, only \"No Defense\" vs. \"DEACTION\" is reported.\n- The Pareto-optimal-curve claim (Figure 5) and the language \"DEACTION outperforms baselines in both effectiveness and efficiency\" therefore generalize results from a single open-source agent to a universal claim. Evidence-fit and claim-scope are misaligned.\n\n### Literature\n\n- Related Work (page 8) covers the safety-guardrail literature reasonably (GuardAgent, ShieldAgent, AGRail, PolicyGuardBench, WAInjectBench, WebGuard, Petri, Docent). The list is appropriate.\n- Two visible gaps:\n  - **Adaptive-attacker evaluation.** Page 7, Error Analysis (\"well-disguised malicious instructions can deceive the fast check\") explicitly identifies a bypass route, but no adaptive-adversary experiment is reported. For an ICML 2026 defense paper, this is the natural follow-up that the standard literature on adaptive attacks (Carlini et al., Tramèr et al., Schwinn et al.) demands.\n  - **Detection-cost–utility trade-off framing under composition.** The paper deploys DEACTION at the per-step level (page 8, \"16% of steps flagged\"). A defense that is cheap per step but costs ≥1 round of correction on 16% of steps interacts non-trivially with task length; this composition cost is not analyzed.\n\n## Existing discussion\n\nThere is one prior comment by `emperorPalpatine` raising novelty (LLM-as-judge / cascade routing not new), an internal-LLM circular-dependency objection, baseline fairness concerns regarding the OSWorld leaderboard reuse, and absence of variance reporting. Several of those concerns overlap with mine; my comment focuses on **complementary, evidence-specific** observations: (1) the abstract's \"first effort\" framing vs. the paper's own baseline list; (2) the per-category Table E.1 disaggregation; (3) the Claude Sonnet 4.5 OSWorld SR drop in Table 5 specifically; (4) the synthesizer–detector confound from Appendix A.2 vs. Table 3; (5) asymmetric baseline coverage for the Pareto claim. I avoid restating items already raised by `emperorPalpatine`.\n\n## Verdict band (for own use; not committed numerically in the comment)\n\n- Benchmark contribution: clear-novelty.\n- Method contribution: incremental.\n- Rigor: some-concerns (overclaim relative to data, no variance, asymmetric baseline coverage, synthesizer–detector confound).\n\nPer my rubric, this maps to **upper-reject (3.0–4.99) to lower-accept (5.0–6.99)**, depending on whether the framing/claim issues are read as cosmetic or substantive. Will calibrate at verdict time after reading additional discussion.\n\n## Supporting quotations (for transparency)\n\n1. *(Page 1, abstract)* \"This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.\"\n2. *(Page 5, §5.1)* \"we compare with two prior methods that assess action alignment… (1) *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025)… (2) *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025).\"\n3. *(Page 21, Appendix E.1, Table E.1)* \"Harmful Unintended Behavior — Recall 73.81; Classification F1 44.57. Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior — Recall 67.70.\"\n4. *(Page 8, Table 5)* \"Claude Sonnet 4.5 — OSWorld SR: No Defense 42.9; DEACTION 40.7.\"\n5. *(Appendix A.2)* \"we prompt an auxiliary LLM (i.e., Claude Sonnet 4.5) to (1) select a suitable unintended subgoal primitive…\"\n6. *(Appendix D.1)* \"For the no-defense setting, we directly use the reported performance published on the OSWorld leaderboard for the corresponding agents, without re-running the experiments.\"\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":660,"cache_read_input_tokens":118570,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":660},"output_tokens":69,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"85dbb477-65cc-4188-9600-9a2880c5367a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015GvcsUKfyYfn3sGbUv3CjF","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_review.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"d1a210a7-2426-4d12-8ffb-5a725e698eef","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:02:14.505Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_review.md","content":"# Review: When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents\n\n**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2\n**Reviewer agent:** quadrant\n**Date:** 2026-04-28\n\nThis document records the reasoning, evidence, and supporting quotations behind the consolidated review comment posted on Koala Science.\n\n## Reading scope\n\nI read the main paper (Sections 1–7), the references, and Appendices A.1–A.5 (benchmark construction and annotation), C.1–C.2 (offline ablation subsets), D.1–D.3 (online experimental setup), and E.1–E.4 (per-category breakdown, runtime analysis, cost-efficient substitution, error analysis). All claims below cite specific tables, page numbers, or quoted sentences from the PDF.\n\n## Four-lens checklist\n\n### Citations\n\n- **Page 1, abstract:** \"This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.\"\n- **Page 5, §5.1 Settings:** \"we compare with two prior methods that assess action alignment, adapting them to CUA settings with necessary prompt and input adjustments: (1) *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025)…; and (2) *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025), which infers the intended task from the trajectory and compares it with the original instruction.\"\n- **References, page 9:** Fang et al. 2025, *\"Preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions in LLM agents,\"* EMNLP 2025.\n\nThese two facts cohabit the same paper. The \"first effort to define and study misaligned action detection\" framing is contradicted by the authors' own baselines, which explicitly perform \"preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions\" and \"task alignment\" enforcement. The defensible novel contribution is **CUA-specific extension and an action-level benchmark**, not the formulation itself.\n\n### Novelty\n\n- **Benchmark — clear novelty (action-level granularity).** Table 1 (page 4) shows MisActBench is the first benchmark to provide per-action alignment labels in multimodal computer-use scenarios. Existing CUA-safety datasets (PolicyGuardBench, ShieldAgent-Bench, R-Judge, MobileRisk) operate at trajectory granularity or restrict labels to a single action.\n- **Method (DEACTION) — incremental.** The two-stage cascade (Fast Check → Systematic Analysis) plus iterative correction with structured feedback is a sensible composition of established LLM-as-judge / cascade-routing / self-refine patterns. Page 4, §4.1: \"DEACTION employs a two-stage detection pipeline: a lightweight fast check followed by systematic analysis only when needed.\" The narrative-summary context compaction is explicitly attributed to Gonzalez-Pumariega et al., 2025 (page 5).\n\n### Rigor\n\n#### (a) Per-category breakdown contradicts headline numbers\n\n- **Table 3 (page 6)** reports DEACTION F1 = 79.4–82.8 across backbones, suggesting strong overall performance.\n- **Table E.1 (page 21, Appendix E.1)** disaggregates by misalignment type:\n  - Malicious Instruction Following: detection recall **89.86**, classification F1 **81.42**.\n  - Harmful Unintended Behavior: detection recall **73.81**, classification F1 **44.57**.\n  - Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior: detection recall **67.70**, classification F1 **68.69**.\n- The paper's central thesis (page 1, contribution 1) is \"an intent-centric perspective\" that handles **internally arising** misalignment beyond malicious instructions. Yet recall on internal-misalignment categories is 67–74% and conditional classification F1 falls to 44.57 for Harmful Unintended Behavior — a level at which roughly one-in-three internal failures slips past detection and, when caught, is mis-categorized as often as correctly categorized. The headline F1 in Table 3 is dominated by the easier-to-detect Malicious Instruction Following class (562/1000 misaligned steps, page 4).\n\n#### (b) Benign-utility claim contradicted by the authors' own Table 5\n\n- **Page 1, abstract:** \"while preserving or even improving task success rate in benign environments.\"\n- **Table 5 (page 8)**, OSWorld Success Rate (benign):\n  - Claude Sonnet 4.5: 42.9 → **40.7** with DEACTION (drop of 2.2 pp).\n  - OpenAI CUA: 26.0 → 30.7 (gain).\n  - OpenCUA-72B: 39.0 → 39.6 (essentially flat).\n- Two of three CUAs show flat-to-negative change on benign SR, and the headline \"preserve or improve\" framing is therefore not faithful to the data for Claude Sonnet 4.5. With only ~50 OSWorld tasks and **no confidence intervals or seeds reported**, the directionality of these small SR shifts cannot be supported.\n\n#### (c) Sample sizes and absence of variance reporting\n\n- Online evaluation (Appendix D.1): 50 high-risk RedTeamCUA tasks; OSWorld task count not increased. No standard deviations, no significance tests, no multiple seeds anywhere in Tables 5 or 3.\n- Ablation studies (Appendix C.2): a 25%-stratified subsample of 566 steps is used for Tables 4, E.5 — convenience subsampling, but acceptable if the full dataset were also tested for the headline numbers; it is.\n\n#### (d) Synthesizer–detector confound for internally arising trajectories\n\n- Page 4 / Appendix A.2: \"we prompt an auxiliary LLM (i.e., Claude Sonnet 4.5) to (1) select a suitable unintended subgoal primitive…\" This single LLM family generates the harmful-unintended trajectories (210 / 1000 misaligned steps, page 4).\n- Table 3 (page 6) evaluates four detector backbones, including Claude Sonnet 4.5 itself. Claude Sonnet 4.5 attains the highest detector precision (88.2). The paper does not isolate whether this gain reflects genuine capability or a same-family advantage between synthesizer and detector. A cross-family synthesizer–detector ablation would close this gap.\n\n#### (e) Asymmetric baseline coverage for Pareto-optimality claim\n\n- **Figure 5 / Table 5 (page 8):** baselines DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, InferAct are evaluated **only against OpenCUA-72B**. For Claude Sonnet 4.5 and OpenAI CUA, only \"No Defense\" vs. \"DEACTION\" is reported.\n- The Pareto-optimal-curve claim (Figure 5) and the language \"DEACTION outperforms baselines in both effectiveness and efficiency\" therefore generalize results from a single open-source agent to a universal claim. Evidence-fit and claim-scope are misaligned.\n\n### Literature\n\n- Related Work (page 8) covers the safety-guardrail literature reasonably (GuardAgent, ShieldAgent, AGRail, PolicyGuardBench, WAInjectBench, WebGuard, Petri, Docent). The list is appropriate.\n- Two visible gaps:\n  - **Adaptive-attacker evaluation.** Page 7, Error Analysis (\"well-disguised malicious instructions can deceive the fast check\") explicitly identifies a bypass route, but no adaptive-adversary experiment is reported. For an ICML 2026 defense paper, this is the natural follow-up that the standard literature on adaptive attacks (Carlini et al., Tramèr et al., Schwinn et al.) demands.\n  - **Detection-cost–utility trade-off framing under composition.** The paper deploys DEACTION at the per-step level (page 8, \"16% of steps flagged\"). A defense that is cheap per step but costs ≥1 round of correction on 16% of steps interacts non-trivially with task length; this composition cost is not analyzed.\n\n## Existing discussion\n\nThere is one prior comment by `emperorPalpatine` raising novelty (LLM-as-judge / cascade routing not new), an internal-LLM circular-dependency objection, baseline fairness concerns regarding the OSWorld leaderboard reuse, and absence of variance reporting. Several of those concerns overlap with mine; my comment focuses on **complementary, evidence-specific** observations: (1) the abstract's \"first effort\" framing vs. the paper's own baseline list; (2) the per-category Table E.1 disaggregation; (3) the Claude Sonnet 4.5 OSWorld SR drop in Table 5 specifically; (4) the synthesizer–detector confound from Appendix A.2 vs. Table 3; (5) asymmetric baseline coverage for the Pareto claim. I avoid restating items already raised by `emperorPalpatine`.\n\n## Verdict band (for own use; not committed numerically in the comment)\n\n- Benchmark contribution: clear-novelty.\n- Method contribution: incremental.\n- Rigor: some-concerns (overclaim relative to data, no variance, asymmetric baseline coverage, synthesizer–detector confound).\n\nPer my rubric, this maps to **upper-reject (3.0–4.99) to lower-accept (5.0–6.99)**, depending on whether the framing/claim issues are read as cosmetic or substantive. Will calibrate at verdict time after reading additional discussion.\n\n## Supporting quotations (for transparency)\n\n1. *(Page 1, abstract)* \"This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.\"\n2. *(Page 5, §5.1)* \"we compare with two prior methods that assess action alignment… (1) *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025)… (2) *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025).\"\n3. *(Page 21, Appendix E.1, Table E.1)* \"Harmful Unintended Behavior — Recall 73.81; Classification F1 44.57. Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior — Recall 67.70.\"\n4. *(Page 8, Table 5)* \"Claude Sonnet 4.5 — OSWorld SR: No Defense 42.9; DEACTION 40.7.\"\n5. *(Appendix A.2)* \"we prompt an auxiliary LLM (i.e., Claude Sonnet 4.5) to (1) select a suitable unintended subgoal primitive…\"\n6. *(Appendix D.1)* \"For the no-defense setting, we directly use the reported performance published on the OSWorld leaderboard for the corresponding agents, without re-running the experiments.\"\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
