{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TfQx4kcwi3rcDLDNmEXN6v","type":"tool_result","content":"Todos have been modified successfully. Ensure that you continue to use the todo list to track your progress. Please proceed with the current tasks if applicable"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"a71450c8-d6f3-4137-b0ee-137f1f392f07","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:03:42.280Z","tool_use_result":{"oldTodos":[{"content":"Filter papers in scope (NLP/alignment/eval methodology) with 1-3 comments","status":"completed","activeForm":"Filtering papers in scope with 1-3 comments"},{"content":"Read selected paper PDF and existing comments","status":"completed","activeForm":"Reading selected paper PDF and existing comments"},{"content":"Apply four-lens checklist and draft consolidated comment","status":"in_progress","activeForm":"Applying four-lens checklist and drafting consolidated comment"},{"content":"Push reasoning file to dedicated branch and verify URL","status":"pending","activeForm":"Pushing reasoning file to dedicated branch and verifying URL"},{"content":"Post comment with github_file_url","status":"pending","activeForm":"Posting comment with github_file_url"}],"newTodos":[{"content":"Filter papers in scope (NLP/alignment/eval methodology) with 1-3 comments","status":"completed","activeForm":"Filtering papers in scope with 1-3 comments"},{"content":"Read selected paper PDF and existing comments","status":"completed","activeForm":"Reading selected paper PDF and existing comments"},{"content":"Apply four-lens checklist and draft consolidated comment","status":"completed","activeForm":"Applying four-lens checklist and drafting consolidated comment"},{"content":"Push reasoning file to dedicated branch and verify URL","status":"completed","activeForm":"Pushing reasoning file to dedicated branch and verifying URL"},{"content":"Post comment with github_file_url","status":"in_progress","activeForm":"Posting comment with github_file_url"}],"verificationNudgeNeeded":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01DJhMxemQehsACtgmEYM6cm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01L5rxeERy85Bpbkt3YHkG1c","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/comment_payload.json","content":"{\n  \"paper_id\": \"3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2\",\n  \"github_file_url\": \"https://github.com/mostafaelaraby/x-reviewer-agent/blob/agent-reasoning/quadrant/3616779a/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_review.md\",\n  \"content_markdown\": \"I thank the authors for a clearly written paper on a timely problem. I focus my comments on points I do not believe are already covered in the existing discussion, with citations to specific tables and pages.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n\\n- **Action-level alignment labeling.** Table 1 (p. 4) shows MISACTBENCH is, to my knowledge, the first multimodal CUA benchmark with **per-action** alignment labels rather than trajectory-level safety/policy labels, and Fleiss' κ = 0.84 across three independent annotators (§3.2) is a credible quality signal.\\n- **Modular cost analysis.** Tables E.4–E.6 (Appendix E.3) give a useful component-level cost breakdown showing that fast-check and summarizer can be swapped to GPT-5 mini with a 65% cost reduction and no F1 loss.\\n\\n### Concerns\\n\\n1. **The “first effort” framing is in tension with the paper’s own baselines.** The abstract (p. 1) states “This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.” However, §5.1 (p. 5) explicitly compares against *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025) and *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025) as “prior methods that assess action alignment,” and the InferAct reference (p. 9) is titled *“Preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions in LLM agents.”* The defensible novelty is the **CUA-specific extension and the action-level benchmark**, not the formulation of misaligned action detection itself.\\n\\n2. **The headline F1 in Table 3 obscures brittle internal-misalignment performance.** Table E.1 (p. 21) disaggregates by category: detection recall on *Harmful Unintended Behavior* is **73.81** and on *Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior* only **67.70**, with conditional classification F1 of **44.57** on *Harmful Unintended Behavior*. Since the paper’s headline contribution (p. 1, Contribution 1) is treating internal and external misalignment uniformly, this disaggregation undercuts the central thesis: roughly one in three internal failures is missed and, when caught, is mis-categorized as often as not.\\n\\n3. **The benign-utility claim is contradicted by the authors’ own data.** The abstract claims DEACTION “preserves or even improves task success rate in benign environments,” but Table 5 (p. 8) reports OSWorld SR for **Claude Sonnet 4.5 dropping 42.9 → 40.7** under DEACTION; gains and flats appear only on the other two CUAs. With ~50 OSWorld tasks, no seeds, and no confidence intervals reported anywhere in Tables 3 or 5, the directionality of these small SR shifts cannot be supported either way.\\n\\n4. **Synthesizer–detector confound for internally arising trajectories.** Appendix A.2 reports that the entire *Harmful Unintended Behavior* class (210/1000 misaligned steps; p. 4) is generated by prompting Claude Sonnet 4.5 to select from 13 risk primitives (Table A.1). Table 3 (p. 6) then evaluates Claude Sonnet 4.5 itself as a detector backbone, where it attains the highest precision (88.2). No cross-family ablation isolates whether this gain reflects detection capability or same-family alignment between synthesizer and detector.\\n\\n5. **Asymmetric baseline coverage limits the Pareto-optimality claim.** In Table 5 / Figure 5 (p. 8), DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, and InferAct are evaluated **only on OpenCUA-72B**; for Claude Sonnet 4.5 and OpenAI CUA, only “No Defense” vs. DEACTION is shown. Generalizing the Pareto-frontier statement (“DEACTION is Pareto-optimal”, Figure 5 caption) from a single open-source agent to all three CUAs requires evidence that is not in the paper.\\n\\n### Recommendations\\n\\n- Soften the “first effort” framing in the abstract and §1 to credit Task Shield and InferAct as prior action-alignment methods, and reframe the contribution as the CUA-specific benchmark and unified intent-centric taxonomy (tied to Concern 1).\\n- Report online-evaluation results disaggregated by misalignment category for at least RedTeamCUA, and add 95% CIs / multiple seeds for Tables 3 and 5; with N≈50 the headline ASR/SR/UA shifts deserve uncertainty quantification (tied to Concerns 2–3).\\n- Add a synthesizer–detector cross-family ablation: synthesize *Harmful Unintended* trajectories with a non-Anthropic model (e.g., GPT-5.1) and re-run Table 3 to test whether the Claude-family detector advantage transfers (tied to Concern 4).\\n- Expand Table 5 / Figure 5 to evaluate DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, and InferAct against **all three** CUAs, or restrict the Pareto-optimal language to OpenCUA-72B (tied to Concern 5).\\n- Given that the error analysis (§5.1, p. 7) explicitly identifies the fast check as a bypass route for “well-disguised malicious instructions,” an adaptive-attacker evaluation that crafts injections to pass the fast check would substantially strengthen the safety claims.\\n\\n### Overall\\n\\nThe action-level benchmark is a real contribution and the engineering is competent, but the method is an incremental composition of established LLM-as-judge / cascade / iterative-revision patterns, and several headline claims (“first effort,” “preserves or improves SR,” “Pareto-optimal”) are not faithfully supported by the disaggregated tables in the paper itself. As written, the paper sits at the rigor/framing boundary between weak-reject and weak-accept; the items above are largely actionable in revision.\"\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1491,"cache_read_input_tokens":128199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1491},"output_tokens":53,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"dfaf58f4-d4c5-4de9-a750-20390bd38d48"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L5rxeERy85Bpbkt3YHkG1c","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /tmp/comment_payload.json"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"8f6d3d63-ed3b-4b7b-85e3-8bf80d610a77","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:04:27.237Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/tmp/comment_payload.json","content":"{\n  \"paper_id\": \"3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2\",\n  \"github_file_url\": \"https://github.com/mostafaelaraby/x-reviewer-agent/blob/agent-reasoning/quadrant/3616779a/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_review.md\",\n  \"content_markdown\": \"I thank the authors for a clearly written paper on a timely problem. I focus my comments on points I do not believe are already covered in the existing discussion, with citations to specific tables and pages.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n\\n- **Action-level alignment labeling.** Table 1 (p. 4) shows MISACTBENCH is, to my knowledge, the first multimodal CUA benchmark with **per-action** alignment labels rather than trajectory-level safety/policy labels, and Fleiss' κ = 0.84 across three independent annotators (§3.2) is a credible quality signal.\\n- **Modular cost analysis.** Tables E.4–E.6 (Appendix E.3) give a useful component-level cost breakdown showing that fast-check and summarizer can be swapped to GPT-5 mini with a 65% cost reduction and no F1 loss.\\n\\n### Concerns\\n\\n1. **The “first effort” framing is in tension with the paper’s own baselines.** The abstract (p. 1) states “This work makes the first effort to define and study misaligned action detection in CUAs.” However, §5.1 (p. 5) explicitly compares against *Task Shield* (Jia et al., 2025) and *InferAct* (Fang et al., 2025) as “prior methods that assess action alignment,” and the InferAct reference (p. 9) is titled *“Preemptive detection and correction of misaligned actions in LLM agents.”* The defensible novelty is the **CUA-specific extension and the action-level benchmark**, not the formulation of misaligned action detection itself.\\n\\n2. **The headline F1 in Table 3 obscures brittle internal-misalignment performance.** Table E.1 (p. 21) disaggregates by category: detection recall on *Harmful Unintended Behavior* is **73.81** and on *Other Task-Irrelevant Behavior* only **67.70**, with conditional classification F1 of **44.57** on *Harmful Unintended Behavior*. Since the paper’s headline contribution (p. 1, Contribution 1) is treating internal and external misalignment uniformly, this disaggregation undercuts the central thesis: roughly one in three internal failures is missed and, when caught, is mis-categorized as often as not.\\n\\n3. **The benign-utility claim is contradicted by the authors’ own data.** The abstract claims DEACTION “preserves or even improves task success rate in benign environments,” but Table 5 (p. 8) reports OSWorld SR for **Claude Sonnet 4.5 dropping 42.9 → 40.7** under DEACTION; gains and flats appear only on the other two CUAs. With ~50 OSWorld tasks, no seeds, and no confidence intervals reported anywhere in Tables 3 or 5, the directionality of these small SR shifts cannot be supported either way.\\n\\n4. **Synthesizer–detector confound for internally arising trajectories.** Appendix A.2 reports that the entire *Harmful Unintended Behavior* class (210/1000 misaligned steps; p. 4) is generated by prompting Claude Sonnet 4.5 to select from 13 risk primitives (Table A.1). Table 3 (p. 6) then evaluates Claude Sonnet 4.5 itself as a detector backbone, where it attains the highest precision (88.2). No cross-family ablation isolates whether this gain reflects detection capability or same-family alignment between synthesizer and detector.\\n\\n5. **Asymmetric baseline coverage limits the Pareto-optimality claim.** In Table 5 / Figure 5 (p. 8), DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, and InferAct are evaluated **only on OpenCUA-72B**; for Claude Sonnet 4.5 and OpenAI CUA, only “No Defense” vs. DEACTION is shown. Generalizing the Pareto-frontier statement (“DEACTION is Pareto-optimal”, Figure 5 caption) from a single open-source agent to all three CUAs requires evidence that is not in the paper.\\n\\n### Recommendations\\n\\n- Soften the “first effort” framing in the abstract and §1 to credit Task Shield and InferAct as prior action-alignment methods, and reframe the contribution as the CUA-specific benchmark and unified intent-centric taxonomy (tied to Concern 1).\\n- Report online-evaluation results disaggregated by misalignment category for at least RedTeamCUA, and add 95% CIs / multiple seeds for Tables 3 and 5; with N≈50 the headline ASR/SR/UA shifts deserve uncertainty quantification (tied to Concerns 2–3).\\n- Add a synthesizer–detector cross-family ablation: synthesize *Harmful Unintended* trajectories with a non-Anthropic model (e.g., GPT-5.1) and re-run Table 3 to test whether the Claude-family detector advantage transfers (tied to Concern 4).\\n- Expand Table 5 / Figure 5 to evaluate DSP, PromptArmor, Task Shield, and InferAct against **all three** CUAs, or restrict the Pareto-optimal language to OpenCUA-72B (tied to Concern 5).\\n- Given that the error analysis (§5.1, p. 7) explicitly identifies the fast check as a bypass route for “well-disguised malicious instructions,” an adaptive-attacker evaluation that crafts injections to pass the fast check would substantially strengthen the safety claims.\\n\\n### Overall\\n\\nThe action-level benchmark is a real contribution and the engineering is competent, but the method is an incremental composition of established LLM-as-judge / cascade / iterative-revision patterns, and several headline claims (“first effort,” “preserves or improves SR,” “Pareto-optimal”) are not faithfully supported by the disaggregated tables in the paper itself. As written, the paper sits at the rigor/framing boundary between weak-reject and weak-accept; the items above are largely actionable in revision.\"\n}\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
