{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_018KRLzTqLduuYYXM7SD899B","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011uw7CJ5G7hhsQk7Az7UuSH","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\nimport json\nwith open('/tmp/nlp_now.json') as f:\n    p = next(p for p in json.load(f) if p['id'].startswith('2d52017e'))\nprint('FULL_ID:', p['id']); print('TITLE:', p['title']); print('PDF:', p['pdf_url']); print('ARXIV:', p['arxiv_id']); print()\nprint(p['abstract'])\nEOF","description":"Get neural topic model paper details"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1873,"cache_read_input_tokens":135172,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1873},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"0a09c55a-e88e-4b33-8eb3-2a2c3c6b7f00"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011uw7CJ5G7hhsQk7Az7UuSH","type":"tool_result","content":"FULL_ID: 2d52017e-6a59-4b49-a189-d38d72724b3d\nTITLE: Improving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nPDF: /storage/pdfs/2d52017e-6a59-4b49-a189-d38d72724b3d.pdf\nARXIV: 2602.17907\n\nTraditional neural topic models are typically optimized by reconstructing the document's Bag-of-Words (BoW) representations, overlooking contextual information and struggling with data sparsity. In this work, we propose a novel approach to construct semantically-grounded soft label targets using Language Models (LMs) by projecting the next token probabilities, conditioned on a specialized prompt, onto a pre-defined vocabulary to obtain contextually enriched supervision signals. By training the topic models to reconstruct the soft labels using the LM hidden states, our method produces higher-quality topics that are more closely aligned with the underlying thematic structure of the corpus. Experiments on three datasets show that our method achieves substantial improvements in topic coherence, purity over existing baselines. Additionally, we also introduce a retrieval-based metric, which shows that our approach significantly outperforms existing methods in identifying semantically similar documents, highlighting its effectiveness for retrieval-oriented applications.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"7f6c9aef-26ca-4ec3-8065-f590370a844a","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:05:12.582Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"FULL_ID: 2d52017e-6a59-4b49-a189-d38d72724b3d\nTITLE: Improving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nPDF: /storage/pdfs/2d52017e-6a59-4b49-a189-d38d72724b3d.pdf\nARXIV: 2602.17907\n\nTraditional neural topic models are typically optimized by reconstructing the document's Bag-of-Words (BoW) representations, overlooking contextual information and struggling with data sparsity. In this work, we propose a novel approach to construct semantically-grounded soft label targets using Language Models (LMs) by projecting the next token probabilities, conditioned on a specialized prompt, onto a pre-defined vocabulary to obtain contextually enriched supervision signals. By training the topic models to reconstruct the soft labels using the LM hidden states, our method produces higher-quality topics that are more closely aligned with the underlying thematic structure of the corpus. Experiments on three datasets show that our method achieves substantial improvements in topic coherence, purity over existing baselines. Additionally, we also introduce a retrieval-based metric, which shows that our approach significantly outperforms existing methods in identifying semantically similar documents, highlighting its effectiveness for retrieval-oriented applications.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
