{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Hz5jdSh8Kbx3uNpnFH6aQu","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\n2\t\n3\t===== PAGE 1 =====\n4\t000\n5\t001\n6\t002\n7\t003\n8\t004\n9\t005\n10\t006\n11\t007\n12\t008\n13\t009\n14\t010\n15\t011\n16\t012\n17\t013\n18\t014\n19\t015\n20\t016\n21\t017\n22\t018\n23\t019\n24\t020\n25\t021\n26\t022\n27\t023\n28\t024\n29\t025\n30\t026\n31\t027\n32\t028\n33\t029\n34\t030\n35\t031\n36\t032\n37\t033\n38\t034\n39\t035\n40\t036\n41\t037\n42\t038\n43\t039\n44\t040\n45\t041\n46\t042\n47\t043\n48\t044\n49\t045\n50\t046\n51\t047\n52\t048\n53\t049\n54\t050\n55\t051\n56\t052\n57\t053\n58\t054\n59\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded\n60\tSoft Label Distributions\n61\tAnonymous Authors1\n62\tAbstract\n63\tTraditional neural topic models are typically opti-\n64\tmized by reconstructing the document’s Bag-of-\n65\tWords (BoW) representations, overlooking con-\n66\ttextual information and struggling with data spar-\n67\tsity. In this work, we propose a novel approach\n68\tto construct semantically-grounded soft label tar-\n69\tgets using Language Models (LMs) by project-\n70\ting the next token probabilities, conditioned on\n71\ta specialized prompt, onto a pre-defined vocabu-\n72\tlary to obtain contextually enriched supervision\n73\tsignals. By training the topic models to recon-\n74\tstruct the soft labels using the LM hidden states,\n75\tour method produces higher-quality topics that\n76\tare more closely aligned with the underlying the-\n77\tmatic structure of the corpus. Experiments on\n78\tthree datasets show that our method achieves sub-\n79\tstantial improvements in topic coherence, purity\n80\tover existing baselines. Additionally, we also in-\n81\ttroduce a retrieval-based metric, which shows that\n82\tour approach significantly outperforms existing\n83\tmethods in identifying semantically similar docu-\n84\tments, highlighting its effectiveness for retrieval-\n85\toriented applications.1\n86\t1. Introduction\n87\tTopic modeling algorithms have long been a useful suite of\n88\talgorithms for uncovering the latent thematic structures in\n89\tlarge text corpora (?). Under the probabilistic topic mod-\n90\teling paradigm (?), documents are modeled as mixtures\n91\tof the underlying topics. Given a topic model, each topic\n92\tcan be represented by the most likely words or phrases to\n93\tprovide human-interpretable summaries of the entire cor-\n94\tpus, whereas the document-level thematic compositions of\n95\ttopics are useful for a wide array of applications including\n96\t1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\n97\tAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n98\t<anon.email@domain.com>.\n99\tPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\n100\ton Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n101\t1we will release the code upon publishing the paper.\n102\t0.20 0.15 0.10 0.05 0.00 0.05 0.10 0.15 0.20\n103\tTarget probability mass   ( lexical   |   semantic )\n104\tlunar\n105\tspace\n106\tastronomy\n107\tmoon\n108\torbit\n109\tsolar\n110\tgravitational\n111\tgeneral\n112\tastro\n113\tscience\n114\torbits\n115\tfield\n116\tfuel\n117\tsun\n118\tstable\n119\tpossible\n120\tproblem\n121\tBoW target (normalized)\n122\tLLM soft target (probability)\n123\tFigure 1.Comparison of reconstruction targets for the topic “lunar\n124\texploration” in the 20 Newsgroups dataset: the bag-of-words\n125\t(BoW) target (left) versus the LLM-derived soft label distribution\n126\t(right, obtained using LLaMA-3.2-1B). Words highlighted in\n127\tgreen boxes are semantically relevant but absent from the BoW\n128\ttarget, whereas words in orange boxes appear in the documents\n129\tyet are semantically distant.\n130\tinformation retrieval (??), content recommendation (??),\n131\tsummarization (??), and exploratory data analysis (??).\n132\tMost existing neural topic models (??????) infer latent\n133\ttopics by reconstructing the document’s Bag-of-Words\n134\t(BoW) representation, which captures statistical word co-\n135\toccurrences, but overlooks critical linguistic elements such\n136\tas word order, syntactic structures, and more importantly,\n137\tthe richer contextual information crucial for deep semantic\n138\tunderstanding. Particularly for short-text topic modeling,\n139\tthe sparse co-occurrence data inherent in BoW further exac-\n140\terbates data sparsity, limiting statistical signals and restrict-\n141\ting the model’s ability to produce coherent, high-quality\n142\ttopics (?).\n143\tOn the other hand, despite the advancements of Large Lan-\n144\tguage Models (LLMs) (????), they still struggle to process\n145\tlarge corpora due to the limited context length and the diffi-\n146\tculties in modeling long-range dependencies. As a result,\n147\texisting works on incorporating LLMs for topic modeling\n148\toften focused on evaluating topic quality (??) or augmenting\n149\tthe source documents to mitigate data sparsity (?). Studies\n150\tthat use LLMs for topic generations often involve complex\n151\tand costly pipelines (???), which are impractical for larger\n152\tcorpora. Additionally, prompting-based topic generation\n153\tmethods fail to provide the probabilistic distribution of top-\n154\t1\n155\t\n156\t===== PAGE 2 =====\n157\t055\n158\t056\n159\t057\n160\t058\n161\t059\n162\t060\n163\t061\n164\t062\n165\t063\n166\t064\n167\t065\n168\t066\n169\t067\n170\t068\n171\t069\n172\t070\n173\t071\n174\t072\n175\t073\n176\t074\n177\t075\n178\t076\n179\t077\n180\t078\n181\t079\n182\t080\n183\t081\n184\t082\n185\t083\n186\t084\n187\t085\n188\t086\n189\t087\n190\t088\n191\t089\n192\t090\n193\t091\n194\t092\n195\t093\n196\t094\n197\t095\n198\t096\n199\t097\n200\t098\n201\t099\n202\t100\n203\t101\n204\t102\n205\t103\n206\t104\n207\t105\n208\t106\n209\t107\n210\t108\n211\t109\n212\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n213\tics, a fundamental advantage offered by probabilistic topic\n214\tmodeling frameworks such as the Latent Dirichlet Alloca-\n215\ttion (LDA) (?).\n216\tMotivated by recent advances in small language models\n217\t(SLMs), which combine strong semantic performance with\n218\tsubstantially lower computational cost and inference la-\n219\ttency (??), we propose a novel topic modeling approach\n220\tthat integrates the capabilities of language models with the\n221\tprobabilistic foundations of neural topic models, where we\n222\tenhance the topic modeling learning objective by leveraging\n223\tSLMs to efficientlyconstruct semantically-rich recon-\n224\tstruction targets.\n225\tMore specifically, instead of relying on sparse BoW repre-\n226\tsentations, we use a simple prompting strategy (e.g., “Gen-\n227\terate a single word label that captures the underlying theme\n228\tof the document.”) that instructs the SLM to generate a\n229\tsoft label target encoding the overall document theme. This\n230\tis done by capturing the probabilities of the next comple-\n231\ttion token immediately following the prompt, and map-\n232\tping the probabilities as a soft label distribution over the\n233\tpredefined topic modeling vocabulary. Figure 1 presents\n234\ta concrete example comparing the reconstruction targets\n235\tused to train topic models (ground-truth class “lunar explo-\n236\tration”). The bag-of-words (BoW) target provides lexical\n237\tsupervision by assigning normalized probability mass only\n238\tto words that explicitly appear in the document, resulting\n239\tin sparse, surface-level signals with words that are seman-\n240\ttically distant, such as “stable” and “possible”. In contrast,\n241\tthe LLM-derived soft label distribution provides semantic\n242\tsupervision by assigning probability mass to thematically re-\n243\tlated words, including words that do not explicitly occur in\n244\tthe document such as “astro”, “space”, and “astronomy”. By\n245\ttraining the neural topic model to reconstruct these dense,\n246\tsemantically-rich soft targets, it learns to infer topics that are\n247\tmore contextually coherent and semantically meaningful.\n248\tFurthermore, we use the last hidden state representations\n249\tof the language models as the contextualized inputs for the\n250\tdocuments, which provide the necessary context for recon-\n251\tstructing the soft targets.\n252\tIn summary, our contributions are: (1) We propose a novel\n253\ttraining paradigm for neural topic modeling that uses se-\n254\tmantically grounded soft label distributions derived from\n255\ta language model as the reconstruction objective; (2) We\n256\tdemonstrate the effectiveness of our approach through ex-\n257\ttensive experiments on three datasets, achieving substantial\n258\timprovements over baseline methods in both topic quality\n259\tand assignment accuracy.\n260\t2. Related Work\n261\t2.1. Neural Topic Models\n262\tBuilt upon the generative probabilistic framework described\n263\tby Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) (?), the LDA family\n264\tof neural topic models integrate deep neural network compo-\n265\tnents through the variational autoencoder (V AE) framework\n266\t(?). This is done by using an encoder network to approximat-\n267\ting the posterior to a variational distribution q(z|x), before\n268\tthe decoder uses the sampled topic proportion θ to recon-\n269\tstruct the document’s BoW representation. For examples,\n270\t?mapped documents into continuous latent representation\n271\tby using the encoder to predict the mean and variance of\n272\ta Gaussian posterior, while ProdLDA (?) used a product-\n273\tof-experts architecture where document–topic vectors are\n274\tsampled from a logistic-normal prior (a laplace approxima-\n275\ttion to a dirichlet). Another line of work have leveraged the\n276\tsemantic information of pre-trained embeddings (??), exam-\n277\tples include the Embedding Topic Model (ETM) (?), which\n278\trepresents topics and words in a shared embedding space,\n279\twhere the document is reconstructed via the inner prod-\n280\tuct between the topic and the initialized word embedding.\n281\tBuilding on ProdLDA, CombinedTM (?) concatenated the\n282\tBoW document input with contextualized Sentence-BERT\n283\t(SBERT) embeddings (?), while ZeroshotTM (?) replaced\n284\tthe input entirely with SBERT embeddings. In our work, we\n285\talso adopt the ProdLDA architecture without modifications\n286\tby replacing the input and and reconstruction targets with\n287\tsemantically-rich representations from language models.\n288\tAlternatively, clustering-based methods (?) congregate con-\n289\ttextualized embeddings to semantically similar word or\n290\tdocument clusters. For example,?performed clustering\n291\ton word embeddings and obtain top words using weighing\n292\tand re-ranking, while BERTopic (?) performed clustering\n293\ton document embeddings and use a class-based TF-IDF\n294\tmethod to label each topical cluster. While these methods\n295\toften achieve high coherence, clustering algorithms often\n296\thave non-linear complexity and cannot efficiently scale-up\n297\tto large corpora.\n298\tFinally, several approaches have leveraged optimal transport\n299\t(OT) to regularize or align topic models in the embedding\n300\tspace (???). Recent works include ECRTM (?), which aug-\n301\tments V AE-based neural topic models with an embedding\n302\tclustering regularization term to prevent topic collapse by\n303\tseparating topic embeddings, and FASTopic (?), which em-\n304\tploys an OT-based transport plan to align documents, topics,\n305\tand words in a shared embedding space while reconstructing\n306\tthe BoW representation of documents.\n307\t2.2. LLMs for Topic Modeling\n308\tRecent studies have incorporated LLMs in topic modeling\n309\tresearch. One line of work utilized LLMs for the evaluation\n310\t2\n311\t\n312\t===== PAGE 3 =====\n313\t110\n314\t111\n315\t112\n316\t113\n317\t114\n318\t115\n319\t116\n320\t117\n321\t118\n322\t119\n323\t120\n324\t121\n325\t122\n326\t123\n327\t124\n328\t125\n329\t126\n330\t127\n331\t128\n332\t129\n333\t130\n334\t131\n335\t132\n336\t133\n337\t134\n338\t135\n339\t136\n340\t137\n341\t138\n342\t139\n343\t140\n344\t141\n345\t142\n346\t143\n347\t144\n348\t145\n349\t146\n350\t147\n351\t148\n352\t149\n353\t150\n354\t151\n355\t152\n356\t153\n357\t154\n358\t155\n359\t156\n360\t157\n361\t158\n362\t159\n363\t160\n364\t161\n365\t162\n366\t163\n367\t164\n368\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n369\tFigure 2.Overview of our proposed method. We create training target by prompting the language model to generate a label for the\n370\tdocument. In 1⃝, the next token distribution over the vocabulary subset of the instruction prompt is used as the soft targets, where in 2⃝\n371\twe use the KL Divergence as the reconstruction loss for the neural topic model. In 3⃝, the last hidden state representation of the final\n372\ttoken is used as input representation.\n373\tof topic models, such as rating the quality of the topics (??)\n374\tand their document representations (?). Another line of\n375\twork focused on improving short-text topic modeling by us-\n376\ting LLMs to expand the original text to obtain a denser BoW\n377\trepresentation (?). More recently, studies have leveraged the\n378\tcapabilities of LLMs to generate topics directly. For exam-\n379\tple,?proposed prompt-based topic extraction framework\n380\twhere topics are directly generated, refined, and summa-\n381\trized through iterative prompting. Similarly, TopicGPT (?)\n382\tfocused on topic assignment using a pipeline that prompts\n383\tthe LLM to generate topics for each document, before refin-\n384\ting the topics and assigning the most probable topic to each\n385\tdocument. While the experimental results for these works\n386\tdemonstrated improved interpretability and topic assign-\n387\tment accuracy, these methods do not form a fully probabilis-\n388\ttic framework since topics are represented by the natural\n389\tlanguage description and topic assignments are binary deci-\n390\tsions. This limits the ability to model topic uncertainty and\n391\tcapture topic distribution necessary for downstream appli-\n392\tcations. Finally,?first train a neural topic model with BoW\n393\ttargets before using a LLM to refine word distributions of\n394\talready learned topics using an optimal-transport alignment\n395\tloss. This approach is complementary to our proposal as we\n396\tfocus on obtaining a higher quality topic model using the\n397\tenhanced reconstruction target.\n398\t3. Method\n399\tFigure 2 provides an overview of our method. We describe\n400\tthe main components in the following subsections: recon-\n401\tstruction targets (subsection 3.1), the loss function and train-\n402\ting objective (subsection 3.2), and the neural topic model\n403\tinput (subsection 3.3).\n404\t3.1. Reconstruction Targets\n405\tFollowing the standard practice for topic modeling (?), we\n406\tfirst pre-process the corpus to build a fixed vocabulary set\n407\tV from the top-|V| most frequent words after tokenization\n408\tand stop-word removal. We set |V|= 2000 to align with\n409\tcommon topic-modeling practice. Our preliminary experi-\n410\tments indicate that increasing the vocabulary size to 4000\n411\tdoes not yield additional performance gains. In practice,\n412\tthis parameter can be adjusted or adapted to specific do-\n413\tmains without modifying the proposed method. For each\n414\tdocument x, we use a short prompt to instruct the language\n415\tmodel to generate a label that captures the underlying theme\n416\tof the document (e.g., “Generate a single-word label captur-\n417\ting the document theme”). Rather than decoding the labels,\n418\t3\n419\t\n420\t===== PAGE 4 =====\n421\t165\n422\t166\n423\t167\n424\t168\n425\t169\n426\t170\n427\t171\n428\t172\n429\t173\n430\t174\n431\t175\n432\t176\n433\t177\n434\t178\n435\t179\n436\t180\n437\t181\n438\t182\n439\t183\n440\t184\n441\t185\n442\t186\n443\t187\n444\t188\n445\t189\n446\t190\n447\t191\n448\t192\n449\t193\n450\t194\n451\t195\n452\t196\n453\t197\n454\t198\n455\t199\n456\t200\n457\t201\n458\t202\n459\t203\n460\t204\n461\t205\n462\t206\n463\t207\n464\t208\n465\t209\n466\t210\n467\t211\n468\t212\n469\t213\n470\t214\n471\t215\n472\t216\n473\t217\n474\t218\n475\t219\n476\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n477\twe take the next-token logits ℓLM(x) immediately follow-\n478\ting the prompt. The logits from the language model is then\n479\trestricted to our pre-processed vocab subset V , such that\n480\tℓv(x)∈R |V| before computing the temperature-scaled soft-\n481\tmax distribution as thesemantically-grounded soft targets\n482\t(Equation 1):\n483\tytarget = softmax\n484\t\u0012 ℓv(x)\n485\tτ\n486\t\u0013\n487\t.(1)\n488\tSpecifically, ytarget is a dense distribution over V and as-\n489\tsigns mass to many thematically-related words. Compared\n490\tto other LLM-based frameworks (???), our approach pro-\n491\tvides a much smaller overhead, while constraining V pre-\n492\tvents out-of-vocabulary hallucinations.\n493\t3.2. Loss Function and Training\n494\tWe adopt ProdLDA (?) as the underlying architecture. The\n495\toriginal ELBO (Equation 2) reconstructs the BoW document\n496\trepresentation while regularizing the latent topic distribution\n497\tθ to a logistic–normal prior (a Laplace approximation to the\n498\tDirichlet prior used in LDA):\n499\tLELBO =E q(θ|x)\n500\t\u0002\n501\tlogp(x|θ,β)\n502\t\u0003\n503\t−D KL\n504\t\u0000\n505\tq(θ|x)∥p(θ)\n506\t\u0001\n507\t. (2)\n508\tWe keep the same prior and latent topic structure, but re-\n509\tplace BoW targets with the semantically-rich soft labels\n510\t(subsection 3.1). We present an augmented ELBO loss\n511\twhere the topic model learns to reconstruct the language\n512\tmodel distribution via KL divergence:\n513\tLours =λD KL\n514\t\u0000\n515\tp(y|θ, β, x emb)∥y target\n516\t\u0001\n517\t−D KL\n518\t\u0000\n519\tq(z|x emb)∥p(z)\n520\t\u0001\n521\t. (3)\n522\tThe final loss is presented in Equation 3, where we use a\n523\thyperparameter λ to balance semantic reconstruction and\n524\tprior regularization.\n525\tAs illustrated in Figure 1, the LLM-derived targets cap-\n526\tture semantic relevance beyond lexical overlap. A formal\n527\tmathematical justification of the KL-based reconstruction\n528\tobjective is provided in Appendix I.\n529\t3.3. Hidden State Inputs\n530\tWe use the hidden states of the language model xemb as\n531\tthe contextualized document representation for topic model\n532\tinput. Specifically, we take the final-layer embedding of\n533\tthe last-token, which is the same representation used by the\n534\tlanguage model to compute the logits of next token ℓLM(x).\n535\t4. Experiments\n536\t4.1. Settings\n537\tMetrics.To start, we evaluate the intrinsic quality of the\n538\ttopics through theircoherenceanddiversity, which have\n539\tshown to be directly correlated with the interpretability of\n540\tthe topics (??). For topiccoherence, we use the widely\n541\tadopted Coherence Value (CV) (?) and the recently pro-\n542\tposedLLMratings (?), while for topicdiversity, we use the\n543\tInversed Rank-Biased Overlap (I-RBO) score (??). Addi-\n544\ttionally, following prior studies (???), we evaluate topical\n545\tassignment accuracyby measuring how well the most prob-\n546\table topic assignments align with the ground-truth labels\n547\tthrough thePurityscore (?). Lastly, we propose a retrieval-\n548\tbased metric to assess the effectiveness of the full topical\n549\tdistribution for finding semantically related documents by\n550\tretrieving top-N documents based on the KL-divergence of\n551\ttopic distribution, and reportPrecisionas the proportion of\n552\tretrieved documents that share the same ground-truth label\n553\tas the query.\n554\tDatasets.We train and evaluate our models on three\n555\tpublicly available text classification datasets with ground-\n556\ttruth labels: 20NewsGroup, StackOverflow (?), and Tweet-\n557\tTopic (?). For TweetTopic, we filter examples with single\n558\tlabels in order to compute thePurityscore. Note that both\n559\tStackOverflow and TweetTopic are short-text datasets that\n560\ttraditional topic models often struggle with.\n561\t4.2. Baselines\n562\tWe compare our approach against a variety of topic model-\n563\ting baselines to demonstrate the benefits of our proposed\n564\tmethod2. Specifically, we choose the following 6 mod-\n565\tels from the LDA-family:LDA(?),ProdLDA(?),Com-\n566\tbinedTM(?),ZeroshotTM(?),ETM(?).\n567\tAdditionally, we also compare with the clustering-based\n568\tmodelBERTopic(?), as well as the more recent models\n569\tECRTM(?) andFASTopic(?). Since our method also\n570\tadopts the ProdLDA architecture without modifications,\n571\tCombinedTM and ZeroshotTM are the most relevant com-\n572\tparisons for illustrating the benefits of our soft-label targets.\n573\t4.3. Hyperparameters\n574\tAs we adopt the exact ProdLDA architecture, our method\n575\tuses the identical hyperparameter settings as the baseline\n576\tmodels ProdLDA, CombinedTM, and ZeroshotTM 3. For\n577\tmodel-specific parameters, we use a temperature of τ= 3 ,\n578\tand a loss weight λ= 1e 3 to balance the reconstruction\n579\tterm with the regularization term. For efficiency, we use\n580\t2Implementation and hyperparameter details of baselines are\n581\tprovided in Appendix C.\n582\t3Hyperparameter details are provided in Appendix D.\n583\t4\n584\t\n585\t===== PAGE 5 =====\n586\t220\n587\t221\n588\t222\n589\t223\n590\t224\n591\t225\n592\t226\n593\t227\n594\t228\n595\t229\n596\t230\n597\t231\n598\t232\n599\t233\n600\t234"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"878bd310-0fd3-48f3-b6e3-a48c9104fa6d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:05:25.495Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/topic_text.txt","content":"\n\n===== PAGE 1 =====\n000\n001\n002\n003\n004\n005\n006\n007\n008\n009\n010\n011\n012\n013\n014\n015\n016\n017\n018\n019\n020\n021\n022\n023\n024\n025\n026\n027\n028\n029\n030\n031\n032\n033\n034\n035\n036\n037\n038\n039\n040\n041\n042\n043\n044\n045\n046\n047\n048\n049\n050\n051\n052\n053\n054\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded\nSoft Label Distributions\nAnonymous Authors1\nAbstract\nTraditional neural topic models are typically opti-\nmized by reconstructing the document’s Bag-of-\nWords (BoW) representations, overlooking con-\ntextual information and struggling with data spar-\nsity. In this work, we propose a novel approach\nto construct semantically-grounded soft label tar-\ngets using Language Models (LMs) by project-\ning the next token probabilities, conditioned on\na specialized prompt, onto a pre-defined vocabu-\nlary to obtain contextually enriched supervision\nsignals. By training the topic models to recon-\nstruct the soft labels using the LM hidden states,\nour method produces higher-quality topics that\nare more closely aligned with the underlying the-\nmatic structure of the corpus. Experiments on\nthree datasets show that our method achieves sub-\nstantial improvements in topic coherence, purity\nover existing baselines. Additionally, we also in-\ntroduce a retrieval-based metric, which shows that\nour approach significantly outperforms existing\nmethods in identifying semantically similar docu-\nments, highlighting its effectiveness for retrieval-\noriented applications.1\n1. Introduction\nTopic modeling algorithms have long been a useful suite of\nalgorithms for uncovering the latent thematic structures in\nlarge text corpora (?). Under the probabilistic topic mod-\neling paradigm (?), documents are modeled as mixtures\nof the underlying topics. Given a topic model, each topic\ncan be represented by the most likely words or phrases to\nprovide human-interpretable summaries of the entire cor-\npus, whereas the document-level thematic compositions of\ntopics are useful for a wide array of applications including\n1Anonymous Institution, Anonymous City, Anonymous Region,\nAnonymous Country. Correspondence to: Anonymous Author\n<anon.email@domain.com>.\nPreliminary work. Under review by the International Conference\non Machine Learning (ICML). Do not distribute.\n1we will release the code upon publishing the paper.\n0.20 0.15 0.10 0.05 0.00 0.05 0.10 0.15 0.20\nTarget probability mass   ( lexical   |   semantic )\nlunar\nspace\nastronomy\nmoon\norbit\nsolar\ngravitational\ngeneral\nastro\nscience\norbits\nfield\nfuel\nsun\nstable\npossible\nproblem\nBoW target (normalized)\nLLM soft target (probability)\nFigure 1.Comparison of reconstruction targets for the topic “lunar\nexploration” in the 20 Newsgroups dataset: the bag-of-words\n(BoW) target (left) versus the LLM-derived soft label distribution\n(right, obtained using LLaMA-3.2-1B). Words highlighted in\ngreen boxes are semantically relevant but absent from the BoW\ntarget, whereas words in orange boxes appear in the documents\nyet are semantically distant.\ninformation retrieval (??), content recommendation (??),\nsummarization (??), and exploratory data analysis (??).\nMost existing neural topic models (??????) infer latent\ntopics by reconstructing the document’s Bag-of-Words\n(BoW) representation, which captures statistical word co-\noccurrences, but overlooks critical linguistic elements such\nas word order, syntactic structures, and more importantly,\nthe richer contextual information crucial for deep semantic\nunderstanding. Particularly for short-text topic modeling,\nthe sparse co-occurrence data inherent in BoW further exac-\nerbates data sparsity, limiting statistical signals and restrict-\ning the model’s ability to produce coherent, high-quality\ntopics (?).\nOn the other hand, despite the advancements of Large Lan-\nguage Models (LLMs) (????), they still struggle to process\nlarge corpora due to the limited context length and the diffi-\nculties in modeling long-range dependencies. As a result,\nexisting works on incorporating LLMs for topic modeling\noften focused on evaluating topic quality (??) or augmenting\nthe source documents to mitigate data sparsity (?). Studies\nthat use LLMs for topic generations often involve complex\nand costly pipelines (???), which are impractical for larger\ncorpora. Additionally, prompting-based topic generation\nmethods fail to provide the probabilistic distribution of top-\n1\n\n===== PAGE 2 =====\n055\n056\n057\n058\n059\n060\n061\n062\n063\n064\n065\n066\n067\n068\n069\n070\n071\n072\n073\n074\n075\n076\n077\n078\n079\n080\n081\n082\n083\n084\n085\n086\n087\n088\n089\n090\n091\n092\n093\n094\n095\n096\n097\n098\n099\n100\n101\n102\n103\n104\n105\n106\n107\n108\n109\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nics, a fundamental advantage offered by probabilistic topic\nmodeling frameworks such as the Latent Dirichlet Alloca-\ntion (LDA) (?).\nMotivated by recent advances in small language models\n(SLMs), which combine strong semantic performance with\nsubstantially lower computational cost and inference la-\ntency (??), we propose a novel topic modeling approach\nthat integrates the capabilities of language models with the\nprobabilistic foundations of neural topic models, where we\nenhance the topic modeling learning objective by leveraging\nSLMs to efficientlyconstruct semantically-rich recon-\nstruction targets.\nMore specifically, instead of relying on sparse BoW repre-\nsentations, we use a simple prompting strategy (e.g., “Gen-\nerate a single word label that captures the underlying theme\nof the document.”) that instructs the SLM to generate a\nsoft label target encoding the overall document theme. This\nis done by capturing the probabilities of the next comple-\ntion token immediately following the prompt, and map-\nping the probabilities as a soft label distribution over the\npredefined topic modeling vocabulary. Figure 1 presents\na concrete example comparing the reconstruction targets\nused to train topic models (ground-truth class “lunar explo-\nration”). The bag-of-words (BoW) target provides lexical\nsupervision by assigning normalized probability mass only\nto words that explicitly appear in the document, resulting\nin sparse, surface-level signals with words that are seman-\ntically distant, such as “stable” and “possible”. In contrast,\nthe LLM-derived soft label distribution provides semantic\nsupervision by assigning probability mass to thematically re-\nlated words, including words that do not explicitly occur in\nthe document such as “astro”, “space”, and “astronomy”. By\ntraining the neural topic model to reconstruct these dense,\nsemantically-rich soft targets, it learns to infer topics that are\nmore contextually coherent and semantically meaningful.\nFurthermore, we use the last hidden state representations\nof the language models as the contextualized inputs for the\ndocuments, which provide the necessary context for recon-\nstructing the soft targets.\nIn summary, our contributions are: (1) We propose a novel\ntraining paradigm for neural topic modeling that uses se-\nmantically grounded soft label distributions derived from\na language model as the reconstruction objective; (2) We\ndemonstrate the effectiveness of our approach through ex-\ntensive experiments on three datasets, achieving substantial\nimprovements over baseline methods in both topic quality\nand assignment accuracy.\n2. Related Work\n2.1. Neural Topic Models\nBuilt upon the generative probabilistic framework described\nby Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) (?), the LDA family\nof neural topic models integrate deep neural network compo-\nnents through the variational autoencoder (V AE) framework\n(?). This is done by using an encoder network to approximat-\ning the posterior to a variational distribution q(z|x), before\nthe decoder uses the sampled topic proportion θ to recon-\nstruct the document’s BoW representation. For examples,\n?mapped documents into continuous latent representation\nby using the encoder to predict the mean and variance of\na Gaussian posterior, while ProdLDA (?) used a product-\nof-experts architecture where document–topic vectors are\nsampled from a logistic-normal prior (a laplace approxima-\ntion to a dirichlet). Another line of work have leveraged the\nsemantic information of pre-trained embeddings (??), exam-\nples include the Embedding Topic Model (ETM) (?), which\nrepresents topics and words in a shared embedding space,\nwhere the document is reconstructed via the inner prod-\nuct between the topic and the initialized word embedding.\nBuilding on ProdLDA, CombinedTM (?) concatenated the\nBoW document input with contextualized Sentence-BERT\n(SBERT) embeddings (?), while ZeroshotTM (?) replaced\nthe input entirely with SBERT embeddings. In our work, we\nalso adopt the ProdLDA architecture without modifications\nby replacing the input and and reconstruction targets with\nsemantically-rich representations from language models.\nAlternatively, clustering-based methods (?) congregate con-\ntextualized embeddings to semantically similar word or\ndocument clusters. For example,?performed clustering\non word embeddings and obtain top words using weighing\nand re-ranking, while BERTopic (?) performed clustering\non document embeddings and use a class-based TF-IDF\nmethod to label each topical cluster. While these methods\noften achieve high coherence, clustering algorithms often\nhave non-linear complexity and cannot efficiently scale-up\nto large corpora.\nFinally, several approaches have leveraged optimal transport\n(OT) to regularize or align topic models in the embedding\nspace (???). Recent works include ECRTM (?), which aug-\nments V AE-based neural topic models with an embedding\nclustering regularization term to prevent topic collapse by\nseparating topic embeddings, and FASTopic (?), which em-\nploys an OT-based transport plan to align documents, topics,\nand words in a shared embedding space while reconstructing\nthe BoW representation of documents.\n2.2. LLMs for Topic Modeling\nRecent studies have incorporated LLMs in topic modeling\nresearch. One line of work utilized LLMs for the evaluation\n2\n\n===== PAGE 3 =====\n110\n111\n112\n113\n114\n115\n116\n117\n118\n119\n120\n121\n122\n123\n124\n125\n126\n127\n128\n129\n130\n131\n132\n133\n134\n135\n136\n137\n138\n139\n140\n141\n142\n143\n144\n145\n146\n147\n148\n149\n150\n151\n152\n153\n154\n155\n156\n157\n158\n159\n160\n161\n162\n163\n164\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nFigure 2.Overview of our proposed method. We create training target by prompting the language model to generate a label for the\ndocument. In 1⃝, the next token distribution over the vocabulary subset of the instruction prompt is used as the soft targets, where in 2⃝\nwe use the KL Divergence as the reconstruction loss for the neural topic model. In 3⃝, the last hidden state representation of the final\ntoken is used as input representation.\nof topic models, such as rating the quality of the topics (??)\nand their document representations (?). Another line of\nwork focused on improving short-text topic modeling by us-\ning LLMs to expand the original text to obtain a denser BoW\nrepresentation (?). More recently, studies have leveraged the\ncapabilities of LLMs to generate topics directly. For exam-\nple,?proposed prompt-based topic extraction framework\nwhere topics are directly generated, refined, and summa-\nrized through iterative prompting. Similarly, TopicGPT (?)\nfocused on topic assignment using a pipeline that prompts\nthe LLM to generate topics for each document, before refin-\ning the topics and assigning the most probable topic to each\ndocument. While the experimental results for these works\ndemonstrated improved interpretability and topic assign-\nment accuracy, these methods do not form a fully probabilis-\ntic framework since topics are represented by the natural\nlanguage description and topic assignments are binary deci-\nsions. This limits the ability to model topic uncertainty and\ncapture topic distribution necessary for downstream appli-\ncations. Finally,?first train a neural topic model with BoW\ntargets before using a LLM to refine word distributions of\nalready learned topics using an optimal-transport alignment\nloss. This approach is complementary to our proposal as we\nfocus on obtaining a higher quality topic model using the\nenhanced reconstruction target.\n3. Method\nFigure 2 provides an overview of our method. We describe\nthe main components in the following subsections: recon-\nstruction targets (subsection 3.1), the loss function and train-\ning objective (subsection 3.2), and the neural topic model\ninput (subsection 3.3).\n3.1. Reconstruction Targets\nFollowing the standard practice for topic modeling (?), we\nfirst pre-process the corpus to build a fixed vocabulary set\nV from the top-|V| most frequent words after tokenization\nand stop-word removal. We set |V|= 2000 to align with\ncommon topic-modeling practice. Our preliminary experi-\nments indicate that increasing the vocabulary size to 4000\ndoes not yield additional performance gains. In practice,\nthis parameter can be adjusted or adapted to specific do-\nmains without modifying the proposed method. For each\ndocument x, we use a short prompt to instruct the language\nmodel to generate a label that captures the underlying theme\nof the document (e.g., “Generate a single-word label captur-\ning the document theme”). Rather than decoding the labels,\n3\n\n===== PAGE 4 =====\n165\n166\n167\n168\n169\n170\n171\n172\n173\n174\n175\n176\n177\n178\n179\n180\n181\n182\n183\n184\n185\n186\n187\n188\n189\n190\n191\n192\n193\n194\n195\n196\n197\n198\n199\n200\n201\n202\n203\n204\n205\n206\n207\n208\n209\n210\n211\n212\n213\n214\n215\n216\n217\n218\n219\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nwe take the next-token logits ℓLM(x) immediately follow-\ning the prompt. The logits from the language model is then\nrestricted to our pre-processed vocab subset V , such that\nℓv(x)∈R |V| before computing the temperature-scaled soft-\nmax distribution as thesemantically-grounded soft targets\n(Equation 1):\nytarget = softmax\n\u0012 ℓv(x)\nτ\n\u0013\n.(1)\nSpecifically, ytarget is a dense distribution over V and as-\nsigns mass to many thematically-related words. Compared\nto other LLM-based frameworks (???), our approach pro-\nvides a much smaller overhead, while constraining V pre-\nvents out-of-vocabulary hallucinations.\n3.2. Loss Function and Training\nWe adopt ProdLDA (?) as the underlying architecture. The\noriginal ELBO (Equation 2) reconstructs the BoW document\nrepresentation while regularizing the latent topic distribution\nθ to a logistic–normal prior (a Laplace approximation to the\nDirichlet prior used in LDA):\nLELBO =E q(θ|x)\n\u0002\nlogp(x|θ,β)\n\u0003\n−D KL\n\u0000\nq(θ|x)∥p(θ)\n\u0001\n. (2)\nWe keep the same prior and latent topic structure, but re-\nplace BoW targets with the semantically-rich soft labels\n(subsection 3.1). We present an augmented ELBO loss\nwhere the topic model learns to reconstruct the language\nmodel distribution via KL divergence:\nLours =λD KL\n\u0000\np(y|θ, β, x emb)∥y target\n\u0001\n−D KL\n\u0000\nq(z|x emb)∥p(z)\n\u0001\n. (3)\nThe final loss is presented in Equation 3, where we use a\nhyperparameter λ to balance semantic reconstruction and\nprior regularization.\nAs illustrated in Figure 1, the LLM-derived targets cap-\nture semantic relevance beyond lexical overlap. A formal\nmathematical justification of the KL-based reconstruction\nobjective is provided in Appendix I.\n3.3. Hidden State Inputs\nWe use the hidden states of the language model xemb as\nthe contextualized document representation for topic model\ninput. Specifically, we take the final-layer embedding of\nthe last-token, which is the same representation used by the\nlanguage model to compute the logits of next token ℓLM(x).\n4. Experiments\n4.1. Settings\nMetrics.To start, we evaluate the intrinsic quality of the\ntopics through theircoherenceanddiversity, which have\nshown to be directly correlated with the interpretability of\nthe topics (??). For topiccoherence, we use the widely\nadopted Coherence Value (CV) (?) and the recently pro-\nposedLLMratings (?), while for topicdiversity, we use the\nInversed Rank-Biased Overlap (I-RBO) score (??). Addi-\ntionally, following prior studies (???), we evaluate topical\nassignment accuracyby measuring how well the most prob-\nable topic assignments align with the ground-truth labels\nthrough thePurityscore (?). Lastly, we propose a retrieval-\nbased metric to assess the effectiveness of the full topical\ndistribution for finding semantically related documents by\nretrieving top-N documents based on the KL-divergence of\ntopic distribution, and reportPrecisionas the proportion of\nretrieved documents that share the same ground-truth label\nas the query.\nDatasets.We train and evaluate our models on three\npublicly available text classification datasets with ground-\ntruth labels: 20NewsGroup, StackOverflow (?), and Tweet-\nTopic (?). For TweetTopic, we filter examples with single\nlabels in order to compute thePurityscore. Note that both\nStackOverflow and TweetTopic are short-text datasets that\ntraditional topic models often struggle with.\n4.2. Baselines\nWe compare our approach against a variety of topic model-\ning baselines to demonstrate the benefits of our proposed\nmethod2. Specifically, we choose the following 6 mod-\nels from the LDA-family:LDA(?),ProdLDA(?),Com-\nbinedTM(?),ZeroshotTM(?),ETM(?).\nAdditionally, we also compare with the clustering-based\nmodelBERTopic(?), as well as the more recent models\nECRTM(?) andFASTopic(?). Since our method also\nadopts the ProdLDA architecture without modifications,\nCombinedTM and ZeroshotTM are the most relevant com-\nparisons for illustrating the benefits of our soft-label targets.\n4.3. Hyperparameters\nAs we adopt the exact ProdLDA architecture, our method\nuses the identical hyperparameter settings as the baseline\nmodels ProdLDA, CombinedTM, and ZeroshotTM 3. For\nmodel-specific parameters, we use a temperature of τ= 3 ,\nand a loss weight λ= 1e 3 to balance the reconstruction\nterm with the regularization term. For efficiency, we use\n2Implementation and hyperparameter details of baselines are\nprovided in Appendix C.\n3Hyperparameter details are provided in Appendix D.\n4\n\n===== PAGE 5 =====\n220\n221\n222\n223\n224\n225\n226\n227\n228\n229\n230\n231\n232\n233\n234","numLines":600,"startLine":1,"totalLines":1869}}}
