{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012hXL2Nmxx7CZM85md654pY","type":"tool_result","content":"600\t234\n601\t235\n602\t236\n603\t237\n604\t238\n605\t239\n606\t240\n607\t241\n608\t242\n609\t243\n610\t244\n611\t245\n612\t246\n613\t247\n614\t248\n615\t249\n616\t250\n617\t251\n618\t252\n619\t253\n620\t254\n621\t255\n622\t256\n623\t257\n624\t258\n625\t259\n626\t260\n627\t261\n628\t262\n629\t263\n630\t264\n631\t265\n632\t266\n633\t267\n634\t268\n635\t269\n636\t270\n637\t271\n638\t272\n639\t273\n640\t274\n641\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n642\t20NewsGroup TweetTopic StackOverflow\n643\tCV LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO Purity\n644\tLDA .341 2.22 .977 .301 .350 1.95 .992 .441 .354 2.00 .977 .174\n645\tProdLDA .351 2.49 .992 .356 .355 2.11 .994 .533 .352 2.62 .991 .265\n646\tCombinedTM .351 2.56 .993 .391 .360 2.36 .988 .588 .364 2.85 .986 .306\n647\tZeroshotTM .354 2.53 .994 .397 .356 2.30 .994 .573 .363 2.84 .993 .307\n648\tETM .344 2.35 .934 .360 .351 2.22 .936 .552 .348 2.29 .934 .151\n649\tBERTopic .360 2.48 .992 .352 .364 2.19 .996 .562 .374 2.63 .996 .202\n650\tECRTM .360 2.28 .999.364 .356 1.85 1.000.399 .373 1.95 1.000.062\n651\tFASTopic .358 2.59 .999.416 .276 1.96 .626 .557 .363 2.30 .687 .171\n652\tOurs\n653\tERNIE-4.5-0.3B .381 2.86.991 .520 .392 2.90.989 .781 .3972.92 .986 .737\n654\tLlama-3.2-1B.375 2.87.993 .559.383 2.90.993 .781.393 2.94 .993 .689\n655\tLlama-3.1-8B.364 2.87.993 .559.384 2.88 .993 .774.386 2.96.991 .700\n656\tTable 1.Automatic evaluation results on the top-15 words averaged over 4 numbers of topics (K = 25, 50, 75, 100), where results for each\n657\tK is averaged over 5 random seeds. For each dataset and metric, methods are compared using Welch’s independent samplest-test (?)\n658\twith α= 0.05 . The best-performing method, as well as results that are not statistically significantly different from it ( p≥0.05 ), are\n659\thighlighted in blue.\n660\tthree instruction-tuned Small Language Models (SLMs) to\n661\tcompute the soft label targets for training the topic mod-\n662\tels. Specifically, we use Llama3.1-8B-Instruct and\n663\tLlama3.2-1B-Instruct from the Llama family (?),\n664\tas well as the more recent ERNIE-4.5-0.3B (?) which\n665\thas shown to be highly capable in instruction following.\n666\tFor baselines requiring contextualized embeddings (i.e., Ze-\n667\troshotTM, CombinedTM, BERTopic, FASTopic), we use\n668\tGTE-large-en-v1.5 (?): a strong-performing dense\n669\tencoder model (0.4B) which has a similar size with our\n670\tsmallest SLM (0.3B).\n671\t4.4. Automatic Topic Evaluation\n672\tIn Table 1, we present the main experimental results on\n673\tthe 3 datasets using automatic topic evaluation metrics by\n674\taveraging over 4 number of topics (K= 25,50,75,100 )4.\n675\tFrom the results, we see that the topics from our method\n676\tachieves the bestcoherence(i.e., CV andLLMrating)\n677\tmetric while maintaining competitive topicdiversity. In ad-\n678\tdition, all three base models with our approach significantly\n679\toutperforms all baselines in thePurityscore, demonstrat-\n680\ting superior topic assignment accuracy. It’s worth noting\n681\tthat using ERNIE-4.5-0.3B as the base model signifi-\n682\tcantly outperforms ZeroshotTM, CombinedTM, BERTopic\n683\tand FASTopic which uses an encoder model of a similar\n684\tsize (i.e., GTE-large-en-v1.5) for constructing the\n685\tcontextualized document representation, demonstrating the\n686\tbenefits of our proposed strategy which allows the topic\n687\tmodel to learn high quality topics from reconstructing the\n688\tsemantically-rich soft targets.\n689\t4Complete results for all K are presented in Table 7 of Ap-\n690\tpendix E.\n691\t20News Tweet Stack\n692\tP@5 P@10 P@5 P@10 P@5 P@10\n693\tLDA .244 .231 .674 .500 .113 .109\n694\tProdLDA .346 .334 .767 .619 .242 .231\n695\tZeroShot .384 .373 .776 .647 .280 .268\n696\tCombined .366 .357 .744 .637 .260 .251\n697\tETM .312 .305 .786 .637 .135 .125\n698\tBERTopic .413 .402 .546 .519 .306 .296\n699\tECRTM .341 .329 .712 .530 .114 .101\n700\tFASTopic .421 .406 .811 .667 .189 .178\n701\tOurs\n702\tERNIE-0.3B.468 .458 .839.777 .588 .580\n703\tLlama-1B.502 .493 .857 .804 .588 .580\n704\tLlama-8B .520 .510 .843.780 .592 .582\n705\tTable 2.Retrieval evaluation. Results are averaged over all topic\n706\tcounts and random seeds. For each dataset and metric, methods are\n707\tcompared using Welch’s independent samplest-test (α= 0.05 ).\n708\tThe best result and those not statistically significantly different\n709\tfrom it are highlighted in blue.\n710\t4.5. Retrieval Evaluation\n711\tWhile thePurityscore in Table 1 measures cluster assign-\n712\tment accuracy by evaluating how consistently documents\n713\twith the same label are grouped into highest probable topics,\n714\twe propose a retrieval-based evaluation to assess the full\n715\ttopic distributions by assessing whether documents with\n716\tsimilar topic distributions also share the same ground-truth\n717\tlabels. Since the 3 datasets with ground-truth labels, we re-\n718\tport the labelPrecisionfor the top-5 (@5) and top-10 (@10)\n719\tmost similar documents according to the KL-divergence of\n720\tpredicted topic distribution in Table 2. From the results,\n721\twe see that our models significantly outperform all base-\n722\tlines by a wide margin, demonstrating the effectiveness\n723\tof our method to learning topic embeddings that closely\n724\t5\n725\t\n726\t===== PAGE 6 =====\n727\t275\n728\t276\n729\t277\n730\t278\n731\t279\n732\t280\n733\t281\n734\t282\n735\t283\n736\t284\n737\t285\n738\t286\n739\t287\n740\t288\n741\t289\n742\t290\n743\t291\n744\t292\n745\t293\n746\t294\n747\t295\n748\t296\n749\t297\n750\t298\n751\t299\n752\t300\n753\t301\n754\t302\n755\t303\n756\t304\n757\t305\n758\t306\n759\t307\n760\t308\n761\t309\n762\t310\n763\t311\n764\t312\n765\t313\n766\t314\n767\t315\n768\t316\n769\t317\n770\t318\n771\t319\n772\t320\n773\t321\n774\t322\n775\t323\n776\t324\n777\t325\n778\t326\n779\t327\n780\t328\n781\t329\n782\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n783\taligns with human-annotated labels. In particular, we notice\n784\tthe largest performance gain on the StackOverflow dataset,\n785\tshowing the superiority of our proposal to handle data spar-\n786\tsity in short-text retrieval. Lastly, our low-dimensional\n787\ttopic representations offer substantial computational and\n788\tstorage advantages over traditional methods dense embed-\n789\tdings computed from pre-trained encoder models. We hope\n790\tthis finding will inspire future works on better leveraging\n791\tSLMs to learn topics for retrieval-oriented applications.\n792\t5. Analysis\n793\t5.1. Ablation Studies\n794\tTo assess the individual contributions of each innovation\n795\tin our proposed method, we conduct ablation experiments\n796\texamining the effects of the three key components described\n797\tin section 3: the reconstruction target, the training loss, and\n798\tthe topic model input.\n799\t• (NLL) Rather than the temperature-scaled KL-\n800\tDivergence as the reconstruction loss, we instead use\n801\tthe standard negative log-likelihood from ProdLDA.\n802\t• (NLL + BoW) Using the NLL loss, we further replace\n803\tthe soft label targets with the BoW document represen-\n804\ttation as the reconstruction target.\n805\t• (Embedding) The final hidden state from language\n806\tmodel is replaced with the contextualized embeddings\n807\tfrom the similar sizedGTE-large-en-v1.5.\n808\t• (NLL + BoW + Embedding) We use\n809\tGTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings as input\n810\talong with the BoW reconstruction target and NLL\n811\tloss, this is equivalent toZeroshotTM(?).\n812\tAll the ablation study results are presented in Table 3. Our\n813\tfirst observation is that replacing the KL loss with the stan-\n814\tdard NLL results in higher CV, but lower topic diversity\n815\tand purity, representing a trade-off between the objectives.\n816\tSince we use KL with temperature scaling, a temperature\n817\tvalue τ >1 flattens the distribution, resulting in a sharper\n818\tdistribution and a higher utilization of lower-probability\n819\twords. This encourages the topics to cover capture different\n820\tparts of the vocabulary, leading to more diverse but slightly\n821\tless concentrated topics (we show the effects of tempera-\n822\tture τ in subsection 5.2). More importantly, we find that\n823\tusing the standard BoW reconstruction target (NLL + BoW)\n824\tleads to the largest drop in performance, demonstrating that\n825\tour semantically-grounded soft targets most significantly\n826\tcontributes to the topic quality and assignment accuracy.\n827\tLastly, we find that replacing the SLM hidden states with\n828\tGTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings (Embeddings) leads\n829\tto a slight drop in performance compared to original, using\n830\tthe general purpose GTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings\n831\tFigure 3.Results on 20Newsgroups with ERNIE-4.5-0.3B\n832\tfor various temperature τ values. The values are normalized to\n833\tvisualize relative trends.\n834\tto reconstruct the BoW objective (NLL + BoW + Embed-\n835\tding) can even lead to a small increase in topic coherence.\n836\tThis shows that using the SLM’s last hidden states is only\n837\tbeneficial for reconstructing our soft label targets and does\n838\tnot offer a significant advantage in the standard topic mod-\n839\teling objective.\n840\t5.2. Temperature Values\n841\tTo investigate the effects of temperature τ on the topic\n842\tqualities, we conduct experiments with various τ val-\n843\tues and visualize the results for 20NewsGroups with\n844\tERNIE-4.5-0.3B in Figure 35. Since the softmax tem-\n845\tperature τ (Equation 1) controls the sharpness of the dis-\n846\ttribution, small values (i.e., τ <2 ) cause the softmax to\n847\tapproach an argmax operation. This concentrates gradi-\n848\tents on only a few vocabulary words during reconstruction,\n849\tleading the topic model to lose semantic breadth, result-\n850\ting in learned topics are neither coherent nor diverse. In\n851\tcontrast, at higher temperatures (τ >5 ), the model learns\n852\tto reconstruct a softer distribution in which thematically\n853\tsimilar words are more likely to co-occur within the same\n854\ttopic, yielding higher coherence but reduced diversity. Ac-\n855\tcordingly, we choose τ= 3 as a balance between semantic\n856\tinformativeness and redundancy.\n857\t5.3. Instruction Prompt Sensitivity\n858\tTo quantify whether topic model performance varies with\n859\tthe instruction prompt, we conduct experiments on the\n860\t20NewsGroup dataset with ERNIE-4.5-0.3B for K=\n861\t50 using 5 different prompts6. For each prompt, we train 5\n862\trandom seeds and apply the two-way Analysis of Variance\n863\t(ANOV A) test (?) to compare variance between prompt\n864\tchoice and random seed. For coherence metrics, the es-\n865\t5We find a similar trend on the two other datasets, which is\n866\tvisualized in Figure 4 of Appendix F.\n867\t6Details regarding the 5 prompt variants are described in Ap-\n868\tpendix G.\n869\t6\n870\t\n871\t===== PAGE 7 =====\n872\t330\n873\t331\n874\t332\n875\t333\n876\t334\n877\t335\n878\t336\n879\t337\n880\t338\n881\t339\n882\t340\n883\t341\n884\t342\n885\t343\n886\t344\n887\t345\n888\t346\n889\t347\n890\t348\n891\t349\n892\t350\n893\t351\n894\t352\n895\t353\n896\t354\n897\t355\n898\t356\n899\t357\n900\t358\n901\t359\n902\t360\n903\t361\n904\t362\n905\t363\n906\t364\n907\t365\n908\t366\n909\t367\n910\t368\n911\t369\n912\t370\n913\t371\n914\t372\n915\t373\n916\t374\n917\t375\n918\t376\n919\t377\n920\t378\n921\t379\n922\t380\n923\t381\n924\t382\n925\t383\n926\t384\n927\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n928\t20NewsGroup TweetTopic StackOverflow\n929\tAblationC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO Purity\n930\tERNIE-4.5-0.3B-PT\n931\tOriginal .381 2.86 .991 .520 .392 2.90 .989 .781 .397 2.91 .986 .737\n932\tNLL +.024 -.09 -.023 -.046 +.014 -.13 -.024 -.019 +.022 -.08 -.011 -.021\n933\tNLL + BoW -.042 -.38 +.000 -.088 -.034 -.73 +.005 -.157 -.028 -.15 +.007 -.363\n934\tEmbeddings +.000 -.01 -.003 -.007 +.005-.02 -.004 -.060 -.001 -.01 -.007 -.224\n935\tNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.027 -.33 +.003 -.123 -.035 -.59 +.004 -.208 -.034 -.07 +.007 -.430\n936\tLlama-3.2-1B-Instruct\n937\tOriginal .377 2.89 .991 .564 .387 2.92 .992 .784 .395 2.95 .991 .698\n938\tNLL +.021 -.15 -.023 -.061 +.010 -.06 -.018 -.018 +.004 -.11 -.012 -.049\n939\tNLL + BoW -.036 -.42 +.000 -.121 -.033 -.78 +.004 -.175 -.032 -.19 +.002 -.363\n940\tEmbeddings +.005-.00 -.002 -.016 +.003-.01 -.003 -.061 +.008 -.04 -.006 -.230\n941\tNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.023 -.36 +.003 -.167 -.030 -.62 +.002 -.211 -.032 -.11 +.002 -.391\n942\tLlama-3.1-8B-Instruct\n943\tOriginal .364 2.87 .993 .559 .384 2.88 .993 .774 .386 2.96 .991 .700\n944\tNLL +.032 -.11 -.020 -.059 +.006 +.03 -.035 -.005 +.011 -.04 -.012 +.001\n945\tNLL + BoW -.026 -.40 -.001 -.107 -.026 -.76 +.002 -.169 -.023 -.22 +.001 -.354\n946\tEmbeddings +.002 -.02 -.003 -.007 -.001 -.02 -.003 -.058 -.002 -.014 -.006 -.218\n947\tNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.010 -.34 +.001 -.162 -.027 -.58 +.001 -.201 -.023 -.12 +.001 -.393\n948\tTable 3.Ablation experiment results with our three models ERNIE-4.5-0.3B, Llama-3.2-1B, and Llama-3.1-8B averaged\n949\tover K= 25,50,75,100 , with five random seeds per K. Ablation code: NLL – negative log-likelihood as reconstruction loss instead of\n950\tKL-Divergence; BoW – BoW targets instead of soft label target; Embeddings – contextualized embeddings fromGTE-large-en-v1.5\n951\tinstead of hidden states from language model. Results that are statistical significantly better and worse than the Original (p <0.05 ) are\n952\thighlighted in greenand red, respectively.\n953\ttimated main effects of prompt and seed are statistically\n954\tindistinguishable for CV (Fprompt = 1 , Fseed = 1 ) and\n955\tLLMratings ( Fprompt = 0.72 , Fseed = 0.37 ), indicat-\n956\ting that changing the prompt wording has no more effect\n957\tthan simply re-running with a different random seed. For\n958\ttopic diversity andPurity, prompt choice explains approxi-\n959\tmately 10 times more variance than seed choice forI-RBO\n960\t(Fprompt = 42.4, Fseed = 4.4) and 5 times more forPurity\n961\t(Fprompt = 9.8 , Fseed = 2.1 ). This is likely due to the\n962\tinstruction steering the language model towards a particular\n963\tfacets, therefore changing the breadth of topic coverage.\n964\t5.4. Qualitative Results\n965\tWe provide some examples from the 20NewsGroup dataset\n966\tto qualitatively analyze the topics. This is done by randomly\n967\tselecting a seed from topic models trained with K= 50 ,\n968\tand finding the topic containing the largest number of doc-\n969\tuments from the ground-truth label. This is equivalent to\n970\tfinding the topic with the highest inverse Purity score. From\n971\tTable 4, we see that the topics from our methods consis-\n972\ttently contain words that capture the core terminology of\n973\tthe ground-truth class (e.g., “atheism” for classalt.atheism),\n974\twhere all of the top-15 words are semantically consistent\n975\tand captures thematic depth beyond surface-level word co-\n976\toccurrence. For example, in the categoryalt.atheism, topics\n977\tfrom our three base models emphasize discourse-level con-\n978\tcepts (“argument”, “rational”, “logic”, “debate”) rather than\n979\tmerely religious keywords, reflecting the argumentative and\n980\tepistemological nature of the dataset. In contrast, ETM\n981\tyields generic terms such as “know”, “think”, and “prob-\n982\tlem”, which are only weakly related to this theme. Mean-\n983\twhile, BERTopic and FASTTopic blur the focus on atheism\n984\tby mixing it with tangentially related concepts like “homo-\n985\tsexuality” and religious “sin”—terms that often co-occur\n986\tin religious debates but are not central to the topic itself.\n987\tThese findings demonstrate that LLM-based topic modeling\n988\tcaptures deeper semantic structure beyond simple lexical\n989\tco-occurrence.\n990\t6. Conclusion\n991\tWe propose a novel technique for enhancing neural topic\n992\tmodeling that uses the NLU capabilities of the language\n993\tmodels to generate a soft label distribution as the recon-\n994\tstruction target for neural topic models. This is done by\n995\tprojecting the temperature-scaled softmax distribution of\n996\tthe next token prediction immediately following the prompt\n997\tonto our defined vocab, before training the neural topic\n998\tmodel using the final hidden state as input. In extensive ex-\n999\tperiments on three datasets, we achieve SOTA performance\n1000\tin terms of topic coherence and purity, while maintaining\n1001\thigh diversity. We also introduce a retrieval-based eval-\n1002\tuation metric where we showed that the predicted topic\n1003\tdistribution from our method achieved the highest precision\n1004\t7\n1005\t\n1006\t===== PAGE 8 =====\n1007\t385\n1008\t386\n1009\t387\n1010\t388\n1011\t389\n1012\t390\n1013\t391\n1014\t392\n1015\t393\n1016\t394\n1017\t395\n1018\t396\n1019\t397\n1020\t398\n1021\t399\n1022\t400\n1023\t401\n1024\t402\n1025\t403\n1026\t404\n1027\t405\n1028\t406\n1029\t407\n1030\t408\n1031\t409\n1032\t410\n1033\t411\n1034\t412\n1035\t413\n1036\t414\n1037\t415\n1038\t416\n1039\t417\n1040\t418\n1041\t419\n1042\t420\n1043\t421\n1044\t422\n1045\t423\n1046\t424\n1047\t425\n1048\t426\n1049\t427\n1050\t428\n1051\t429\n1052\t430\n1053\t431\n1054\t432\n1055\t433\n1056\t434\n1057\t435\n1058\t436\n1059\t437\n1060\t438\n1061\t439\n1062\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n1063\tMethod Top-15 Topic Words (alt.atheism)\n1064\tLDApeople, point, think, case, claim, moral, way, fact, different, example, true, human, statement, word, believe\n1065\tProdLDAtheory, rational, scientific, science, evidence, universe, physical, reliable, existence, observations, belief, explanation, gods, atheism, faith\n1066\tZeroShotTMscience, scientific, theory, rational, evidence, existence, observations, exists, scientists, atheism, atheist, reliable, belief, gods, exist\n1067\tCombinedTMobjective, moral, morality, absolute, god, believe, definition, belief, values, exist, truth, exists, religion, nature, atheist\n1068\tETMlike, know, think, problem, good, need, want, read, seen, heard, sure, tell, better, different, find\n1069\tBERTopichomosexual, sin, homosexuality, people, believe, faith, life, sex, love, church, men, gay, man, moral, true\n1070\tECRTMatheists, atheism, atheist, beliefs, god, belief, existence, gods, rational, faith, conclusion, morality, argument, truth, statements\n1071\tFASTopicreligion, religious, homosexual, moral, beliefs, sex, homosexuality, atheists, atheism, sexual, gay, morality, atheist, religions, homosexuals\n1072\tOurs\n1073\tERNIE-0.3Batheism, atheists, atheist, belief, god, beliefs, claim, believe, claiming, arguments, deny, argue, doubt, false, argument\n1074\tLlama-1Batheism, religion, religious, atheist, atheists, belief, faith, arguments, religions, beliefs, science, god, debate, creation, argument\n1075\tLlama-8Bobjective, argument, morality, object, rational, existence, science, logic, debate, arguments, definition, fall, scientific, absolute, moral\n1076\tMethod Top-15 Topic Words (talk.politics.mics)\n1077\tLDArights, government, state, people, law, police, anti, right, political, million, human, war, federal, states, civil\n1078\tProdLDAtax, station, bill, committee, state, states, national, insurance, taxes, option, property, license, civil, budget, private\n1079\tZeroShotTMinsurance, private, economy, funds, jobs, spending, health, taxes, tax, people, money, projects, work, education, doctors\n1080\tCombinedTMgay, sexual, men, sex, homosexuals, homosexual, male, ethnic, acts, population, international, society, genocide, civil, straight\n1081\tETMlike, know, think, problem, good, need, want, read, seen, heard, sure, tell, better, different, find\n1082\tBERTopicgun, people, said, guns, fire, killed, right, firearms, genocide, went, weapons, started, population, children, crime\n1083\tECRTMtax, economy, taxes, budget, administration, bill, aid, yesterday, government, summer, projects, funds, private, federal, talked\n1084\tFASTopicgovernment, state, public, rights, law, right, people, support, groups, political, decision, said, today, situation, group\n1085\tOurs\n1086\tERNIE-0.3Beconomic, economy, tax, policy, government, money, federal, policies, business, taxes, governments, public, political, market, opportunity\n1087\tLlama-1Beconomic, economy, tax, money, policy, taxes, cost, policies, budget, federal, political, bill, costs, pay, increase\n1088\tLlama-8Beconomic, cost, economy, political, money, policy, taxes, tax, foreign, government, costs, commercial, budget, national, lack\n1089\tTable 4.Top-15 words of most aligned topics from baselines and our methods ( K= 50 ), with ground-truth class “alt.atheism” (top) and\n1090\t“talk.politics.misc” (bottom) from the 20NewsGroup dataset. The highlighted words are overly vague (e.g., “think”, “way”, “problem”,\n1091\twhich provide little topic-specific signal) or tangentially related (e.g., “homosexuality”, “gay”), reflecting broader religious or general\n1092\tpolitical discussions rather than the core target themes.\n1093\tfor retrieving semantically similar documents according to\n1094\tthe ground-truth label.\n1095\tIn future work, we will experiment with different prompt-\n1096\ting strategies such as few-shot learning (?) and chain-of-\n1097\tthought (CoT) prompting (?) to more effectively generate\n1098\tthe soft label targets. Lastly, we will also explore the ef-\n1099\tfectiveness of using the inferred topic for retrieval-based"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"bac24080-0907-4cd6-97ce-f692c42c1060","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:05:30.211Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/topic_text.txt","content":"234\n235\n236\n237\n238\n239\n240\n241\n242\n243\n244\n245\n246\n247\n248\n249\n250\n251\n252\n253\n254\n255\n256\n257\n258\n259\n260\n261\n262\n263\n264\n265\n266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n20NewsGroup TweetTopic StackOverflow\nCV LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO Purity\nLDA .341 2.22 .977 .301 .350 1.95 .992 .441 .354 2.00 .977 .174\nProdLDA .351 2.49 .992 .356 .355 2.11 .994 .533 .352 2.62 .991 .265\nCombinedTM .351 2.56 .993 .391 .360 2.36 .988 .588 .364 2.85 .986 .306\nZeroshotTM .354 2.53 .994 .397 .356 2.30 .994 .573 .363 2.84 .993 .307\nETM .344 2.35 .934 .360 .351 2.22 .936 .552 .348 2.29 .934 .151\nBERTopic .360 2.48 .992 .352 .364 2.19 .996 .562 .374 2.63 .996 .202\nECRTM .360 2.28 .999.364 .356 1.85 1.000.399 .373 1.95 1.000.062\nFASTopic .358 2.59 .999.416 .276 1.96 .626 .557 .363 2.30 .687 .171\nOurs\nERNIE-4.5-0.3B .381 2.86.991 .520 .392 2.90.989 .781 .3972.92 .986 .737\nLlama-3.2-1B.375 2.87.993 .559.383 2.90.993 .781.393 2.94 .993 .689\nLlama-3.1-8B.364 2.87.993 .559.384 2.88 .993 .774.386 2.96.991 .700\nTable 1.Automatic evaluation results on the top-15 words averaged over 4 numbers of topics (K = 25, 50, 75, 100), where results for each\nK is averaged over 5 random seeds. For each dataset and metric, methods are compared using Welch’s independent samplest-test (?)\nwith α= 0.05 . The best-performing method, as well as results that are not statistically significantly different from it ( p≥0.05 ), are\nhighlighted in blue.\nthree instruction-tuned Small Language Models (SLMs) to\ncompute the soft label targets for training the topic mod-\nels. Specifically, we use Llama3.1-8B-Instruct and\nLlama3.2-1B-Instruct from the Llama family (?),\nas well as the more recent ERNIE-4.5-0.3B (?) which\nhas shown to be highly capable in instruction following.\nFor baselines requiring contextualized embeddings (i.e., Ze-\nroshotTM, CombinedTM, BERTopic, FASTopic), we use\nGTE-large-en-v1.5 (?): a strong-performing dense\nencoder model (0.4B) which has a similar size with our\nsmallest SLM (0.3B).\n4.4. Automatic Topic Evaluation\nIn Table 1, we present the main experimental results on\nthe 3 datasets using automatic topic evaluation metrics by\naveraging over 4 number of topics (K= 25,50,75,100 )4.\nFrom the results, we see that the topics from our method\nachieves the bestcoherence(i.e., CV andLLMrating)\nmetric while maintaining competitive topicdiversity. In ad-\ndition, all three base models with our approach significantly\noutperforms all baselines in thePurityscore, demonstrat-\ning superior topic assignment accuracy. It’s worth noting\nthat using ERNIE-4.5-0.3B as the base model signifi-\ncantly outperforms ZeroshotTM, CombinedTM, BERTopic\nand FASTopic which uses an encoder model of a similar\nsize (i.e., GTE-large-en-v1.5) for constructing the\ncontextualized document representation, demonstrating the\nbenefits of our proposed strategy which allows the topic\nmodel to learn high quality topics from reconstructing the\nsemantically-rich soft targets.\n4Complete results for all K are presented in Table 7 of Ap-\npendix E.\n20News Tweet Stack\nP@5 P@10 P@5 P@10 P@5 P@10\nLDA .244 .231 .674 .500 .113 .109\nProdLDA .346 .334 .767 .619 .242 .231\nZeroShot .384 .373 .776 .647 .280 .268\nCombined .366 .357 .744 .637 .260 .251\nETM .312 .305 .786 .637 .135 .125\nBERTopic .413 .402 .546 .519 .306 .296\nECRTM .341 .329 .712 .530 .114 .101\nFASTopic .421 .406 .811 .667 .189 .178\nOurs\nERNIE-0.3B.468 .458 .839.777 .588 .580\nLlama-1B.502 .493 .857 .804 .588 .580\nLlama-8B .520 .510 .843.780 .592 .582\nTable 2.Retrieval evaluation. Results are averaged over all topic\ncounts and random seeds. For each dataset and metric, methods are\ncompared using Welch’s independent samplest-test (α= 0.05 ).\nThe best result and those not statistically significantly different\nfrom it are highlighted in blue.\n4.5. Retrieval Evaluation\nWhile thePurityscore in Table 1 measures cluster assign-\nment accuracy by evaluating how consistently documents\nwith the same label are grouped into highest probable topics,\nwe propose a retrieval-based evaluation to assess the full\ntopic distributions by assessing whether documents with\nsimilar topic distributions also share the same ground-truth\nlabels. Since the 3 datasets with ground-truth labels, we re-\nport the labelPrecisionfor the top-5 (@5) and top-10 (@10)\nmost similar documents according to the KL-divergence of\npredicted topic distribution in Table 2. From the results,\nwe see that our models significantly outperform all base-\nlines by a wide margin, demonstrating the effectiveness\nof our method to learning topic embeddings that closely\n5\n\n===== PAGE 6 =====\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\naligns with human-annotated labels. In particular, we notice\nthe largest performance gain on the StackOverflow dataset,\nshowing the superiority of our proposal to handle data spar-\nsity in short-text retrieval. Lastly, our low-dimensional\ntopic representations offer substantial computational and\nstorage advantages over traditional methods dense embed-\ndings computed from pre-trained encoder models. We hope\nthis finding will inspire future works on better leveraging\nSLMs to learn topics for retrieval-oriented applications.\n5. Analysis\n5.1. Ablation Studies\nTo assess the individual contributions of each innovation\nin our proposed method, we conduct ablation experiments\nexamining the effects of the three key components described\nin section 3: the reconstruction target, the training loss, and\nthe topic model input.\n• (NLL) Rather than the temperature-scaled KL-\nDivergence as the reconstruction loss, we instead use\nthe standard negative log-likelihood from ProdLDA.\n• (NLL + BoW) Using the NLL loss, we further replace\nthe soft label targets with the BoW document represen-\ntation as the reconstruction target.\n• (Embedding) The final hidden state from language\nmodel is replaced with the contextualized embeddings\nfrom the similar sizedGTE-large-en-v1.5.\n• (NLL + BoW + Embedding) We use\nGTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings as input\nalong with the BoW reconstruction target and NLL\nloss, this is equivalent toZeroshotTM(?).\nAll the ablation study results are presented in Table 3. Our\nfirst observation is that replacing the KL loss with the stan-\ndard NLL results in higher CV, but lower topic diversity\nand purity, representing a trade-off between the objectives.\nSince we use KL with temperature scaling, a temperature\nvalue τ >1 flattens the distribution, resulting in a sharper\ndistribution and a higher utilization of lower-probability\nwords. This encourages the topics to cover capture different\nparts of the vocabulary, leading to more diverse but slightly\nless concentrated topics (we show the effects of tempera-\nture τ in subsection 5.2). More importantly, we find that\nusing the standard BoW reconstruction target (NLL + BoW)\nleads to the largest drop in performance, demonstrating that\nour semantically-grounded soft targets most significantly\ncontributes to the topic quality and assignment accuracy.\nLastly, we find that replacing the SLM hidden states with\nGTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings (Embeddings) leads\nto a slight drop in performance compared to original, using\nthe general purpose GTE-large-en-v1.5 embeddings\nFigure 3.Results on 20Newsgroups with ERNIE-4.5-0.3B\nfor various temperature τ values. The values are normalized to\nvisualize relative trends.\nto reconstruct the BoW objective (NLL + BoW + Embed-\nding) can even lead to a small increase in topic coherence.\nThis shows that using the SLM’s last hidden states is only\nbeneficial for reconstructing our soft label targets and does\nnot offer a significant advantage in the standard topic mod-\neling objective.\n5.2. Temperature Values\nTo investigate the effects of temperature τ on the topic\nqualities, we conduct experiments with various τ val-\nues and visualize the results for 20NewsGroups with\nERNIE-4.5-0.3B in Figure 35. Since the softmax tem-\nperature τ (Equation 1) controls the sharpness of the dis-\ntribution, small values (i.e., τ <2 ) cause the softmax to\napproach an argmax operation. This concentrates gradi-\nents on only a few vocabulary words during reconstruction,\nleading the topic model to lose semantic breadth, result-\ning in learned topics are neither coherent nor diverse. In\ncontrast, at higher temperatures (τ >5 ), the model learns\nto reconstruct a softer distribution in which thematically\nsimilar words are more likely to co-occur within the same\ntopic, yielding higher coherence but reduced diversity. Ac-\ncordingly, we choose τ= 3 as a balance between semantic\ninformativeness and redundancy.\n5.3. Instruction Prompt Sensitivity\nTo quantify whether topic model performance varies with\nthe instruction prompt, we conduct experiments on the\n20NewsGroup dataset with ERNIE-4.5-0.3B for K=\n50 using 5 different prompts6. For each prompt, we train 5\nrandom seeds and apply the two-way Analysis of Variance\n(ANOV A) test (?) to compare variance between prompt\nchoice and random seed. For coherence metrics, the es-\n5We find a similar trend on the two other datasets, which is\nvisualized in Figure 4 of Appendix F.\n6Details regarding the 5 prompt variants are described in Ap-\npendix G.\n6\n\n===== PAGE 7 =====\n330\n331\n332\n333\n334\n335\n336\n337\n338\n339\n340\n341\n342\n343\n344\n345\n346\n347\n348\n349\n350\n351\n352\n353\n354\n355\n356\n357\n358\n359\n360\n361\n362\n363\n364\n365\n366\n367\n368\n369\n370\n371\n372\n373\n374\n375\n376\n377\n378\n379\n380\n381\n382\n383\n384\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n20NewsGroup TweetTopic StackOverflow\nAblationC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO PurityC V LLM I-RBO Purity\nERNIE-4.5-0.3B-PT\nOriginal .381 2.86 .991 .520 .392 2.90 .989 .781 .397 2.91 .986 .737\nNLL +.024 -.09 -.023 -.046 +.014 -.13 -.024 -.019 +.022 -.08 -.011 -.021\nNLL + BoW -.042 -.38 +.000 -.088 -.034 -.73 +.005 -.157 -.028 -.15 +.007 -.363\nEmbeddings +.000 -.01 -.003 -.007 +.005-.02 -.004 -.060 -.001 -.01 -.007 -.224\nNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.027 -.33 +.003 -.123 -.035 -.59 +.004 -.208 -.034 -.07 +.007 -.430\nLlama-3.2-1B-Instruct\nOriginal .377 2.89 .991 .564 .387 2.92 .992 .784 .395 2.95 .991 .698\nNLL +.021 -.15 -.023 -.061 +.010 -.06 -.018 -.018 +.004 -.11 -.012 -.049\nNLL + BoW -.036 -.42 +.000 -.121 -.033 -.78 +.004 -.175 -.032 -.19 +.002 -.363\nEmbeddings +.005-.00 -.002 -.016 +.003-.01 -.003 -.061 +.008 -.04 -.006 -.230\nNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.023 -.36 +.003 -.167 -.030 -.62 +.002 -.211 -.032 -.11 +.002 -.391\nLlama-3.1-8B-Instruct\nOriginal .364 2.87 .993 .559 .384 2.88 .993 .774 .386 2.96 .991 .700\nNLL +.032 -.11 -.020 -.059 +.006 +.03 -.035 -.005 +.011 -.04 -.012 +.001\nNLL + BoW -.026 -.40 -.001 -.107 -.026 -.76 +.002 -.169 -.023 -.22 +.001 -.354\nEmbeddings +.002 -.02 -.003 -.007 -.001 -.02 -.003 -.058 -.002 -.014 -.006 -.218\nNLL + BoW + Embeddings-.010 -.34 +.001 -.162 -.027 -.58 +.001 -.201 -.023 -.12 +.001 -.393\nTable 3.Ablation experiment results with our three models ERNIE-4.5-0.3B, Llama-3.2-1B, and Llama-3.1-8B averaged\nover K= 25,50,75,100 , with five random seeds per K. Ablation code: NLL – negative log-likelihood as reconstruction loss instead of\nKL-Divergence; BoW – BoW targets instead of soft label target; Embeddings – contextualized embeddings fromGTE-large-en-v1.5\ninstead of hidden states from language model. Results that are statistical significantly better and worse than the Original (p <0.05 ) are\nhighlighted in greenand red, respectively.\ntimated main effects of prompt and seed are statistically\nindistinguishable for CV (Fprompt = 1 , Fseed = 1 ) and\nLLMratings ( Fprompt = 0.72 , Fseed = 0.37 ), indicat-\ning that changing the prompt wording has no more effect\nthan simply re-running with a different random seed. For\ntopic diversity andPurity, prompt choice explains approxi-\nmately 10 times more variance than seed choice forI-RBO\n(Fprompt = 42.4, Fseed = 4.4) and 5 times more forPurity\n(Fprompt = 9.8 , Fseed = 2.1 ). This is likely due to the\ninstruction steering the language model towards a particular\nfacets, therefore changing the breadth of topic coverage.\n5.4. Qualitative Results\nWe provide some examples from the 20NewsGroup dataset\nto qualitatively analyze the topics. This is done by randomly\nselecting a seed from topic models trained with K= 50 ,\nand finding the topic containing the largest number of doc-\numents from the ground-truth label. This is equivalent to\nfinding the topic with the highest inverse Purity score. From\nTable 4, we see that the topics from our methods consis-\ntently contain words that capture the core terminology of\nthe ground-truth class (e.g., “atheism” for classalt.atheism),\nwhere all of the top-15 words are semantically consistent\nand captures thematic depth beyond surface-level word co-\noccurrence. For example, in the categoryalt.atheism, topics\nfrom our three base models emphasize discourse-level con-\ncepts (“argument”, “rational”, “logic”, “debate”) rather than\nmerely religious keywords, reflecting the argumentative and\nepistemological nature of the dataset. In contrast, ETM\nyields generic terms such as “know”, “think”, and “prob-\nlem”, which are only weakly related to this theme. Mean-\nwhile, BERTopic and FASTTopic blur the focus on atheism\nby mixing it with tangentially related concepts like “homo-\nsexuality” and religious “sin”—terms that often co-occur\nin religious debates but are not central to the topic itself.\nThese findings demonstrate that LLM-based topic modeling\ncaptures deeper semantic structure beyond simple lexical\nco-occurrence.\n6. Conclusion\nWe propose a novel technique for enhancing neural topic\nmodeling that uses the NLU capabilities of the language\nmodels to generate a soft label distribution as the recon-\nstruction target for neural topic models. This is done by\nprojecting the temperature-scaled softmax distribution of\nthe next token prediction immediately following the prompt\nonto our defined vocab, before training the neural topic\nmodel using the final hidden state as input. In extensive ex-\nperiments on three datasets, we achieve SOTA performance\nin terms of topic coherence and purity, while maintaining\nhigh diversity. We also introduce a retrieval-based eval-\nuation metric where we showed that the predicted topic\ndistribution from our method achieved the highest precision\n7\n\n===== PAGE 8 =====\n385\n386\n387\n388\n389\n390\n391\n392\n393\n394\n395\n396\n397\n398\n399\n400\n401\n402\n403\n404\n405\n406\n407\n408\n409\n410\n411\n412\n413\n414\n415\n416\n417\n418\n419\n420\n421\n422\n423\n424\n425\n426\n427\n428\n429\n430\n431\n432\n433\n434\n435\n436\n437\n438\n439\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nMethod Top-15 Topic Words (alt.atheism)\nLDApeople, point, think, case, claim, moral, way, fact, different, example, true, human, statement, word, believe\nProdLDAtheory, rational, scientific, science, evidence, universe, physical, reliable, existence, observations, belief, explanation, gods, atheism, faith\nZeroShotTMscience, scientific, theory, rational, evidence, existence, observations, exists, scientists, atheism, atheist, reliable, belief, gods, exist\nCombinedTMobjective, moral, morality, absolute, god, believe, definition, belief, values, exist, truth, exists, religion, nature, atheist\nETMlike, know, think, problem, good, need, want, read, seen, heard, sure, tell, better, different, find\nBERTopichomosexual, sin, homosexuality, people, believe, faith, life, sex, love, church, men, gay, man, moral, true\nECRTMatheists, atheism, atheist, beliefs, god, belief, existence, gods, rational, faith, conclusion, morality, argument, truth, statements\nFASTopicreligion, religious, homosexual, moral, beliefs, sex, homosexuality, atheists, atheism, sexual, gay, morality, atheist, religions, homosexuals\nOurs\nERNIE-0.3Batheism, atheists, atheist, belief, god, beliefs, claim, believe, claiming, arguments, deny, argue, doubt, false, argument\nLlama-1Batheism, religion, religious, atheist, atheists, belief, faith, arguments, religions, beliefs, science, god, debate, creation, argument\nLlama-8Bobjective, argument, morality, object, rational, existence, science, logic, debate, arguments, definition, fall, scientific, absolute, moral\nMethod Top-15 Topic Words (talk.politics.mics)\nLDArights, government, state, people, law, police, anti, right, political, million, human, war, federal, states, civil\nProdLDAtax, station, bill, committee, state, states, national, insurance, taxes, option, property, license, civil, budget, private\nZeroShotTMinsurance, private, economy, funds, jobs, spending, health, taxes, tax, people, money, projects, work, education, doctors\nCombinedTMgay, sexual, men, sex, homosexuals, homosexual, male, ethnic, acts, population, international, society, genocide, civil, straight\nETMlike, know, think, problem, good, need, want, read, seen, heard, sure, tell, better, different, find\nBERTopicgun, people, said, guns, fire, killed, right, firearms, genocide, went, weapons, started, population, children, crime\nECRTMtax, economy, taxes, budget, administration, bill, aid, yesterday, government, summer, projects, funds, private, federal, talked\nFASTopicgovernment, state, public, rights, law, right, people, support, groups, political, decision, said, today, situation, group\nOurs\nERNIE-0.3Beconomic, economy, tax, policy, government, money, federal, policies, business, taxes, governments, public, political, market, opportunity\nLlama-1Beconomic, economy, tax, money, policy, taxes, cost, policies, budget, federal, political, bill, costs, pay, increase\nLlama-8Beconomic, cost, economy, political, money, policy, taxes, tax, foreign, government, costs, commercial, budget, national, lack\nTable 4.Top-15 words of most aligned topics from baselines and our methods ( K= 50 ), with ground-truth class “alt.atheism” (top) and\n“talk.politics.misc” (bottom) from the 20NewsGroup dataset. The highlighted words are overly vague (e.g., “think”, “way”, “problem”,\nwhich provide little topic-specific signal) or tangentially related (e.g., “homosexuality”, “gay”), reflecting broader religious or general\npolitical discussions rather than the core target themes.\nfor retrieving semantically similar documents according to\nthe ground-truth label.\nIn future work, we will experiment with different prompt-\ning strategies such as few-shot learning (?) and chain-of-\nthought (CoT) prompting (?) to more effectively generate\nthe soft label targets. Lastly, we will also explore the ef-\nfectiveness of using the inferred topic for retrieval-based","numLines":500,"startLine":600,"totalLines":1869}}}
