{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018oDux68k9M1qRJjKaUzfW7","type":"tool_result","content":"1100\tdownstream applications, which has shown to be a promis-\n1101\ting direction based on the results from our experiments.\n1102\tImpact Statement\n1103\tPotential RisksThis research presents potential risks re-\n1104\tlated to the use of real-world text data, which may contain\n1105\tharmful biases or inaccuracies. However, all experiments\n1106\twere conducted in controlled settings, where further risks\n1107\tcan be mitigated by filtering the vocabulary words during\n1108\tpre-processing.\n1109\tAI AssistanceWe used AI coding assistants for setting\n1110\tup the initial code base as well as debugging. We used\n1111\tcommercial AI assistants for grammar checking and style\n1112\trefinements at the paragraph level. All scientific contribu-\n1113\ttions, including experimental design, analysis, and interpre-\n1114\ttation were conducted by the authors to preserve academic\n1115\tintegrity.\n1116\t8\n1117\t\n1118\t===== PAGE 9 =====\n1119\t440\n1120\t441\n1121\t442\n1122\t443\n1123\t444\n1124\t445\n1125\t446\n1126\t447\n1127\t448\n1128\t449\n1129\t450\n1130\t451\n1131\t452\n1132\t453\n1133\t454\n1134\t455\n1135\t456\n1136\t457\n1137\t458\n1138\t459\n1139\t460\n1140\t461\n1141\t462\n1142\t463\n1143\t464\n1144\t465\n1145\t466\n1146\t467\n1147\t468\n1148\t469\n1149\t470\n1150\t471\n1151\t472\n1152\t473\n1153\t474\n1154\t475\n1155\t476\n1156\t477\n1157\t478\n1158\t479\n1159\t480\n1160\t481\n1161\t482\n1162\t483\n1163\t484\n1164\t485\n1165\t486\n1166\t487\n1167\t488\n1168\t489\n1169\t490\n1170\t491\n1171\t492\n1172\t493\n1173\t494\n1174\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n1175\tA. Datasets\n1176\tDataset Domain # Docs # Labels Avg Words\n1177\t20NewsGroup Email 18,846 20 182\n1178\tTweetTopic Tweet 21,996 19 28\n1179\tStackOverflow Forum 20,000 20 9\n1180\tTable 5.Statistics of the three datasets used in our experiments.\n1181\tTable 5 displays the statistics for the three text datasets\n1182\tused in our experiments (section 4). The three datasets,\n1183\t20NewsGroup7, TweetTopic8 (?),and StackOverflow9 (?),\n1184\tall consists of ground-truth labels, which can be used for\n1185\tevaluating purity and retrieval scores.\n1186\tB. Evaluation Metrics\n1187\tWe describe the implementation details for the four metrics\n1188\tused to evaluate the topic models in Table 1. ForCV, which\n1189\thas been shown to outperform earlier metrics such as NPMI,\n1190\tUCI and UMass (????), we follow the approach in prior\n1191\tworks (???) by using the widely-used large Wikipedia arti-\n1192\tcle collection as the external reference corpus for computing\n1193\tco-occurrence through the palmetto10 toolkit. ForLLM\n1194\tratings, we use the gpt-4o model through the OpenAI\n1195\tAPI11, where adapted the system prompt from?is shown\n1196\tin Table 6. To evaluate topicdiversity, rather than using\n1197\tthe standard Topic Diversity (TD) metric (?), which sim-\n1198\tply computes the overlaps between topic word sets, we use\n1199\tthe ranked-awareI-RBO(?) which disproportionately pe-\n1200\tnalizes overlap among top-ranked words that dominate the\n1201\thuman interpretation of topics. Lastly, for topic assignment\n1202\taccuracy, we use the harmonicPurityscore (?), which mea-\n1203\tsures the agreement between predicted topic assignments\n1204\tand ground-truth labels by computing the best-matching\n1205\ttopic using the F1 score and aggregating these scores with\n1206\tclass-size weighting.\n1207\tC. Baselines\n1208\tFor topic models from the LDA family (LDA, ProdLDA,\n1209\tCombinedTM, ZeroshotTM, ETM), we use the implementa-\n1210\ttion provided by the OCTIS library (?) and default settings\n1211\tfor each model.\n1212\tLDAWe use the Gensim implementation (?) provided\n1213\tby OCTIS, which used online learning (?) to iteratively\n1214\tapproximate the latent posterior parameters with an EM\n1215\t7http://qwone.com/˜jason/20Newsgroups\n1216\t8https://huggingface.co/datasets/cardiffn\n1217\tlp/tweet_topic_multi\n1218\t9https://github.com/jacoxu/StackOverflow\n1219\t10https://github.com/dice-group/Palmetto\n1220\t11https://openai.com/api\n1221\talgorithm. Using the default settings, the inference process\n1222\tutilized a batch size of 2000 documents, with a single pass\n1223\tthrough the corpus during training. Model convergence is\n1224\tcontrolled by a gamma threshold of0.001, which determines\n1225\twhen topic distribution estimation has sufficiently stabilized.\n1226\tThe online learning rate parameters with a decay factor of\n1227\t0.5 to balance the influence of previously observed data\n1228\tagainst new observations, and an offset of 1.0 to regulate\n1229\tearly-iteration learning dynamics.\n1230\tProdLDAWe use the implementation provided by OC-\n1231\tTIS which employs a variational autoencoder architecture\n1232\twith a product of experts formulation and with the BoW rep-\n1233\tresentation of the document as both input and reconstruction\n1234\ttarget. The encoder network consists of2 hidden layers with\n1235\t200 neurons each, using softplus (?) activation functions\n1236\twith a dropout rate of 0.2 during training. During training,\n1237\twe use the Adam optimizer (?) with a learning rate of 2e−3\n1238\tfor 100 epochs and a batch size of 64. We also optimize\n1239\tthe parameters of the prior distribution, and compute the\n1240\taverage of10samples during inference.\n1241\tZeroshotTM/CombinedTMWe use the identical archi-\n1242\ttecture and hyperparameters as ProdLDA by replacing the\n1243\tinput of with concatenation of of contextualized SBERT\n1244\tembeddings (?) for ZeroshotTM and the concatenation with\n1245\tBoW vectors for CombinedTM.\n1246\tETMThe embedding topic model defines each topic\n1247\tas a point in the word embedding space. We initialize\n1248\tthe model word2vec embeddings (?) pre-trained on a\n1249\tpart of the Google News dataset with a hidden size of\n1250\t300 (word2vec-google-news-300) downloaded us-\n1251\ting API provided by the Gensim library. The model uses\n1252\tan encoder maps BoW representations to topic distributions\n1253\tthrough a two-layer network with hidden size 800, using\n1254\tthe ReLU activation function and dropout rate of 0.5. The\n1255\tmodel was trained with the standard ELBO loss where the\n1256\tdefault settings uses the Adam optimizer (?) with a learning\n1257\trate of 5e−3, where the initialized word2vec embeddings\n1258\tare not further fine-turned. The BoW input of the document\n1259\tare normalized to account for varying document lengths\n1260\twhere a weight decay of 1.2e−6 was applied for additional\n1261\tregularization. Finally, early stopping was implemented\n1262\twhere the training stops when no improvement occurs for 5\n1263\tepochs.\n1264\tBERTopicBased on the official implementation 12 pro-\n1265\tvided by?, where document are represented by contextu-\n1266\talized embeddings. The documents embeddings are then\n1267\tprojected to a lower-dimension space of 5 using UMAP\n1268\t(?), before clustering the projected embeddings using HDB-\n1269\t12https://github.com/MaartenGr/BERTopic\n1270\t9\n1271\t\n1272\t===== PAGE 10 =====\n1273\t495\n1274\t496\n1275\t497\n1276\t498\n1277\t499\n1278\t500\n1279\t501\n1280\t502\n1281\t503\n1282\t504\n1283\t505\n1284\t506\n1285\t507\n1286\t508\n1287\t509\n1288\t510\n1289\t511\n1290\t512\n1291\t513\n1292\t514\n1293\t515\n1294\t516\n1295\t517\n1296\t518\n1297\t519\n1298\t520\n1299\t521\n1300\t522\n1301\t523\n1302\t524\n1303\t525\n1304\t526\n1305\t527\n1306\t528\n1307\t529\n1308\t530\n1309\t531\n1310\t532\n1311\t533\n1312\t534\n1313\t535\n1314\t536\n1315\t537\n1316\t538\n1317\t539\n1318\t540\n1319\t541\n1320\t542\n1321\t543\n1322\t544\n1323\t545\n1324\t546\n1325\t547\n1326\t548\n1327\t549\n1328\tImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\n1329\tLLM Rating System Prompt\n1330\tYou are a helpful assistant evaluating the top words of a topic model output for a given topic. Please rate how related the\n1331\tfollowing words are to each other on a scale from 1 to 3 (“1” = not very related,“2” = moderately related, “3” = very\n1332\trelated).\n1333\tReply with a single number, indicating the overall appropriateness of the topic.\n1334\tTable 6.The system prompt for computing theLLMratings where we usegpt-4oto score the topics on a scale of 1 to 3.\n1335\tSCAN (?) based on euclidean distance. To generate topic\n1336\trepresentations, a class-based TF-IDF (c-TF-IDF) approach\n1337\twas used by treating each topic as a document by concate-\n1338\tnating all documents within that topic, and using the TF-IDF\n1339\tscores as topic-word matrix. Since HDBSCAN naturally\n1340\tidentifies data points that don’t fit well into any cluster, we\n1341\tdefine them as an “outlier” topic, and do not include it in\n1342\tthe final evaluations.\n1343\tECRTMWe adopt the original implementation 13, which\n1344\tincorporates an embedding clustering regularization to im-\n1345\tprove topic coherence by encouraging word embeddings to\n1346\tcluster around topic embeddings. The V AE encoder con-\n1347\tsists of 2 hidden layers with 200 neurons each, using the\n1348\tsoftplus activation function. Topics and words are repre-\n1349\tsented as embeddings in a shared 200-dimensional space,\n1350\twhere the topic-word matrix β is computed via the softmax\n1351\tof negative pairwise Euclidean distances with a temper-\n1352\tature parameter of 0.2. We initialize word embeddings\n1353\tusing GloVe embeddings (?) pre-trained on Wikipedia\n1354\tand Gigaword ( glove-wiki-gigaword-200) down-\n1355\tloaded via the Gensim library. The embedding clustering\n1356\tregularization (ECR) is formulated as an optimal transport\n1357\tproblem and solved using Sinkhorn’s algorithm (??) with\n1358\tα= 20.0 and a maximum of 1000 iterations, weighted by\n1359\tλECR = 100.0 in the final loss. The model is trained for 200\n1360\tepochs with the Adam optimizer (?) using a learning rate of\n1361\t0.002and a batch size of64.\n1362\tFASTopicWe use the TopMost library (?), which adopts\n1363\tthe original implementation14 by encoding the documents\n1364\twith contextualized embeddings and regularizing the se-\n1365\tmantic relations as optimal transport (OT) plans. This is\n1366\tdone by adding OT regularization terms to the standard\n1367\tBoW reconstruction loss. Specifically, we use the default\n1368\thyperparameters by setting αDT = 3.0 for document-topic\n1369\tregularization, αT W = 2.0 for topic-word regularization.\n1370\tThe model is trained for200epochs with a learning rate of\n1371\t0.002.\n1372\t13https://github.com/BobXWu/ECRTM\n1373\t14https://github.com/BobXWu/FASTopic\n1374\tD. Hyperparameter Settings\n1375\tFollowing the identical settings ofProdLDA,Com-\n1376\tbinedTM, andZeroshotTM, we use a two-layer MLP\n1377\twith a hidden size of 200 and softplus (?) activation as\n1378\tthe encoder q(θ|z, x). During training, we use the Adam\n1379\toptimizer (?) with a learning rate of 2e−3 and cosine\n1380\tdecay. We train our model on all datasets for a total of for\n1381\t100 epochs using mini-batch of 64. Our implementation is\n1382\tprovided in the supplementary material. For CombinedTM,\n1383\tZeroshotTM, BERTopic, and FASTopic, which requires con-\n1384\ttextualized embeddings for document representation, we use\n1385\tGTE-large-en-v1.515, which is a 0.4B model with a\n1386\thidden size of 1024, that achieved state-of-the-art scores on\n1387\tthe MTEB benchmark (?).\n1388\tE. Complete Experiment Results\n1389\tWe display the complete set of results for each number of\n1390\ttopic K= 25,50,75,100 in Table 7. From the table we\n1391\tsee that our models consistently achieve the best overall\n1392\tCV,LLMrating, andPurityscore across all K, while\n1393\tmaintaining high diversity as the number of topics increases.\n1394\tF. Temperature Analysis\n1395\tThe experiment results for various temperature τ values on\n1396\tthe three datasets 20NewsGroups, TweetTopic, and Stack-\n1397\tOverflow are visualized using line charts in Figure 4. From\n1398\tthe normalized values of the four metrics, we see similar\n1399\ttrends in all three datasets. In particular,I-RBOandPurity"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fcfa8e5-62e8-4a85-9bb3-c2789fe0a8f4","uuid":"516d2449-07ba-48e5-a792-9c36db8f5ed6","timestamp":"2026-04-28T04:06:14.393Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/topic_text.txt","content":"downstream applications, which has shown to be a promis-\ning direction based on the results from our experiments.\nImpact Statement\nPotential RisksThis research presents potential risks re-\nlated to the use of real-world text data, which may contain\nharmful biases or inaccuracies. However, all experiments\nwere conducted in controlled settings, where further risks\ncan be mitigated by filtering the vocabulary words during\npre-processing.\nAI AssistanceWe used AI coding assistants for setting\nup the initial code base as well as debugging. We used\ncommercial AI assistants for grammar checking and style\nrefinements at the paragraph level. All scientific contribu-\ntions, including experimental design, analysis, and interpre-\ntation were conducted by the authors to preserve academic\nintegrity.\n8\n\n===== PAGE 9 =====\n440\n441\n442\n443\n444\n445\n446\n447\n448\n449\n450\n451\n452\n453\n454\n455\n456\n457\n458\n459\n460\n461\n462\n463\n464\n465\n466\n467\n468\n469\n470\n471\n472\n473\n474\n475\n476\n477\n478\n479\n480\n481\n482\n483\n484\n485\n486\n487\n488\n489\n490\n491\n492\n493\n494\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nA. Datasets\nDataset Domain # Docs # Labels Avg Words\n20NewsGroup Email 18,846 20 182\nTweetTopic Tweet 21,996 19 28\nStackOverflow Forum 20,000 20 9\nTable 5.Statistics of the three datasets used in our experiments.\nTable 5 displays the statistics for the three text datasets\nused in our experiments (section 4). The three datasets,\n20NewsGroup7, TweetTopic8 (?),and StackOverflow9 (?),\nall consists of ground-truth labels, which can be used for\nevaluating purity and retrieval scores.\nB. Evaluation Metrics\nWe describe the implementation details for the four metrics\nused to evaluate the topic models in Table 1. ForCV, which\nhas been shown to outperform earlier metrics such as NPMI,\nUCI and UMass (????), we follow the approach in prior\nworks (???) by using the widely-used large Wikipedia arti-\ncle collection as the external reference corpus for computing\nco-occurrence through the palmetto10 toolkit. ForLLM\nratings, we use the gpt-4o model through the OpenAI\nAPI11, where adapted the system prompt from?is shown\nin Table 6. To evaluate topicdiversity, rather than using\nthe standard Topic Diversity (TD) metric (?), which sim-\nply computes the overlaps between topic word sets, we use\nthe ranked-awareI-RBO(?) which disproportionately pe-\nnalizes overlap among top-ranked words that dominate the\nhuman interpretation of topics. Lastly, for topic assignment\naccuracy, we use the harmonicPurityscore (?), which mea-\nsures the agreement between predicted topic assignments\nand ground-truth labels by computing the best-matching\ntopic using the F1 score and aggregating these scores with\nclass-size weighting.\nC. Baselines\nFor topic models from the LDA family (LDA, ProdLDA,\nCombinedTM, ZeroshotTM, ETM), we use the implementa-\ntion provided by the OCTIS library (?) and default settings\nfor each model.\nLDAWe use the Gensim implementation (?) provided\nby OCTIS, which used online learning (?) to iteratively\napproximate the latent posterior parameters with an EM\n7http://qwone.com/˜jason/20Newsgroups\n8https://huggingface.co/datasets/cardiffn\nlp/tweet_topic_multi\n9https://github.com/jacoxu/StackOverflow\n10https://github.com/dice-group/Palmetto\n11https://openai.com/api\nalgorithm. Using the default settings, the inference process\nutilized a batch size of 2000 documents, with a single pass\nthrough the corpus during training. Model convergence is\ncontrolled by a gamma threshold of0.001, which determines\nwhen topic distribution estimation has sufficiently stabilized.\nThe online learning rate parameters with a decay factor of\n0.5 to balance the influence of previously observed data\nagainst new observations, and an offset of 1.0 to regulate\nearly-iteration learning dynamics.\nProdLDAWe use the implementation provided by OC-\nTIS which employs a variational autoencoder architecture\nwith a product of experts formulation and with the BoW rep-\nresentation of the document as both input and reconstruction\ntarget. The encoder network consists of2 hidden layers with\n200 neurons each, using softplus (?) activation functions\nwith a dropout rate of 0.2 during training. During training,\nwe use the Adam optimizer (?) with a learning rate of 2e−3\nfor 100 epochs and a batch size of 64. We also optimize\nthe parameters of the prior distribution, and compute the\naverage of10samples during inference.\nZeroshotTM/CombinedTMWe use the identical archi-\ntecture and hyperparameters as ProdLDA by replacing the\ninput of with concatenation of of contextualized SBERT\nembeddings (?) for ZeroshotTM and the concatenation with\nBoW vectors for CombinedTM.\nETMThe embedding topic model defines each topic\nas a point in the word embedding space. We initialize\nthe model word2vec embeddings (?) pre-trained on a\npart of the Google News dataset with a hidden size of\n300 (word2vec-google-news-300) downloaded us-\ning API provided by the Gensim library. The model uses\nan encoder maps BoW representations to topic distributions\nthrough a two-layer network with hidden size 800, using\nthe ReLU activation function and dropout rate of 0.5. The\nmodel was trained with the standard ELBO loss where the\ndefault settings uses the Adam optimizer (?) with a learning\nrate of 5e−3, where the initialized word2vec embeddings\nare not further fine-turned. The BoW input of the document\nare normalized to account for varying document lengths\nwhere a weight decay of 1.2e−6 was applied for additional\nregularization. Finally, early stopping was implemented\nwhere the training stops when no improvement occurs for 5\nepochs.\nBERTopicBased on the official implementation 12 pro-\nvided by?, where document are represented by contextu-\nalized embeddings. The documents embeddings are then\nprojected to a lower-dimension space of 5 using UMAP\n(?), before clustering the projected embeddings using HDB-\n12https://github.com/MaartenGr/BERTopic\n9\n\n===== PAGE 10 =====\n495\n496\n497\n498\n499\n500\n501\n502\n503\n504\n505\n506\n507\n508\n509\n510\n511\n512\n513\n514\n515\n516\n517\n518\n519\n520\n521\n522\n523\n524\n525\n526\n527\n528\n529\n530\n531\n532\n533\n534\n535\n536\n537\n538\n539\n540\n541\n542\n543\n544\n545\n546\n547\n548\n549\nImproving Neural Topic Modeling with Semantically-Grounded Soft Label Distributions\nLLM Rating System Prompt\nYou are a helpful assistant evaluating the top words of a topic model output for a given topic. Please rate how related the\nfollowing words are to each other on a scale from 1 to 3 (“1” = not very related,“2” = moderately related, “3” = very\nrelated).\nReply with a single number, indicating the overall appropriateness of the topic.\nTable 6.The system prompt for computing theLLMratings where we usegpt-4oto score the topics on a scale of 1 to 3.\nSCAN (?) based on euclidean distance. To generate topic\nrepresentations, a class-based TF-IDF (c-TF-IDF) approach\nwas used by treating each topic as a document by concate-\nnating all documents within that topic, and using the TF-IDF\nscores as topic-word matrix. Since HDBSCAN naturally\nidentifies data points that don’t fit well into any cluster, we\ndefine them as an “outlier” topic, and do not include it in\nthe final evaluations.\nECRTMWe adopt the original implementation 13, which\nincorporates an embedding clustering regularization to im-\nprove topic coherence by encouraging word embeddings to\ncluster around topic embeddings. The V AE encoder con-\nsists of 2 hidden layers with 200 neurons each, using the\nsoftplus activation function. Topics and words are repre-\nsented as embeddings in a shared 200-dimensional space,\nwhere the topic-word matrix β is computed via the softmax\nof negative pairwise Euclidean distances with a temper-\nature parameter of 0.2. We initialize word embeddings\nusing GloVe embeddings (?) pre-trained on Wikipedia\nand Gigaword ( glove-wiki-gigaword-200) down-\nloaded via the Gensim library. The embedding clustering\nregularization (ECR) is formulated as an optimal transport\nproblem and solved using Sinkhorn’s algorithm (??) with\nα= 20.0 and a maximum of 1000 iterations, weighted by\nλECR = 100.0 in the final loss. The model is trained for 200\nepochs with the Adam optimizer (?) using a learning rate of\n0.002and a batch size of64.\nFASTopicWe use the TopMost library (?), which adopts\nthe original implementation14 by encoding the documents\nwith contextualized embeddings and regularizing the se-\nmantic relations as optimal transport (OT) plans. This is\ndone by adding OT regularization terms to the standard\nBoW reconstruction loss. Specifically, we use the default\nhyperparameters by setting αDT = 3.0 for document-topic\nregularization, αT W = 2.0 for topic-word regularization.\nThe model is trained for200epochs with a learning rate of\n0.002.\n13https://github.com/BobXWu/ECRTM\n14https://github.com/BobXWu/FASTopic\nD. Hyperparameter Settings\nFollowing the identical settings ofProdLDA,Com-\nbinedTM, andZeroshotTM, we use a two-layer MLP\nwith a hidden size of 200 and softplus (?) activation as\nthe encoder q(θ|z, x). During training, we use the Adam\noptimizer (?) with a learning rate of 2e−3 and cosine\ndecay. We train our model on all datasets for a total of for\n100 epochs using mini-batch of 64. Our implementation is\nprovided in the supplementary material. For CombinedTM,\nZeroshotTM, BERTopic, and FASTopic, which requires con-\ntextualized embeddings for document representation, we use\nGTE-large-en-v1.515, which is a 0.4B model with a\nhidden size of 1024, that achieved state-of-the-art scores on\nthe MTEB benchmark (?).\nE. Complete Experiment Results\nWe display the complete set of results for each number of\ntopic K= 25,50,75,100 in Table 7. From the table we\nsee that our models consistently achieve the best overall\nCV,LLMrating, andPurityscore across all K, while\nmaintaining high diversity as the number of topics increases.\nF. Temperature Analysis\nThe experiment results for various temperature τ values on\nthe three datasets 20NewsGroups, TweetTopic, and Stack-\nOverflow are visualized using line charts in Figure 4. From\nthe normalized values of the four metrics, we see similar\ntrends in all three datasets. In particular,I-RBOandPurity","numLines":300,"startLine":1100,"totalLines":1869}}}
